<HEAD>
<TITLE>Bosnian Opposition Parties Cooperate</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">
<h1>Tilting at Windmills</h1>

<strong><em>by Zlatko Dukic</em></strong><P>

<h2>Oslobodenje-Svijet, Sarajevo-Ljubljana, Bosnia-Hercegovina, 4/11/96</h2>

During the last weekend in March, personalities from the parties and
associations and organizations from almost all parts of the territory
of Bosnia-Hercegovina, met in Tuzla and not for the first time; this 
association has been known for a while under the name of the Democratic 
Alternative.  Specifically, we have in mind the representatives of the
both Social Democratic parties in Bosnia-Hercegovina, SDP and UBSD, then
the representatives of the opposition parties from the Serb entity and
the representatives of various associations similar to Circle 99 from
Sarajevo and Civic Forum from Tuzla.  The topic for discussion  at the meeting
was "Democratic and free elections, the precondition for the lasting and stable
peace."  On its second day the conference tackled "the role of media
in the reintegration of the country."<P>

Summarizing the achievements, the leader of the Tuzla Civic Forum, Vehid Sehic,
claimed that the people from the Democratic Alternative had realized a long
time ago that the Dayton Agreement hadn't brought real peace but only a 
ceasefire.  For this we should "thank" the ruling oligarchies which,
exactly because they accepted under the pressure a difficult and hurtful
compromise, have practically lost the legitimacy of the peace builders.  This
can be easily demonstrated on the example of the Federation: the ruling
duet is the greatest opposition to each other; therefore it would be the
most democratic and honorable if they would give up their places to those 
who can, know how and are willing to make democratic steps without
"spicing them up" with fervent nationalism.<P>

<strong>Democracy or a stable</strong>: On this occasion, in one place it 
was possible to find several opposition leaders, for example Bogic Bogicevic,
Vlatko Dolocek, Neda Milicevic, Sejfudin Tokic, Boro Bjelobrk, from the
federal side and Miodrag Zivanovic, Milorad Dodik or Brano Miljus from the
Serb entity side; this demonstrates that the aforementioned conclusion is not
simply a private nor exceptional opinion.  Especially after some illustrations about the transformation of the
public opinion, frequently illustrated with lively and exotic details, which demonstrate
that the psychological framework which has ruled over the last four years is slowly 
changing.  In connection with that, especially captivating was the story told
by Zivanovic about how at the session of the Banja Luka city council a fat 
representative used "facts" in order to explain why it was necessary to change
the name of Rudi Cajavec street: "I've heard that he was a pilot, that he did
a heroic deed of some kind...  However, we must find out with what intentions
and why he did that heroic deed; until we find out, no street in Banja Luka 
should be named after him!"<P>

If there are still those, more-or-less cautious, who have an inclination to ask
why the opposition (or "opposition") hadn't appeared in Pale before the last
year of the war, in order to "shine" in the middle of 1995 when a meeting
with our opposition representatives took place in Perugia [in Italy] (since
then a number of similar meetings has taken place), we should respond that
after all, talk is cheap and doesn't hurt.  Even those who were cautious
at the start have found out that this was true.  Simply they didn't not trust
the leaders of the opposition from the other side - Dodik and Zivanovic.  Now
after Dayton, the situation seems different.  And leaves increasingly less
reason for doubt.<P>

<strong>Secret dinners</strong>: This was especially obvious in Tuzla, although
at times the participants allowed themselves generalizations such as "all three sides
are equally to blame for this war."  Disagreement with this statement does not
influence the overall impression and the united position of the Democratic
Alternative of Bosnia-Hercegovina, which, in the common statement at the end
of the Tuzla session, repeated its demand to the international community to
pressure the ruling structures in order to force them to spend more time 
worrying about the implementation of the Dayton Agreement and less on mutual
(mis)trust and suspicions.  Another point: this should be done through the
existing institutions and not in the top party leadership, "secret dinners"
and secret planning meetings.<P>

One need not be extremely well informed and clever to realize that if the IFOR troops depart from our territory after only one year, a spark of new
war could immediately turn into a new conflagration. Sejfudin Tokic is already
blaming ruling national oligarchies for that: they hadn't asked the people
for anything and haven't so far done anything against the "federal mafia"
which is still influential, powerful and rich.<P>

The leader of Banja Luka liberals, Miodrag Zivanovic, goes even further, wondering
whether and who will (if the Dayton Agreement was put together for the state
of Bosnia-Hercegovina) block the crucial influence and open meddling into Bosnian
affairs by "the fascist regime of Franjo Tudman and the police-party regime
of Slobodan Milosevic, both of whom support the political and ethnic division
of Bosnia-Hercegovina?"<P>

That ruling teams do not care a lot about their peoples, although we should stay
away from drawing false parallels, was known before the meeting in Tuzla.  
Nevertheless, that knowledge now presupposes even more open and concrete
discussion of the facts which demonstrate that the rulers care about their own 
interests and not the interests of the others.  That is the reality.  As is
reality, according to Milorad Dodik, that Serbs are afraid of SDA and Alija 
Izetbegovic, as well as the Bosniaks are afraid of Krajisnik, Koljevic and 
the company.  Mutual fear feeds the rulers; on the balance of fear they maintain
their systems and further their interests.<P>

<strong>Tuzla model</strong>: "We must offer the Tuzla model to the whole of
Bosnia-Hercegovina, since that model is the affirmation of civic principles,
tolerance, coexistence, understanding and cooperation, which are the only
perspective of Bosnia-Hercegovina."<P>

These Dodik's words at this time give an impression of a persistent, but slow,
approach towards an utopian goal.  Maybe that's not true.  Nevertheless, from 
the current perspective, the Tuzla meeting hasn't received good reviews from
the passionate apologists of the national oligarchies; furthermore, even the 
decisions and the agreements from Tuzla were sharply criticized, including 
the decision to hold the next meeting of the Democratic Alternative, if
possible and safe, in Banja Luka.<P>

It is possible to get an idea of how realistic and achievable these goals are
from the commentary of Jasminko Hodzic, the young editor-in-chief of the news
program on the Television of Tuzla-Podrinje canton, which is the official
media outlet and pet of the canton government and the canton SDA organization.
The editor's commentary, after all, boiled down to these "democratic" and 
"antifascist" words:<P>

"We will achieve democracy in Bosnia-Hercegovina when we do the same thing 
Americans did a long time ago: when we put our reds into reservations!"<P>

<hr>

Translated on 6/5/96<P>
