<TITLE> Another Country/ Dossier Pakracka Poljana, Part  1 </TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
used without permission, for ``fair use" only
<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1> Another President</h1><p>

 
<h2><i> Picaskvandal <br>  Feral Tribune, 5/19/95, Split, Croatia</i></h2><p>

email:FERAL_TRIBUNE@ZAMIR-ZG.ztn.apc.org<p>

<hr>

Speaking on behalf of the president of the republic, his envoy emphasized that there were three leading ideas shared by all antifascists: "Never forget, never forgive and never again allow the repetition of the horrors which occured in the fascist camps."  He said these words at the commemoration of the 50 years since the prisoner break out from the Ustashe concentration camp in Jasenovac, organized  last Thursday by the Association of Antifascist Veterans.  After extending the president's greetings to the audience, his envoy emphasized that the commemorations like that one and the common effort in building of the united Europe urge new generations to never forget the fascist crimes.  Together with the envoy of the president of the republic, a high ranking officer also attended the ceremony as a military representative.<P>

The name of the president who devoted so much attention to the commemoration of the Ustashe victims held in Zagreb is <strong>Bill Clinton</strong>, and the republic whose leader he is is the United States of America;  the envoy who sharply denounced fascism is the American ambassador [in Croatia],<strong>Peter Galbraight</strong>, and the officer was the American military attache in Croatia.<p>

The president of the Association of Antifascist Veterans <strong>Ivan Fumic</strong>,
Jewish community president, Dr. <strong>Ognjen Kraus</strong> and the president of the Union of Roma <strong>Vid Bogdan</strong> also spoke at the commemoration.  Dr. <strong>Franjo Tudman</strong> didn't send his envoy; the Croatian Army neither.  Croatian president is certainly preoccupied with the preparations for the trip to London to the celebration of the 50th anniversary of victory against fascism.  <em>Glede & unatoc</em>, that is only a sign of his consistency.  Yes to antifascism, but only abroad.  At home, it is another story... <P>
 
</FONT>
<hr>

Translated on 1/25/96

<hr>

<A HREF="/info/students/marko/croind.html"><IMG SRC="/home/marko/public_html/pictures/home.gif" HIGHT=40 WIDTH=80 ALT="HOME"></a><P>

