<HEAD>
<TITLE>Croatian Demonstrations in Mostar</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>Croatian Exercise in Grassroots Democracy</h1>
 
<strong><em>by Alija Behram</em></strong><P>

<h2>Oslobodenje-Svijet, Sarajevo-Ljubljana, Bosnia-Hercegovina, 2/15 1996</h2>

During the night between Wednesday and Thursday, Mostar inhabitants hardly had any sleep; many of them got up with blood shot eyes.  The city greeted the dawn covered with snow, but its whiteness couldn't hide a sad and ugly blemish on the face of Mostar.  This unfortunate place reached again, as many times before during the year and a half of the cold war situation on the shores of the Neretva, the verge of violence and aggression.  Only a little was needed to restart the flames of war.<P>

The wave of violence started when a group of militant supporters of the tired "Herceg-Bosna" listened in Hotel for retired persons (where the EU city administration headquarters is located) to Koschnick's decisions concerning his arbitration on the territorial-legal project for the city of Mostar.  Mladen Misic and a handful of his bojovnici [soldiers] were dominant among the extremists gathered next to a bar.  Koschnick was holding a press conference for about 100 journalists in the hotel lobby and had to ask several times for the intervention of the European police in order to reduce the noise coming from the bar.<P>

When Koschnik revealed that both himself and Europe (including all mentors of the Muslim-Croatian federation, especially the USA) demand unification of the city, with single police force and the right of return for all expelled persons, the group of extremists walked out of the hotel.  It wasn't hard to predict the further scenario for the Croatian exercise in grassroots democracy.  As soon as the journalists hurried outside to send the first reports out to the world, the seat of the EU city administration was surrounded by a group of several hundred demonstrators.  "Mostar is a Croatian city!"..."This is Croatia"..."Koschnick go home".. are only a few of the "messages" that came from the unhappy crowd.<P>

<strong>Humiliating Experience</strong>: The demonstrators were soon joined by a new group, mostly women and children, gathered in the middle of a school lesson.  All this happened at the time when Koschnick decided to attend the opening of the restored Hercegovina Archive building, on the eastern shore of the Neretva.  A crowd of extremists surrounded Koschnick's car (which has bulletproof windows).  "That was a humiliating, terrifying experience,"  Koschnick would state later to the foreign correspondents who had a difficult task to witness and tape a wave of protest which was slowly turning into destruction and aggression.  A ZDF journalist found himself facing a Croatian extremist who threatened to shoot the journalist unless he stopped taping the events.  Fortunately he shot twice into the air.  All this time, Koschnick quietly sat at the rear seat of the car which was pushed by several muscular youngsters who wanted to flip the car over and throw the European administrator into mud.  They were swearing at him, demanding that he resign, calling him a terrorist and a Muslim conspirator...  Several men were jumping on the roof of the car while others were beating the windows and the trunk with wooden clubs.<P>

<strong>Mass Escape</strong>: The crowd broke into the hotel lobby and then "captured" the second floor on which the European administration offices were located.  Dumbfounded and terrified officials ran from one office to another searching for a way out.  A 70-years-old Bosniak, a high official in the European administration, almost didn't manage to get out through the side corridors; he jumped out to the hotel garden and sneaked over to the eastern shore. A few officials managed to escape together with him.  Journalists from several Bosnian media managed to escape at the last moment.  They were picked up by a European administration car which fortunately managed to get away from the angry crowd.  The crowd vented its rage on several (Bosniak) passerbys.  Among them was an old lady who was by chance passing from the western blocks across the boulevard.  Sky-news recorded as she was beaten on her head.  The most fervent demonstrators were until recently soldiers in the HVO [Bosnian Croat militia].  They were shouting: "Za dom spremni" [ready for the homeland, Croatian fascist salute during WWII], and the crowd replied "This is Croatia, this is Croatia"...<P>

European police was totally surprised and unprepared to react.  The policeman silently watched while the extremists were beating two members of the European police.  Nobody dared to confront the violence.  Koschnick was saved with help of IFOR.  He was transfered to a more peaceful wing of the European police building.  He stayed there until the following morning when he returned to his cabinet in the Hotel for retired persons ("Ero").<P>

Mostar inhabitants are wondering: who were the demonstrators?  It was obvious that there were not many urbanized Mostar Croats.  They were, they say on the eastern shore, usurpers of the Bosniak and Serb property, people who used the war for plunder; they obtained other people's apartments, garages, cafes, restaurants cars and other property.  Now they want to keep the fruit of their labor!  Among the extremists were certainly those who cannot get over the disappearance of "Herceg-Bosna"; someone from Zagreb has been fiercely saying to them: Croatian border is in Mostar, for now on the Boulevard...<P>

At the time when this article is sent into print, we have received the following message from the Koschnick's office:" I do not intend to step back nor to resign.  There is no reason to change anything in my decree!"<P>

That is what Hans Koschnick is saying.  The real Mostar inhabitants wish that Europe and the United States enable him to implement his decision.<P>
   

<hr>

Translated on 4/18 1996

<hr>
