<HEAD>
<TITLE>Peace Under Guard</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">


<h1>Peace Under Guard</h1>

<em><strong>by Gojko Beric</em></strong><P>

<h2>Oslobodenje-Svijet, Sarajevo-Ljubljana, Bosnia-Hercegovina, May 2 1996</h2>

Media reports of the current state of peace in Bosnia are more and more filled with developments of the kind which preceded the recently finished war.  Again, we are witnessing the "grass-roots democracy", an infamous Serb political invention.  There is shooting, beatings and stoning.  Victims are people who are trying to visit the homes from which they have been expelled and the graves of the loved ones.  As at the beginning of the war, groups of extremists are in charge of lynch and intimidation, while the local police ignores their actions aware that the incident has been planned by the authorities.<P>

A larger group of Bosniaks and Croats was stoned during their attempt to enter Doboj, although they had a permission from the Serb authorities and were escorted by IFOR troops.  Witnesses claim that the Serb thugs were led by Chetniks from the Ozren mountain who now live in the best Bosniak and Croat houses in Doboj.  IFOR soldiers had  shoot in the air in order to prevent a bloodbath.  Frustrated General Mladic who tries to fend away fear by claiming that his head is too expensive, threatened IFOR by saying that "a spontaneous revenge of the Serb people" was inevitable if a similar event happens again.  Therefore, if IFOR keeps preventing Serb thugs, Serb people will apply the tactics of revenge since the war has been lost already.<P>

Only a few days later, Serb extremists repeated their achievement.  This time they beat up with wooden clubs ten, out of about 300 Croat civilians from Tramosnica near Gradacac who had come to visit the village from which they had been expelled in 1992.  Then Croats took care that Serbs are not left without anything to complain about and prevented 600 refugees from visiting their homes and family graves in Glamoc.  Croatian authorities had previously approved this visit, but the number of refugees was supposed to be smaller.<P>

These incidents indicate that refugees are a detonator which can incite new explosions in Bosnia.  Their attempts to return to their homes, as is stipulated in the Dayton agreement, so far are taking shape of a war of nerves which can one day transform itself into a real war.  Return of refugees, even in a limited numbers, would signify the defeat of all extremists, especially the Serb and Croat ones. Of course, one can argue whether it is realistic to expect the return. Nationalistic leaders make the return conditional on purported reciprocity while in fact they try to prevent it with all their might; otherwise
their adventure in Bosnia would collapse.  They favor the situation which will
separate the nations all the way to the last individual, complicate their lives and turn them into apathetic, timid and servile subjects.  Although they are 
the signatories of the federal agreement, Croats and Bosniaks, are making
lives difficult for each other.  Evidence can be found in Stolac and Capljina
on one and Bugojno on the other side.  What can one then expect from Karadzic
Serbs.<P>

Belgrade and Zagreb have been collaborating in the business of the total ethnic 
division of Bosnia since the meeting in Karadordevo. The latest example is
Mostar.  Milosevic has recently prevented a group of Serb refugees from Mostar to travel to Mostar to assess the chances for return in order not 
to aggrieve Tudman.  Because, if Serbs were to return to Mostar, the situation in that city would change significantly.  But, in that case Tudman would also have his claims from Milosevic in [northern] Bosnia.  And in their game of political chess a draw, at least as far as Bosnia is concerned, has been agreed a long time ago.  Epidemics of hate is still going strong.  All of its departments are
still working, from media to the hitmen who intimidate the persons from the "other" nation.  The whole life has been infected by hate.  The members of the Sarajevo band, "Zabranjeno Pusenje" [No Smoking] were assaulted during their concert in the Zagreb club "Best".  The assault began when the Sarajevo boys started the song "Fato Mori Dusmanke," which reminded angry Croat patriots of Serbs.  The boys probably know that in World War II, Americans and Germans fought to the finish, but they obviously have no idea that American soldiers liked to listen to "Lilly Marlen" and German soldiers to jazz.<P>

Here, hate, regardless whether we speak about the beating of refugees 
or musicians, is the engine of a political project whose goal is the
division and the disappearance of Bosnia-Hercegovina.  But, the historic
drama of Bosnia-Hercegovina is that it cannot be divided.  The present
division was carried out with force and mass crimes against Bosniaks.
The peace is at the moment under the guard of IFOR, the strongest of
the four armies based in Bosnia.  But, the present peace will eventually become unbearable.  Two million people are still displaced.  This energy can decisively influence the reintegration
of Bosnia but, likewise, it can push it into a new war.<P>

<hr>

Translated on 5/21/96
</FONT>

