<HEAD>
<TITLE>Tiger Ate a Penguin</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>Tiger Ate a Penguin</h1>

<strong><em>by Dejan Anastasijevic</em></strong><P>

<h2>Vreme, Belgrade, FR Yugoslavia, 3/23/96</h2>

This week, another Belgrade radio station with the word "independent" in its name, found a new owner and lost its independence.  "There are no independent media today," said the new editor-in-chief about the new editorial policy which will exclude politics and concentrate on music and entertainment.  However, this event didn't provoke reactions of the European Union, State Department, Committee for the Protection of Journalists, not even Serbian opposition parties.  In fact, even the employees had nothing against the change.  They are used to having much worse experiences at their work places.  Of course, we are talking about the former "independent Radio Penguin" (frequency 90.9MHz) which, since Monday, March 3, bears the name "Radio Tiger".  That radio station crossed from the hands of a local businessman Giovanni Di Stefano to the hands of another businessman, Zeljko Raznatovic Arkan.  Both businessmen have an enviable international reputation: they have been sentenced, both here and abroad, for numerous criminal actions; some countries still have warrants for their arrest.  The history of the station, which has changed three owners in six months is also interesting.<P>

"Radio Penguin" was founded in 1990 by late Radojica Nikcevic, Montenegrin businessman, as "the first private and independent" radio station in Belgrade (Radio B92 existed at the time but was still officially a "socially owned" company).  From the start, "Radio Penguin" was an absolutely apolitical station, whose program boiled down to music and entertainment (mostly listener phone-in) programs.  Nikcevic gathered around this station a large number of young people who were tired of their fruitless attempts to brake through the ossified structures of state-controlled radio stations and were waiting for a chance to prove themselves.  "We were all full of energy and enthusiasm," remembers Darko Kocijan, first editor-in-chief in "Penguin".  However, some things were  unclear: for example, where did Nikcevic find money for the equipment and offices, how did he manage to secure in a very short time frequencies and permits which are very hard to obtain in this state (Radio B92 is still waiting for most of those permits).  Nikcevic shed some light on that mystery boasting while tipsy that he didn't know for which state's intelligence service he worked: federal, Serbian or Montenegrin.  Still, nobody had a problem with that: as we mentioned, the program was apolitical and fun, while the salaries were good.<P>

<strong>MURDER:</strong>  First scandal with connection to "Radio Penguin" (true, only to a certain extent) happened on October 7, 1993, when Radojica Nikcevic was murdered at the parking lot in front of his other company, Building Co-op "Sumadija", in Vase Pelagic street.  The murder was carried out very professionally and hasn't been solved until today.  The investigation never progressed from the two bullet cartridges, caliber 0.44 found next to the corpse and the witness testimony which stated that Nikcevic was approached by two men in worker suits while getting out of his car; the men shot him in the head.  The murder revealed two more things, until then hidden from the public: first, that Nikcevic, besides "Sumadija" and "Penguin" also had a business partner, Giovanni Di Stefano; second, that a short time before his death Nikcevic traveled with Di Stefano to Columbia.  This information was also interesting because several months later several foreign agencies that fight against international drug trade made discrete inquiries in Belgrade regarding Di Stefano and his connections with drug cartel from Medellin in Columbia.<P>

However, Di Stefano has always denied any involvement in drug trade and in the death of his business partner; after inheriting his companies, Di Stefano appropriately grieved for Nikcevic and only had good things to say about his partner (Di Stefano still keeps Nikcevic's photo on his desk).<P>

The takeover of "Penguin" opened another channel for Di Stefano's self promotion, something for which he had shown a lot of inclination since his arrival to Belgrade in 1992.  This Italian from the Pescara region, who hardly knows any Italian but speaks fluent English with [London] cockney accent, at first (falsely) introduced himself as the main owner of the American film company "Metro Goldwin Mayer" (and a dozen of less known companies); he was drawn to Yugoslavia by his great love for Serbs and everything Serbian.  More likely, Di Stefano sensed fantastic business opportunities in the country under international sanctions, whose government urgently needed services in the field of illegal financial transactions.<P>

In that sense, Di Stefano was, without a doubt, a great expert who paid for his education with a jail sentence which he had served in England (he tried to establish a bank without capital) and trials in many other countries, including France and the United States of America.  Like Nikcevic, he had a talent for breaking of bureaucratic barriers: for example he obtained a Yugoslav passport with the address in the immediate Milosevic's neighborhood in the extremely short time.<P>

However, something went wrong in his relations with the local authorities in April 1994, when he was arrested.  He was soon released but the DM 70,000 bail bond was never paid back to him.  That case did not affect "Penguin" at all: the station continued to broadcast good music and good entertainment programs, although the salaries were not as good as at the beginning.<P>

<strong>DISMISSAL:</strong>  The next scandal occured on April 27, 1995.  On that day, certain Mijo Medak, a driver in "Radio Penguin" was accidentally shot and wounded by one of Di Stefano's body guards.  For the majority of journalists who were incensed by extremely arrogant behavior of the station's owner and ever more infrequent and smaller pay checks this was the last straw.  In protest, fifty two of them resigned.  Nevertheless, some remained, and with assistance of newly employed underqualified personnel, the program continued.  Out of the better known journalists only Marko Jankovic, former star D.J. from "Studio B" remained; today he is the deputy editor-in-chief at "Radio Penguin".<P>

We can only speculate why Di Stefano decided to pass the station to Raznatovic.  Di Stefano is Arkan's old friend: at the time he (allegedly) financed Arkan's and Ceca's wedding, which was worth some DM 300,000 and besides that he used to boast that he was a general in Arkan's guard (although he has never been seen on the front).  Taking into account an old Di Stefano's statement that he "owes his life to Arkan", it is clear that if Zeljko desired "Penguin", this was an offer Di Stefano couldn't refuse.  Besides, he has been, for a while now, slowly moving the center of his activities to Italy where he is currently based as one of the 100,000 individuals running for office in the forthcoming elections.  In addition to that, after the suspension of sanctions it is uncertain whether anyone here will need Di Stefano's services in the future.  The jarring absence of prominent official figures at Di Stefano's wedding in June, 1995, is another indication that this might be the case.<P>

It is another question why Arkan, who directly or indirectly controls three illustrated magazines ("Srpsko Jedinstvo" [Serb Unity], "Metak" [Bullet] and "Ring"), would need a radio station.  Furthermore, according to Borislav Prelevic, Arkan's deputy and current editor-in-chief of former "Penguin", "'Tiger' will not rest until we get the permit for the broadcast of TV program."  In that way, former criminal, then the leader of soccer fans, baker, patriot and a businessmen will become a media tycoon.<P>

"Radio Tiger" like "Radio Penguin" will exclusively broadcast music and entertainment programs.  Prelevic promised to distribute long overdue pay checks, and a neon penguin with a top hat is still showing off on the facade of the April 11 sport center building on Bezanijska Kosa.  He will probably soon be replaced by a less likeable, but more dangerous animal from the genus of     large cats.<P>

<hr>

<h2>And the music played on...</h2>

<strong><em>by Teofil Pancic</em></strong><P>

<em>Who are the owners of Belgrade radio stations</em><P>

Local authorities are very sensitive when it comes to claims that in Serbia, especially when electronic media are concerned, there is not enough media freedom and variety; although they do not tolerate spontaneous pluralism (the left of that kind has always been afraid of "uncontrolled developments in the society"), our authorities have nothing against organized, almost directed media pluralism.  On the contrary: whenever possible (and it is always possible), the ruling party and its trustworthy people, including those who "let us be clear are not the members of any party" establish a new radio or TV station.  This strategy is as simple as it is efficient: classical state-controlled media (Serbian TV and its subsidiaries) are used for ideological awakening of the masses, while "commercial" and "private" media are there to make sure that everything besides news programs passes by in the perpetual "Time for sport and fun"[well known radio program].  In this way, today every Serbian town  has a radio and/or TV station which serves to divert the population which has definitively had enough of politics.  All sorts of music tastes are covered, from turbo folk and astrological mumbo-jumbo, over easy listening to grateful teenage audience.  Because of unidentified reasons, the personnel of the radio stations, including editors and management usually refuses to talk to journalists about the ownership of the media house they work for.<P>

In the office of <strong>Radio Roda</strong> [Stork] our early morning call was taken by a young colleague who politely responded that as far as she knew, "unless something has changed in the meantime", Radio Roda belonged to Cukarica county.<P>

It seems that the employees in <strong>Radio Golf</strong> try not to talk about such a sensitive (?) topic while their bosses are away; they asked us to call later.  Later, a surprised voice responded to our question with another question: why does it matter?  To our conciliatory reply that maybe it doesn't matter, but hopefully is not a secret, the voice said that "Golf has several owners, and all of them are businessmen who invest their money in different projects.  You know we are totally apolitical radio station, we only play music (Vreme: "I know, I know, I listen to your station a lot...").  And your paper is very political, isn't it?  Anyway, you could be anyone.  Leave me your number and I will have the editor-in-chief call you when he comes to work."  We are still waiting.<P>

<strong>Radio Kosava</strong>:  In the most windy Belgrade radio station, a secretary responds to our naive question regarding the identity of the station's owner: "I could give you that information, but it depends on what you intend to do with it."  Since, it seems, I wasn't convincing enough regarding my intentions, the secretary finally responded: "you should call our marketing director around 11 o'clock."  The gentlemen didn't show up on time.  Nor did he show up by twelve.  Nor one.  As far as I am concerned, he hasn't shown up until today.<P>

<strong>Radio S</strong>: a secretary sounded as if she just got back from a briefing with the colleague from Kosava Radio: I don't know, I'm not from here, it's only us chicken here; leave me your number and I will have the editor-in-chief call you when he comes to work.  We established without any doubt that the editor's name is Godot.  By the way, it is known that the station used to be owned by the company "Genes S" (director Zoran Andelkovic-Baki), which is on the other hand owned by the Serbian Socialist Party [ruling party in Serbia] but the last fall, according to our source at the radio, Baki resigned in order to get out of the unenviable situation in which the radio was at the time.  Then he informed employees that "Genes S" had nothing to do with Radio S and that the program (introduced a while ago as a program with a lot of "cultural and amusement content") would have to finance itself and even pay a debt to Andelkovic's company.  Another source claims that Andelkovic and "Genes S" still own the station.  Whoever is the nominal owner of the station, the whole affair never left the family circle.<P>

Although peace has no alternative in Serbia likeable penguins are turning into blood-thirsty tigers, without any excitement.  It seems that the public has finally accepted the motto of the reserve state-controlled media: let us be happy!  Until we all become a part of the animal kingdom.<P>

<hr>

Translated on May 27 1996<P>

