A new conjugate gradient constant modulus adaptive processor is proposed and 
studied.  For the generalized sidelobe canceler signal processing 
configuration, this algorithm, called the CGGSC for Conjugate Gradient 
adaptive algorithm as applied to the Generalized Sidelobe Canceler, 
exhibits improved convergence over existing methods.  Theoretical expressions 
are presented for convergence and weight update of the linearly constrained 
constant modulus generalized sidelobe canceler.  Theoretical  expressions 
are then derived for the conjugate direction vectors.  These vectors are used 
to update the filter weights for a conjugate gradient adaptation rule.  A 
simulation study of the new conjugate adaptation rule reveals an increase 
in convergence rate for the generalized sidelobe canceler.  Performance 
comparisons of the CGGSC and the first-order gradient GSC for a BPSK 
signal with multipath and white noise interference  indicate that the CGGSC 
adaptation rule not only increases convergence by a factor of five 
compared to the first-order gradient GSC, but in some instances improves 
the bit error rate of the demodulated BPSK signal.     
</DOC>
