<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Opposition and the Bosnian Elections</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">
<h1>Symbiosis</h1>

<strong><em>by Vlastimir Milovic</em></strong><P>

<h2>Oslobodenje-Svijet, Sarajevo-Ljubljana, Bosnia-Hercegovina, 5/30/96</h2>

The elections may or may not take place in September, as planned, but, whenever
they finally take place, the advantage will be on the side of the currently
ruling, national parties.  Civic option has achieved a lot by managing to survive
in the nationalist storm of the war.  Therefore, it keeps open a chance for
its recovery, although not in a near future, as its supporters might wish.
The circumstances favor so called war parties, actually national movements
which in the Bosnian war storm became the representatives of the people, whether 
that people wanted that or not.<P>

On the territory under the control of the young men who wear uniforms with the Bosnian
insignia the Party of Democratic Action is undisputed favourite to win the
forthcoming elections.  The main reason for that is the merger between the leading
Bosniak party and the state.<P>

The Party of Democratic Action has grown so close to the state that it is impossible
to distinguish between the two.  If during the war and the resistance to the
merciless aggression one could find justification for unity, this peace,
no matter how uncertain it may seem, sets the obligation of respect for the true
democratic principles.  Those who remind that the process of the separation
of the party and state structure requires at least as much time as was
necessary for the merger of the two structures have a point.  Those who claim
that this separation will not occur without outside pressure do not lack arguments:
they point out that this symbiosis of the ruling party and the state will
defend its monopoly with all available means.<P>

Monopolies and privilege are multiplying progressively.  Those who have good memory
remember well how that process developed in socialism: how the Communist League
merged with the state and how the political monopoly of that party turned into
the monopoly and privilege of its members.  Membership in the ruling socialist
party was the precondition for any sort of political, social and economic 
success.  The state had a clear communist party infrastructure, almost identical
to the one we have today, but in the Party for Democratic Action version.  As in the
past all directors of larger state-controlled companies were members of the League
of Communists, today all directors of larger state-controlled companies
are members of the Party for Democratic Action.<P>

A great purge has been conducted during the last five years; it was based on the 
party membership;  it seems that it still goes on.  People whose good will we 
shouldn't doubt (although we can doubt their sources, since they are foreigners)
recently warned about this trend.  Still, the analysts of the OSCE, in charge
of the pre-election process in Bosnia, do not have to offer new evidence for
the claim that SDA, "especially in the provinces", applies pressure to other 
parties and independents.  It has been a public secret that the members of
the ruling party have taken all important positions in political, social and
economic leadership.  They utilize their positions in two ways: to perpetuate
their power and to induce independent voters to "make the right choice".
In such a way, they essentially use non-political methods to strengthen their 
power and the primacy of the ruling party.<P>

Politicians view elections as a kind of a war.  As there is a dirty war, as we
learned from the Serb-Montenegrin variety, there are also dirty elections.  
If something doesn't significantly change in the meantime, we will experience
dirty elections as well.  That is the essence of the warning issued
by the OSCE mission for Bosnia-Hercegovina, that the elections should be
as honest as possible, although this warning is only a version of an old and
worn out song.  Still these warnings used to come from the opposition parties
which in Bosnia haven't been treated adequately; therefore their warnings haven't
had desired effects.  European warning might fare better, since in this 
country we habitually pay more attention to anything coming from abroad than
to our own people, public, and political parties.<P>

The key problems in connection with the forthcoming Bosnian elections are
the consequences of some bad solutions from the Dayton Agreement, and the
lack of determination in the world community, and the guarantors
of the peace agreement, to help eliminate some results of the war, above all
the results of ethnic cleansing.  This topic is as old as the electoral rules
imposed on Bosnia-Hercegovina by the foreigners, the electoral rules to which 
anyone sane and honest has a lot of objections because of the aforementioned 
reasons.  However, in the obsession with, we must emphasize, the most
important defects of the election rules and pre-election situation, the problem
of party fair play has been undeservedly marginalized.  And this problem doesn't
only exist in Sarajevo, as the OSCE mission reaction indicated.  This problem is
even more pronounced in Pale [Bosnian Serb capital] and Grude [Bosnian Croat capital]
where the Serbian Democratic Party and the Croatian Democratic Community control
everything.  There, membership in other parties is dangerous for one's life.
>From that stems the need to, whenever elections take place, develop a situation
in which all parties and their members will be treated equally.  Absolute
equality, due to current circumstances, cannot be promoted at the moment,
but every new building, including the erection of the modern democratic
infrastructure in Bosnia-Hercegovina, starts from the foundation.<P>


<hr><P>Translated on 8/20/96<P>
</FONT>
