<HEAD>
<TITLE>Mostar Elections</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">
<h1>Two Mostars - Three Bosnias</h1>

<strong><em>by Alija Behram</em></strong><P>

<h2>Oslobodenje-Svijet, Sarajevo-Ljubljana, Bosnia-Hercegovina, 6/13/96</h2>

On June 30 the citizens of Mostar will make a fateful decision which will
 certainly define the political future of the city for years to come.
The threat of division hangs over the Neretva.  At the time, immediately
after the bloody and tragic conflicts besides the Neretva, the Bosniak side 
approached the negotiations with the motto: "two Mostars = three Bosnias"
(or "One Mostar - peaceful Bosnia") trying to warn that the ethnic divisions
could only be the introduction to the definitive dissolution
of Bosnia.<P>

Many in Mostar are aware that the inhabitants are facing the following question:
will the June elections be simply the election for the local authorities or the
elections for the democratic concept of Bosnia-Hercegovina.  The great majority
of inhabitants hopes that the idea of the future unification of their city
will prevail at the election.<P>

<strong>POLITICAL SCENE</strong>: Mostar awaits these elections physically divided;
However, those experts who warn that more worrisome is the psychological division 
of the city, numerous blockades, denials and violations of human rights and freedoms,
hit the heart of the problem.  At work is the unbelievable intransigency which
tries to defend the unnatural situation besides the Neretva which had been achieved 
by force.  Exactly because of that, about a month ago, the idea of "the list for Mostar" initiated by the mayor
of the eastern half of the city, Safet Orucevic, was received with hope and understandable emotions.  Its goal was to activate
a pro-Bosnian front for the unification of the city.<P>

The coalition of six political parties of Bosnian orientation was interpreted
in the Bosnian public as a welcome sign of the readiness to push the narrow
political interests aside in this crucial moment for the future of Mostar and
emphasize the common goal of the integral Bosnia whose chances are being tested
in Mostar.<P>

"The elections in Mostar are the chance to forge a Bosnian front in order to
try to realize here all those ideas which are shared by the ruling party as 
well as the opposition parties," said Safet Orucevic.<P>

However, in Mostar, they are not hiding the unacceptable attitude of some circles
in the ruling SDA who would rather see the victory over the opposition than 
the united victory against the extremists which support the ethnic division of the
city.<P> 

Still, in Mostar, nothing has been lost.  On the contrary.  Many here believe
that the most important political and diplomatic battle had already been won
since all the citizens of Mostar will be allowed to vote in the election, wherever they
live today.  The Election results will hardly affect the changes of the county
statute, which ensured the equality of all citizens in the City council and
another six municipal councils.  The most important thing, according to Orucevic, 
is that  the citizens of Mostar were given a chance to be heard, to say that
they are alive and that they belong to this city and that this city belongs
to them; to condemn the crimes and criminals because of whom they had had to 
escape from the city.<P>

<strong>ENIGMA SILAJDZIC</strong>: Many in Mostar wonder how the Party
for Bosnia-Hercegovina, led by the former prime minister dr. Haris Silajdzic, will
treat Mostar.  "Mostar is a special sort of challenge," Silajdzic has told
this journalist; he assessed that the best solution for Mostar was a common
list of all the parties from this region and that the victory was less important
compared with the future of the city.  Of course, Mostar as a multinational
center of the region.  It remains to be seen whether Silajdzic will contest the 
election with the list of the opposition parties or together with Orucevic,
as he had promised earlier.<P>

The press has already registered that Dr. Durakovic's statements regarding
the possible coalition of the Party for Bosnia-Hercegovina and the list
of five opposition parties were interpreted in the cabinet of Dr. Silajdzic
as Dr. Durakovic's attempt to "assume the position of a spokesperson for the 
party for Bosnia-Hercegovina".  Therefore, it seems more likely that Silajdzic,
together with some other parties which are "checking out" the situation in 
Mostar, might stay in coalition with SDA; also, he might decide to enter the
elections besides the Neretva on his own.  Ilija Simic, vicepresident of
Croatian Peasant Party (HSS) says that that party has decided to enter a coalition
in Mostar, but that doesn't mean that they will contest the forthcoming
Bosnia-wide elections within the same coalition.  The Republicans, according to
Stjepan Kljuic, will also enter a coalition with other opposition parties
since their motto is "the preservation of secular and multiethnic Bosnia,"
and that is what they want to achieve in Mostar.  Muja Kafedzic, from the
Muslim Bosniak Organization (MBO) believes that in this case it is important
to demonstrate common support for the reintegration of Bosnia-Hercegovina.
"Our programs are mostly similar and we want to unite people regardless of 
their nationality," says Kafedzic.<P>

<strong>SERBS WILL(NOT) VOTE</strong>:  Local Serbs will also get the chance
to vote in the local elections.  However, the member of the advisory council of the EU
Mostar administration, Obren Lozo is bitter because of the fact that the agreement
on the conduct of the local elections in this city (signed by Rajko Gatalo,
as a member of the Serb community in the same council) rejected the idea that
Mostar Serbs vote in some locations in Nevesinje and Belgrade, where the 
majority of them lives today.  Lozo emphasizes that very few of them will
come to Mostar to vote.  It was necessary to allow the Serbs to vote in those
cities.  However, Lozo doesn't know how it was possible that Rajko Gatalo
"on behalf of Serbs" signed such a document.  "I do know that this kind of
voting procedure discriminates against Serbs; that is not correct and we
will protest because of that," concludes Obren Lozo.<P>

Serb Civic Council (SGV) from Sarajevo also issued a statement regarding the 
election in Mostar.  "If the EU does not accept the SGV demand to open two
voting stations in Belgrade in Nevesinje, than it will be responsible for
discriminating against one of the ethnic groups in Mostar, this time
against Serbs; by doing so the EU will prevent Serbs from taking part
in a democratic process and making decision about theirs and the future of
Mostar," were the words of Mirko Pejanovic, the president of SGV of 
Bosnia-Hercegovina.  SGV has sent letters to the Italian Foreign Minister, 
Lamberto Dini, German Foreign Minister, Klaus Kinkel and the chiefs of OSCE,
ambassadors of the USA and Great Britain, demanding that the EU administration
in Mostar provide two voting stations for Mostar Serbs living in 
Nevesinje in Belgrade.<P>

The musings of the current local HDZ chief in Mostar, Jadranko Topic, are 
also interesting.  He has stated for the Agence France-Presse that "the 
elections are simply a chance for the population to have some fun." In the 
end, he predicted, Mostar would be divided by Croatia and Serbia.  To 
journalist's remark that Tudman had had to give in in Mostar because of
the EU pressure, Topic responded: "Every president Tudman's decision  is
acceptable for us.  It is high time to understand that only Croatian leadership
can debate and make decisions about Croatian lands."  He also added:<P>

"The elections will confirm the struggle of the Croatian people in this region,
but also the divisions among the Muslim people, as in 1990...  This elections
must demonstrate what has been agreed about Mostar.  That there are three
Muslim and three Croat municipalities in the city.  The Federation will also
have to be divided in that manner; it will consist of Croatian and Muslim
municipalities, cantons and regions..."<P>

The refugees will vote in Sweden, Switzerland, Norway and Germany.  There
are rumors that the Serbs might get their way and that they will be allowed
to vote in the Italian embassy in Belgrade.  Will Milosevic [Serbian president]
agree with that?<P>

"We will shortly provide the text of the amendments which will regulate all the
remaining points," says Ricardo Peres-Casado, the administrator of Mostar.
Political parties are going through the last preparations for the election campaign.
First signs of election platforms which will be offered to Mostar inhabitants
can already be discerned.  It remains to be seen whether the citizens of Mostar 
will recognize the best option.<P>

<hr><P>Translated on 7/17/96<P>
</FONT>
<hr>
<a HREF="/info/students/marko/musbos.html"><IMG SRC="/info/students/marko/
pictures/home.gif" ALT="HOME" WIDTH=80 HIGHT=40></a>
