<HEAD>
<TITLE>Struggle in the top of SDA</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>Fatal Delay</h1>

<strong><em>by Gojko Beric</em></strong><P>

<h2>Oslobodenje-Svijet, Sarajevo-Ljubljana, Bosnia-Hercegovina, 4/4/96</h2>

The latest <a HREF="/info/students/marko/ljiljan3.html">interview of president 
Alija Izetbegovic</a> to <em>Ljiljan</em> was shockingly refreshing to all
those who follow president's public appearances and statements.  Interview
was conducted by  Izetbegovic's close friend and the SDA ideologist, Dzemaludin 
Latic and the dialog had more resemblance to a family quarrel than to a conversation
among the two men coming from the same political party.  In the interview,
Izetbegovic almost nervously contradicted a local stereotype  which states
that the whole world has been plotting against Bosnia-Hercegovina and the 
Bosniaks, and emphasized that we had made some mistakes as well.<P>  

He mentioned the media who are falling head over heels trying
to prove that the multinational Bosnia is not possible; he used <em>Ljiljan</em> 
as an example.   He admitted that the fact that near Fojnica,
even after the signing of the Dayton Agreement, there was a base for the 
training of commandos was a "huge mistake".<P>

Recognizing in Latic's question the thesis that America is the enemy of Bosnia,
Izetbegovic almost quipped at Latic: "Let me ask you this: would Bosnia be
more secure if we found out that America and with it another 10 most important
countries in the world were all our enemies.  I don't think that America is our 
enemy, but we can make an enemy out of it...  Iran proved during the war that
it is a true friend, but Iran is far and our enemies are close."<P>

The analysis of this, as well as several other recent public appearances of
president Izetbegovic, lead to the conclusion that he has changed his political
tactics.  This change was forced by the grey perspective for Bosnia, the
situation in the ruling party and the latest pressure from the American government, 
which believes that it has been lenient towards Izetbegovic long enough.<P>

Izetbegovic is probably aware that there is little he can do for the future of 
Bosnia. Even if everything depended on his skill and will there is no time 
left for that deed.  On the other hand he cares about what he will leave behind.
During his stay in a hospital, he addressed the public twice.  On the Statehood 
day he appealed that "all of us, in the future, behave less like Bosniaks,
Croats, Serbs, Jews... and more like the citizens of Bosnia-Hercegovina."
Izetbegovic sees in the symbiosis of ethnic and national identity the way
to cure the wounds of this war and to avoid the repetition of the tragedy.<P>

In some better times, when no one sensed the horror lurking behind the hill,
this message would have had the value of a true political program.  Unfortunately
it is coming to us with a fatal delay.  We can only talk about its usefulness
in the context of the forthcoming elections.  Today, Izetbegovic has serious
difficulties with his political philosophy, which can be condensed in the 
analysis of religion and ethnicity.  From the very start, due to Izetbegovic's 
influence, SDA has had the character of a political and religious movement. 
At the time when the Bosniak people had already had a knife on its throat,
that orientation had some practical sense, but in the meantime it has become
harmful.  SDA today functions as a conservative political party, with religion
in place of ideology, which objectively excludes it from the club of modern
European parties.  However, the main problem is in its wrong policy, which
superficially appears as a pure dilettantism.  No one knows what the SDA national
and religious programs are; if they exist they are essentially contradictory.<P>

Izetbegovic knows that the political restoration of SDA is necessary, but he
is not sure how far he can go in that.  The party compass is still in his hands.
However, isn't a sudden change in direction dangerous for him as well?  There
are also other troubles.  The latest assessments show that the split with
Silajdzic may be more dangerous than it seemed at first.  Silajdzic is
reserving ever more stronger criticism for his former party because of the
misuse of religion in politics (this is the program of the extreme wing of SDA).
Controversy arising from the split between Silajdzic and Izetbegovic is somewhat
paradoxical since one has an impression that the two of them essentially
share the same political views...  If he starts an open showdown with the
extremists of the politically religious orientation, who dangerously complicate
the Bosnian position in the eyes of the West, that would mean that Izetbegovic
was trying to liberalize his party and at the same time to diminish the importance
of the split with the former Prime Minister, who had for a long time been 
his right hand.  Izetbegovic's fear that the liberal wing of SDA could join Silajdzic's new party has some basis in reality.<P>

Both domestic and foreign affairs limit the time in which Izetbegovic has to
make up his mind about what he really wants.  That is a new factor for all 
those trying to divine whether Bosnia is moving toward reintegration or toward
the tragic dawn of its dissolution.<P>

<hr>

Translated on 6/19/96<P>
</FONT>
