<HEAD>
<TITLE>Maja Cleans Up Croatia</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>Cleaning Up Our Own House</h1>

<strong><em>by Maja Freundlich</em></strong><P>

<h2>Hrvatski Obzor, Zagreb, Croatia, 11/13 1995</h2>

It has been five years since we decided that we didn't want to be a part of Yugoslavia.  We decided to start with democratic elections and to choose in those elections that party which guaranteed freedom from slavery under Serb domination, and which promised the end of the seventy-years-old destiny of the deceived, imprisoned and used nation.  We decided to make any sacrifices necessary to finally achieve independence, not to be ruled by anyone, not to be endangered by anyone, not to be killed and persecuted by anyone.<P>

The war is waning, nearing its end, and it is necessary to remind ourselves why we wanted out of Serb or any other Yugoslavia.  There are two reasons for that.  First, because some in the world, exactly those who at the time founded Yugoslavia, would like to push us back into it again, and give it a different name.  Now, it would allegedly be called <A HREF="http://www.mix.it/logoi/eurosing.htm">Euroslavia</A>.  Even this name shows that the babbling about Europe is actually a setting of a tempting goal through which it would be possible to impose any serious political solution on Croats and other South Slav savages and slowly push them back where they used to be in the first place.  The war at the south of Europe doesn't seem tragic to the English and those like them because the Serbs are killing people or because the Serbs have destroyed everything, but because the Serbs are loosing this war.  Indeed, the last hopes for the resurrection of Yugoslavia disappear with the Serb defeat.  That current in the world politics sees the only way out in the blackmail with eastern Slavonia and the Bosnian solution.<P>

<h2>Systematic Immigration</h2>

We wanted out of Yugoslavia because every nation has a right to freedom, independence, its own life in its historic house.  Today, when we are winning this war, which has been started by Serbia, today, after four years of suffering, today, when we see the light at the end of the tunnel, we cannot even contemplate a return to somebody's common bedroom, nor can we ever sacrifice our fate in order to satisfy the imperialist illness of the Russians, Serbs or English.  Or anyone else.<P>

However, at the first elections we also sought to achieve freedom from all constraints, policemen and persecution which had constituted Serb rule and domination in Croatia.  Let us recall Yugoslavia from which we wanted to escape.  It wasn't only built on its outside borders.  On the contrary.  For years, especially in Croatia, it was based on a complicated system of Serb overseers and sentries, who controlled our lives.<P>

Croatia was imagined as a country whose natural resources were handed over to Serbia, whose people was only a never-ending source of industrious slaves, whose foreign currency earnings had to be handed over to Serbs or to Serbia.  Croats were systematically denied employment, advancement in service, success; instead they were offered jail or a passport for a journey to Germany.  Serbs immigrated to Croatia, systematically and according to a plan, in order to increase their numbers and to turn Croatia into their country, really "a Serb land, which has always been a Serb land."  The greatest percentage of Serbs, who today demand all kinds of rights for themselves in Croatia, were colonized here with the clear intent for enslavement, gradual ethnic cleansing, changing of the ethnic composition of the population and the establishment of the strong network for police rule over Croats and Croatia.<P>

Serbs were in the most important positions in every Croatian company, factory, cultural establishment, school, government.  Wherever the source of power was in the director's position, a Serb man or a woman would certainly occupy that position.  Whenever a director was only a figurehead, the real power was in the hands of a chief of personnel.  In that case, a Croat would be found for the position of the director and the personnel would collect new reliable Serbs through advertisements.  In those cases, the professionalism of that man wasn't important; it was important that he was "our man".<P>

<h2>Power from Shadows</h2>

Therefore, when the former Communists and Serbs accuse today Croatian authorities for ethnic and party based cleansing of the society, they don't talk about what the Croatian authorities actually do.  Croatian authorities, on the contrary and unfortunately, haven't yet done that anywhere.  They are talking about cleansing because they know that they used to carry it out themselves; they know that the changes in the composition of the people can cause true changes in the social system, and are shouting in order to prevent the establishment of the true Croatian rule in the society.  Fighting for their own survival, they started shouting against "revenge" as early as 1990.<P>

Former rulers still control the core of the Croatian society, only because they sit at comfortable, hidden, but the most powerful positions.  While the Croats are dying, while Croats think that, besides the war, it is necessary to produce wealth for all members of the society, while Croats argue over whether someone stole something or gained more than others, the former people still think about "their people", assiduously care for them, and develop "organizations for protection of human rights."  Of course they wouldn't have been able to do all that without help from abroad.  Croatian police action "Zenit" revealed only a millimeter high top of a huge iceberg, and proved that Serb spies are in many important positions, even as important as the expert services in the Parliament.  Imagine then where else they could be.  Besides, the operation "Zenit" discovered only "operatives", those who, as former policemen, were actually establishing a spy network.  What about all those "our people" who had been implanted here a long time ago?<P>

To what extent do these people want to destroy the possibility for the survival of the Croatian society?  To what extent are they destroying it from inside, in hope that it will soon fail, and that a new slave-owning Yugoslav rubbish heap will grow on its ashes?  Isn't is our duty today, five years after the first elections in which we wanted freedom from all that, after we have secured our borders, to turn around in our own house and think about all those things we need to do in the future?<P>
 

<hr>

Translated on 4/28 1996<P>


