<HEAD>
<TITLE>Croatia Refused Membership in the European Council</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">
  

<h1>New Humiliation for Croatia</h1>

 

<h2> Hrvatski Obzor, Zagreb, Croatia, 5/27/96, page 7.</h2>

"Croatia must wait a little longer before being welcomed
into the European Union. This decision, made by the
community of western states showed once again their rigidity
in its grotesquely incorrect behaviour towards a country
struck by aggression." With  these words started the
commentary published a few days ago in the respected
Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung by Johann Georg Reissmueller.
The author stated that "the West didn't do anything when the
war started in Croatia, they only observed ethnic cleansing,
and in a carefree manner left a third of Croatia's
territories in the hands of the aggressors". That same West
"closed access to international monetary institutions, and
up until today, the European Union is acting towards the
country in an unfriendly and degrading manner."<P>

Given the fact that Russia in spite  of everything, has been
accepted into the European Union, the commentator asks - "Is
this a political cabaret?" In regard to Croatia's sins, in
the first place there is the Zagreb crisis, for which they
say the "Croatian leadership is behaving in a politically
short-sighted way, however, in keeping within the state's
law and democracy." But because of this crisis  "delaying
Croatia's entrance into the European Union is
irresponsible."  The text also sets out Croatia's co-
operation with the Hague Tribunal where only Croatia has
voluntarily delivered General Blaskic, "which  is not the
case with the Russian generals who have committed war crimes
in Chechenya". Continuing about the freedom of the media,
the author concludes that "not one of the criticisms is
sufficient for the decision to defer the acceptance of
Croatia for a longer period".  The main reason Croatia's
rejection is said to be Bosnia Herzegovina, however
according to Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung "Croatia is not
primarily responsible for the situation in that country, nor
can she alter it."<P>


<hr>
