<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Official Croatian View of the Situation in Mostar</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>

<FONT SIZE="+1">

<h1>Stop for Instigators</h1>

<strong><em>by Miljenko Karacic</em></strong><P>

<h2>Hrvatski Obzor, Zagreb, Croatia, February 26 1996</h2>

Mostar isn't any more the most serious conflict point in the Federation
of Croats and Bosniaks.  It is true, the situation in that divided city
is still far from ideal, but at least no one can point their accusing finger
at Mostar Croats and accuse them of slowing down the implementation of
the Dayton Agreement.  As late as last Friday, it was impossible to 
predict that the solution which would satisfy both the Croats and
Bosniak Muslims was at hand.  In fact, after numerous diplomatic meetings, 
last Friday, in Sarajevo a Croatian delegation led by [Croatian foreign 
minister] Dr. Mate Granic and a Bosniakmuslim delegation led by [Bosnian
president] Alija Izetbegovic set down at the same table.  The mayor of eastern
Mostar, Safet Orucevic, and the EU administrator of the city, Hans Koschnick
were also supposed to be at that meeting.  However, the two of them, in spite
of a written invitation from the Federation president [a Croat, Kresimir Zubak],
did not show up in Sarajevo.  On the contrary, Koschnick had stated at his
weekly press-conference that he hadn't been invited to that meeting.  Alija
Izetbegovic was adamant after the negotiations in Sarajevo: "Koschnik's
decision is in itself a compromise and it won't be modified.  There can be no
compromise with a compromise."<P>

<h2>Granic was an Optimist</h2>

The leader of the Croatian diplomacy indicated that is may be possible to find 
certain modifications which would be a step in the right direction.  That
Granic's optimism was not unfounded.  Since, in spite a strong anti-Croatian
campaign from the EU Mostar administration headquarters, among the authors
of the Dayton Agreement there were those who thought that Koschnik's decision
should have been given a second look; that it was necessary to take into account
Croatian documents which warned about the direct violation of the Dayton
Agreement.<P>

Then, on Saturday morning, Koschnick, Brajkovic [mayor of western Mostar],
and Orucevic were invited to Rome.  As the trip to Rome is much more agreeable
than a trip between Mostar and Sarajevo, none of the three had a problem with
going to "the eternal city".  Actually they were not given a chance to avoid 
 this meeting, since they were picked up by a NATO aircraft in Mostar.
According to the statements of IFOR soldiers, the three Mostar mayors shook
hands before getting in the aircraft, but kept silent throughout the flight.
At the Sunday evening press-conference in Rome in was announced that the borders
of the central city administration district had been changed.  This district
has been significantly reduced and a good part of its territory returned 
to Croatian control.<P>

<h2>High School the Only Remaining Point of Disagreement</h2>

The only difference between the new agreement and the initial Croatian 
proposal is that, against the Croatian will, the old High School building  
is still within the central district and it is supposed to house the city 
government.<P>

This was confirmed by Koschnick himself; he emphasized that, lo and behold,
not everything turned out the way Croats wanted.  After his return to Mostar,
Koschnick said that he hadn't taken part in the Rome negotiations, but that
the official representatives of the Bosniakmuslim and Croatian peoples
had agreed about the new solution and that he could only respect that fact.
Therefore, Koschnick returned from Rome with a new understanding that his 
authority, in spite of loud support from Kinkel and a few other European
ministers, burned out among the Mostar ruins (no connection with the burning
of Koschnick's effigy during the Mostar carnival).  On the other hand, Orucevic
returned to the eastern part of Mostar with a signed resignation to the position
of the president of the "Presidency of Mostar county", as his personal expression
of the dissatisfaction with the new agreement.  Of course, Alija Izetbegovic
refused to accept Orucevic's resignation.  Miro Brajkovic, visibly tired
after Rome, kept his caution:" This is not a victory.  We shouldn't be
euphoric about this.  This is simply a reality which we had supported 
from the beginning."<P>

All together, this was a great triumph for Croatian policy, its use of good
arguments and consistency in the implementation of the agreements.
This became obvious in the days which followed.<P>

<h2>Freedom of Movement was Two Hours Late</h2>

Namely, February 20 was an important day for Mostar.  On that day, after 2p.m.
all the citizens of Mostar were free to move all over the city.  It wasn't easy 
to ensure that.  The freedom of movement was ensured two hours late, after numerous
conversations and phone consultations with Sarajevo and Zagreb.  After all that 
had happened in Mostar it wasn't an easy task.  Especially because in a large group
of those who were waiting to cross from the eastern to the western past of the city,
there was a certain number of trouble-makers, who oppose the peace process.
How else to interpret the hoisting of a green flag with a crescent moon on the
police shelter next to the department store "Hit"?  Some of them wanted to
bring their Bayram [Muslim religious celebration] good mood, stoked by a huge quantity of alcohol, to the
western part of the city.  Police denied to such individuals the right to cross
to the western Mostar and a few of them were arrested.<P>

Koschnick admitted that he had believed that the freedom of movement and the 
unification of police forces wouldn't happen.  Alija Izetbegovic also hurried
with his accusations of Croats, saying that they do not stick to agreed deadlines.<P>

<h2>Only a Few Cross to Eastern Mostar</h2>

"Those two hours are not important, not at all.  What is important is that
the process has started, that Croats have yet again demonstrated good will
and that they respect agreements," said Ivan Jarnjak [Croatian minister of 
Internal Affairs], at the moment when the first patrol of the joint police force
made up from two Croat, two Bosnianmuslim, and two European policemen, and a translator,
arrived to the central administrative district.  The following days followed
without incidents.  Crossings of the citizens from eastern to western part
of Mostar went without troubles.  Police hardly had anything to do.  The 
crossings from western to the eastern side were rare.  Actually, only those who
had crossed to the western side out of curiosity or in order to buy something
returned to the eastern side.  Mostar cab drivers and merchants have made the
most profit out of the new freedom of movement so far.  In the shops in the
central part of the city there is a great demand for bananas and <em>Lasko</em>
beer.  So far, taxi cab drivers are sticking to their respective sides.<P>

Joint police force will be active in the central district until March 1.  After
that it will be active in the whole city.  Koschinick has signed the new statute 
for the city, the election agreement and the map of the central administrative 
district agreed in Rome; according to the 1991 census, there were 3,700
inhabitants in the central district: 41 percent Serbs and others [Yugoslavs],
36 percent Bosniaks and 23 percent Croats.  One month after the signing of
the city statute the return of all refugees and displaced persons to their
apartments should be ensured.  Those displaced persons who now live
in Mostar apartments can stay in them until their problem is resolved on the
federal level.<P>

<h2>Gasic Takes Vacation</h2>

Anti-Croatian campaign from the hotel "Ero" [headquarters of the EU city 
administration] has stopped.  Some colleagues see a reason for that in
the fact that Koschnick's spokesperson, Dragan Gasic [a Serb, according to the Croatian "patriotic" press], is on a vacation.
Whatever the reason, the EU administration will stay in Mostar until the
end of the year.  Its mandate was extended for another six months in Rome.
Koschnick says that he faces a new struggle with the Foreign ministers
of the European Union who are supposed to finance the administration
for another six months.  Therefore, a lot has changed in Mostar after Rome.
Nevertheless, Mostar  is still in Rama-Neretva-Hum velezupa [canton].
As the Federal minister of foreign affairs, Dr. Jadranko Prlic, said, 
the solution for Mostar would be closely related to the establishment of
the borders between the velezupas [cantons] in the Bosnian Federation.
Croatian proposal that Ljubuski, Siroki Brijeg and Posusje [Croat majority
towns before the war] are put in the same velezupa with Mostar was not accepted.
Those counties were given an opportunity of forming a separate velezupa
or forming a united velezupa together with Tomislavgrad, Livno, Kupres, 
Glamoc, Drvar and Bosansko Grahovo.<P> 

After these Mostar events, the problems of establishment of Federal structures
in other regions remain.  Another crisis points are in Bugojno, where the return
of Croats has been blocked, and in Vares where Croats are exposed to increasingly
brutal pressures.<P>


<hr><P>
Translated on 7/19/96<P>
<hr>
</FONT>
<A HREF="/info/students/marko/cropat.html"><IMG SRC="/info/students/marko/pictures/
home.gif" ALT="HOME" WIDTH=80 HIGHT=40></a>
<hr>
