<TITLE>HDZ and the opposition cooperate in Croatia</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">


<h1>AGREEMENT ON THE MOST IMPORTANT ASPECTS</h1>

<em><strong>by Branko Tuden</em></strong><P>

<h2>Vecernji List, Zagreb, Croatia, 5/27/96 , page 2</h2>

The government and opposition have not for a long time had
talks in such a tolerant and constructive atmosphere as
during the course of the weekend at the meeting of the
Presidential Council, dedicated to the international
position of Croatia.<P>

The meeting was well prepared, about one hundred
participants and speakers, all well known experts in the
field of contemporary politics, geopolitics and diplomacy,
touched on many themes of critical importance for the future
of Croatia. The quality of the debate was lifted by the
participation of many Croatian diplomats from abroad, who
were also present. It seems that this type of meeting had
not previously been held in the independent Croatian state,
at least not publicly.<P>

The principle reason of the discussion on the international
position of the Republic of Croatia was the postponement of
the acceptance of Croatia into the Council of Europe.
Although an absolute consensus was not reached as to the
reason, the government maintained that it was due to outside
pressure, whilst the opposition said that it was due to
this, but also some domestic mistakes. That which is  most
important, is the following : when the key interests of
Croatia are in question all the important political forces
in the country are in agreement.<P>

That primarily relates to attempts to force Croatia into
associations that would return her to the Balkans, or push
her into federations similar to the one she left with great
sacrifices.<P>

The meeting showed that President Tudman and the Croatian
Democratic Union (HDZ) are not exclusive and arrogant, as is
sometimes ascribed to them, and that the opposition is not a
"natural disaster". Also, that when capriciousness is left
out, talks can be held and agreement reached on all of the
most important questions.<P>

A very positive reaction was given to the stand of Dr
Milorad Pupovac in the name of the Serbian community in
Croatia. It even caused President Tudman in his concluding
comments to refer to the stand taken by Dr Pupovac, and to
emphasise it, as a very positive act.<P>

<hr>
