<a NAME="neum"></a>
used without permission, for "fair use" only<hr>
<FONT SIZE="+1">



<h1>Through Neum Without a Customs Inspection</h1>

<strong><em>D. Knezevic</strong></em><P>

<h2>Vecernji List, Zagreb, Croatia, May 14, 1996</h2>

Croatian citizens as well as foreign tourists who will be
coming to the Croatian Adriatic coast will have the right
to freely pass through the Neum municipality. The Ploce
harbor will be open for the needs of the Bosnia-
Herzegovina Federation. Those are, in a practical sense,
two legal documents which were signed by the Premiers of
Croatia and Bosnia-Herzegovina in Zagreb on Saturday.
They deal with the implementation of the agreement  made
between Croatia and the Bosnia-Herzegovina Federation in
which Croatian passage through Federation territory is
ensured, as is Federation access to the Adriatic. It is
clear that the signing of those documents had certain
political weight because they demonstrate adherence to
the Washington and Dayton Agreements, as well as
favorable economic implications for both countries.<P>

<h2>THE RESTORATION OF ROAD INFRASTRUCTURE</h2>

Guaranteeing unrestricted transit through Neum, as well
as the opening of the Ploce harbor for the needs of the
Bosnia-Herzegovina Federation, will at the same time give
both countries admission to the World Bank so that they
may receive credit for the restoration of road
infrastructure.<P>
Among others, the agreement maintains that the Bosnia-
Herzegovina Federation is to allow trucks and remaining
road vehicles unrestricted entry for the transit of goods
and passengers from Croatia through Neum. Customs
inspections do not apply to vehicles with Croatian
license plates. Those vehicles will not be checked, nor
will official Federation authorities approach them,
unless the driver commits some type of traffic or customs
violation. Meanwhile, Deputy Premier Ljerka Mintas Hodak
estimates that the agreement realizes more than the
agreements in the US resolved because the Croatian side
chose freedom of transit for tourists who are coming to
the Croatian Adriatic coast and wish to pass through
Neum.<P>
In the second agreement, Croatia guarantees Bosnia-
Herzegovina  the unhindered and safe flow of goods
through the customs zone in the Ploce harbor. Goods that
are passing through that harbor on the way from the
Bosnia-Herzegovina Federation
or on the way in, do not pay customs or other dues and do
not file a customs report.<P>

<h2>MEASURES AGAINST BLACK-MARKETEERING</h2>
With that agreement, Croatia is obligated to maintain
land traffic (road and railway) from the harbor to the
border with Bosnia-Herzegovina, and not discriminate
against ships which are sailing for the needs of the
Federation, regardless of their national afiliation.
Since with the legal establishment of freedom of transit
for Neum and Ploce comes the risk of an increase in black-
marketeering, there is a clause built into the agreement
about Ploce in which road transit in and from the the
Federation will proceed with the supervision or
accompaniment of Croatian police. It will be like that
until a separate road from the unrestricted customs zone
to the Bosnia-Herzegovina border is buildt. Similarly, it
is expected that black-marketeering in Neum will be
rendered impossible only when a road is constructed in
which full transit control would be made possible.<P>

The agreements signed last Saturday in Zagreb went into
effect immediately but are considered temporary. Passage
through the Federation should be continuously regulated
by other documents which would control railway as well as
road transit. Likewise, new documents for  permanent
means in the future should be  arranged for Federation
access to the Adriatic. The present agreement does not
apply to goods and destinations in the rest of Bosnia-
Herzegovina.<P>

<hr>

From Croatian-News List
<hr>
</FONT>
<a HREF="/info/students/marko/cropat.html"><IMG SRC="/info/students/marko/pictures/home.gif" ALT="HOME" HIGHT=40 WIDTH=80></a>
