<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - Modern Day Explorers</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">
	
	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	<br>

	<table border=0>
	
	<tr>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/00a.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a></td>
	<br>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<img src="../gfx/002head2.jpg" alt="Modern Day Explorers header gif">
	<p>
	
	
	
	In 1909, a party of prospectors in northern Ontario, Canada, literally stumbled
	on to what would turn into one of the biggest gold finds of the century. One of the
	men slipped and fell, dislodged a piece of moss and found underneath a dome-shaped
	rock structure studded with gold. Hence the name Dome Mines Limited, one of the
	companies which would eventually become Placer Dome Inc. The term "placer" refers
	to water-borne deposits of sand or gravel containing valuable mineral nuggets of
	silver and gold.
	<p>
	
	Until the Second World War, prospectors trenched and scraped their way to most of
	the world's mineral finds. Today, advanced satellite imaging, super sensitive
	electromagnetic testing and the rapid transmission of digital information have
	improved the odds of locating elusive resources.
	<p>

	<img src="../gfx/plantpic.jpg" alt="Cortez contruction jpeg" align=right vspace=10>
	<p>	
	
	<font size=+1>
	<strong>
	<a href="02b.html">
	Primordial Prospectors</a>
	</strong>
	</font>
	<br>
	From our earliest attempts to compete in a world where we were usually at a
	disadvantage, humans have used metals. Prospecting is one of the oldest of our
	activities.
	<p>

	<font size=+1>
	<strong>
	<a href="02c.html">
	Exploration in the Satellite Age</a>
	</strong>
	</font>
	<br>
	During the past 40 years, advances in technology and in the earth sciences
	-- particularly in geology, physics and chemistry -- have brought radical changes
	to mineral exploration methods.
	<p>

	<font size=+1>
	<strong>
	<a href="02d.html">
	The $110 Million Search</a>
	</strong>
	</font>
	<br>
	Many zones of mineralization await discovery beneath the continents and the
	oceans. Placer Dome spends more than $110 million annually on exploration to add
	major gold, silver, copper and molybdenum reserves.	
	<p>	
	
        
	<font size=+1>
	<strong>
	The Sidebars
	</strong>
	</font> 
	<p>

	<a href="02e.html"><li>Minex: New Mines for Old</a>
	<br>
	<a href="02f.html"><li>The Rugged Office</a>
	<p></td>

	</table>

	<p>

	<a name="00">
	<table border=0></a>
	<tr>
	
	<td width=120></td>
	
	<td>
	
	<center>	

	<img src="../gfx/menuba1.gif" alt="Placer Dome footer gif">
