<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Explorers - Exploration by Satellite</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">
	
	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	<br>

	<table border=0>
	
	<tr>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/00a.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a></td>
	<br>
		
	<td valign=top>
	
	<h2>
	Exploration in the Satellite Age
	</h2>
	
	<a href="02a.html">
	Back to "Modern Day Explorers"</a>
	<p>
	
	The primordial prospectors of bygone eras would never recognize or understand
	Placer Dome's eclectic mix of explorationists. Picks and pans have been replaced
	by laptop computers and satellites. Specialists in geology, geophysics,
	geochemistry and information systems are the new trail blazers, working their way
	through data toward the discovery of mineral reserves. Most importantly, they're
	working together. More than anything else, Placer Dome's exploration story is one
	of converging technologies.
	<p>
	
	<img src="../gfx/02satell.jpg" align=right alt="satellite exploration jpeg" hspace=10 vspace=10>

	At Placer Dome, we believe that a "global approach" to exploration is essential to
	the future growth of a successful mining company. With more than 20 exploration
	offices scattered across the globe, our story is inextricably bound to that of
	information technology.
	<p>
	
	<strong>
	What kind of information?
	</strong>
	<p>

	Different scientific approaches, some of them unknown a generation ago, are now a
	normal part of exploration.  New methodologies underly work in the areas of
	geology, geophysics and geochemistry. Combined with digital data management and
	telecommunications systems, it's a new world.
	<p>

	Magnetic, electromagnetic, radio-metric, resistivity, gravity, seismic and
	induced polarization surveys are commonly used to detect mineral deposits.
	Some of this information can now be superimposed on images produced by satellites
	400 miles above the earth's surface that can see through the clouds. These maps-for-the-modern-age can reveal or
	confirm subtle variations not evident to geologists on the surface and not always
	clearly delineated through aerial photography.
	<p>

	<strong>
	Moving the sun around
	</strong>
	<p>
	
	In still another advance made possible by satellites and computers, geologists can
	view large sections of the earth's surface with the features enhanced by shadows
	resulting from the sun's rays. This is not remarkable in itself, except that the
	shadows are there whether the clouds are in the way or not. Furthermore, the
	geologist can have the computer take control of the sun's location, then move the
	sun up or down and all around the image. Each angle reveals different features of
	the surface and provides new clues for exploration people.
	<p>

	Exploration in the satellite age is the application of logical methodology to the
	search for mineral resources, employing specialized personnel and a variety of
	scientific techniques. The geologist formulates a geological concept, on the basis
	of comparison with known deposits and of knowledge of the basic geological
	processes and mineral distribution patterns. Those areas most favorable for the
	particular type of mineralization sought are then selected. Geological,
	geophysical and geochemical studies further delineate areas for more intense
	investigation until a significant anomaly is indicated.
	<p>

	At this point, the program becomes more specific by seeking actual samples.
	Trenching is used if the minerals are reasonably close to the surface; otherwise
	drilling and underground openings are the only ways of obtaining the samples on
	which all further calculations and decisions will be based.
	<p>

	The principle of drilling for samples is simple -- a drill stem, powered at the
	surface, penetrates the rocks of the target area. Samples, in the form of chips or
	core, are recovered for lab analysis. The major expense occurs in moving equipment
	into remote areas and preparing the drill site. Often, miles of road must be built
	or helicopters chartered, months of planning completed (including environmental
	protection) and a self-sustaining camp established before drilling -- to determine
	the size and grade of an anomaly -- can be carried out.
	<p>

	<strong>
	Exploration: No stasis
	</strong>
	<p>
	
	Although exploration is increasingly disciplined, methodical and scientific, one
	thing it will never be -- in the satellite age -- is static.
	<p>

	As the global information highway continues to evolve, new ways of "crunching the
	data" and sharing results will revolutionize Placer Dome's exploration efforts. A
	sophisticated telecommunications network, underway, provides improved means by which to reach a number of specialists in
	a variety of locations quickly.  The result: timely communications and full
	use of our knowledge base.
	<p>

	Many zones of mineralization still await discovery beneath the continents and
	oceans of our globe. Some of them could be richer than than any now known,
	but because they lie at depths beyond the reach of current methods of detection,
	their development depends upon the discovery of new and more imaginative methods
	of exploration.
	<p>

	Within this context, it's easy to see why, at Placer Dome, long-term exploration
	with adequate and consistent funding will continue to be an essential part of the
	company's growth strategy.
	<p></td>
	
	</table>

	<p><br>

	<a name="00">
	<table border=0></a>
	<tr>

	<td width=120></td>

	<td>
	
	<center>	

	<img src="../gfx/menuba1.gif" alt="Placer Dome footer gif">
