<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Explorers - $110 Million Search</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">
	
	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	<br>

	<table border=0>
	
	<td valign=top>
	
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/00a.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a></td>
	<br>
		
	<td valign=top>
	
	<h2>
	The $110 Million Search
	</h2>
	
	<a href="02a.html">
	Back to "Modern Day Explorers"</a>
	<p>
	
	<img src="../gfx/02millio.jpg" align=right alt="geologists viewing ore sample" hspace=10 vspace=5>

	In 1995, Placer Dome spent $110 million on exploration which boosted the
	Corporation's share of estimated gold reserves to 21 million ounces, compared with
	19.8 million ounces a year earlier.
	<p>
	
	The essential purpose of exploration is to find mineral deposits and prove their
	potential as ore. By definition, the term ore means a mineral assemblage that can
	be developed, mined and processed at a profit. Whether a profit can be derived
	from a mineral deposit is dependent on many technical and economic factors. Such
	things as tonnage, grade and metal recovery can be established with considerable
	accuracy and remain relatively fixed.
	<p>

	Economic factors -- metal prices, capital and operating costs, infrastructure,
	transportation and taxation rates -- are constantly changing. In addition,
	changing technology, government legislation and legal and social influences can
	dramatically affect the viability of a potential mine. As a result, what
	constitutes ore varies as to place and time. The mineral industry is extremely
	sensitive to these changes and is continually reviewing international developments
	to determine those areas most favorable for developing economic mineral reserves.
	<p>
	
	Placer Dome's resource evaluations during 1995 were centred mainly on the Cerro
	Crucitas, Costa Rica, and Donlin Creek, Alaska projects and the newly-discovered
	QK Zone at the Detour Lake Mine in Canada. In 1996, intensive drilling
	continued on these properties.
	<p>
	
	The increase in reserves came from additional on-property exploration and from the 
	inclusion of 1.2 million ounces at Musselwhite in Canada and 1.5 million ounces at Cortez
	for the South Pipeline deposit in the United States.
	<p>
	
	The Corporation's share of estimated ore reserves at gold mining operations
	is shown in the following table:
	<p>
	
	<table border=1 cellpadding=2>
	<tr>
	<td colspan=4 align=center>
	<font size=-1>
	(thousands of ounces)</td>
