<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Performer - Healer, Hedge & Adornment</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	<br>

	
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/00a.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	<br>
		
	<table border=0>
	
	<tr>
	
	<td>
	<font size=+2>
	<strong>
	Healer, Hedge and Adornment
	</strong>
	</font>
	<p>	
	
	<a href="01a.html">
	Back to "Lustrous Performer"</a>
	<p>

	Asked to think of gold, most people imagine glittering pendants, rings and
	chains. Or perhaps it's gleaming stacks of bars, looming behind heavily
	armed guards.
	<p>	

	<img src="../gfx/girl1.jpg" alt="cosmetic uses for gold jpeg" align=right vspace=5 hspace=5>
	<p>
	
	Gold is everywhere. You probably wouldn't think of it as microscopic pellets
	pulsing through veins and arteries.  Yet gold fights illnesses. Injection of such
	pellets helps retard prostate cancer in men. Women with ovarian cancer are
	treated with colloidal gold. And because it is biologically benign, biochemists
	use gold to form compounds with complex materials such as proteins to create new
	lifesaving drugs. One experimental new gold compound being tested for use in AIDS
	treatment blocks virus replication in infected cells.
		<p>
	Gold helps to prevent injuries. Gold delivers electricity and heat. It is stored
	in vaults by central banks as a means of monetary control. And it is worn as
	personal adornment in countries around the world.
	<p>		
	
	<h4>
	Five miles to the ounce
	</h4>
		
	If you own an ounce of gold, you might know its current market value. But you
	probably didn't know the same ounce can be drawn into a wire that stretches five
	miles. This metal is completely recyclable and is virtually immune to the effects
	of air, water and oxygen.
	<p>
	An unparalleled combination of physical and chemical properties makes gold 
	invaluable in thousands of common, everyday applications that require perfect
	performance over a long period of time.
	<p>	
	Virtually all reliable electronic products depend on gold to guarantee
	consistent performance. Gold is used in electronic equipment because,
	unlike other metals, it does not tarnish or corrode and is an exceptional
	transmitter of electricity and heat.
	<p>

	<img src="../gfx/golduse.jpg" alt="gold in electronics jpeg" align=left hspace=7 vspace=5>
	<p>

	Gold is found in cameras, videocassette recorders, fax machines, televisions
	and compact discs. Telephones would not provide clear reception over time 
	without gold-coated contacts at key transmission points. And gold is used
	on printed wiring boards of cellular phones to create a pathway which conducts 
	the current.
	<p>
	The wires within camcorders that connect microelectronic circuitry are 
	made of gold. Music lovers also depend on gold for the highest quality
	surface available on compact discs. The 24-karat gold surface resists 
	oxidation, eliminating its potential destruction by moisture.
	<p>
	Computers found in homes and offices use gold in microchips and 
	circuit boards. Modems, printers and other electronic devices all require
	gold.
	<p>
	As one distinguished engineer says, "Gold is absolutely essential when signal 
	purity, conductivity and reliability are required."
	<p></td>
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	<a name="00">
	<table border=0></a>
	
	<tr>

	<td width=120></td>
	
	<td>	
	<img src="../gfx/menuba1.gif" alt="Placer Dome footer gif">
