<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Performer - Ancient Tombs</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	<br>

	
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/00a.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	<br>
		
	<table border=0>
	
	<tr>
	
	<td>
	<font size=+2>
	<strong>
	Ancient Tombs of Gold
	</strong>
	</font>
	<p>	
	
	<a href="01a.html">
	Back to "Lustrous Performer"</a>
	<p>

	As early as 4,000 BC, Egyptian Pharoah Narmer minted the world's first gold bars.
	Valued for its rarity and beauty, gold was believed to have been placed on Earth
	by the Egyptians' sun god. Pharoahs and other royalty were buried with all of their
	golden treasures, in tombs made of gold, believing they would return one day with
	all of their wealth intact.
	<p>	
	
	<img src="../gfx/rawgold.jpg" align=right>
	<p>
	
	<h4>
	The first gold coins
	</h4>
	
	The first gold coins were minted by King Gyges of Lydia around 650 BC. He believed
	raw gold and silver were poor media for the development of trade. Gold became a
	monetary metal, and was valued at 13.33 times the value of silver.	
	<p>
	Around 300 BC, Alexander the Great created the first world-wide currency, the Drachma.
	His Macedonian Empire crumbled, however, when he produced more gold coins than
	useful goods and commodities, triggering the world's first inflation.	

	<h4>
	Empires built on gold
	</h4>
	
	After the Roman Empire was established by Augustus in 27 BC, its rulers raided and
	robbed country after country of gold. Later, the Romans made the mistake of
	"watering down" their gold with other metals, inducing inflation and currency
	depreciation. The Roman Empire fell.
	<p>
	In 325 AD, Byzantium rose from the ashes of Rome, creating a new world power and a
	new world-wide currency, the gold coin Solidus. It retained its worth for nearly
	800 years. Finally, in 1200 AD, the currency was watered down with other base metals
	and the Empire declined.
	
	<h4>
	Power from gold or gold from power?
	</h4>
	
	<img src="../gfx/00gold$.jpg" alt="raw gold jpeg" align=left vspace=5 hspace=5>
	<p>

	During the reign of Queen Elizabeth	I (1533-1603), Sir Francis Drake raised funds
	from the British public to attack the Spanish fleet in open seas. Drake's crew
	returned successfully, its holds laden with gold. As Britain gained dominance of
	seas, gold flowed through the arteries of commerce into its treasuries.  
	<p>	
	In the early 1700's, France experimented with the first paper 
	currency based on gold. This had an international impact until 1821,
	at which time Britain returned to the Gold Standard. In the decades that followed,
	its neighboring partners and the United States also adopted it. In 1914, England
	abandoned the Gold Standard, as did most of its neighbors, due to the escalating
	expenses of World War I. Gold then took on the role of inflation and currency hedge.
	<p>


	The Gold Exchange Standard was established in 1922. This allowed countries to 
	exchange paper currency instead of gold. The end result	was paper currency-based 
	inflation. A global stock market crash occurred seven years later. By 1931, most
	countries were off the Gold Exchange Standard. In 1934, the United States devalued
	the dollar by raising the official price of gold from $20.67/ounce to $35.00/ounce.
	This was the first price change since Sir Isaac Newton established the $20.67/ounce
	price in 1717. As the decades unfolded, the price of gold stayed at $35 while
	the dollar was backed by a smaller and smaller percentage of it.	
	<p>		
	In 1965, the gold reserve requirement was completely removed from the dollar,
	allowing currencies to "float." Again, inflation set in during the 1970s and another
	global stock market crash occurred several years later, in 1987. Now gold trades in a 
	range from $370/oz. to $400/oz.
	<p>
	<li>
	<a href="01a4.html">History of gold repeats itself</a>	
	
	</td>
	</table>
	
	<br><br>
	
	<a name="00">
	<table border=0></a>
	
	<tr>

	<td width=120></td>
	
	<td>	
	<img src="../gfx/menuba1.gif" alt="Placer Dome footer gif">
	<br>
	<center>
	<font size=-1>
	<a href="../02expl/02a.html">
	Explorers</a> |
	<a href="01a.html">
	Performer</a> | 
	<a href="../03world/03a.html">
	One  World</a> |
	<a href="../04prof/04a.html">
	Profile</a> |
	<a href="../07numb/07a.html">
	Numbers</a> |
	<a href="../05tech/05a.html">
	Tools</a> |	
	<a href="../08map/08a.html">
	Sites</a> |
	<a href="../06faq/06a.html">
	FAQ & Glossary</a> |
	<a href="../09latest/09a.html">
	Latest</a>
	<br>
	
	<font size=-1>
