<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Performer - Search for supply</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	<br>

	
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/00a.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	<br>
		
	<table border=0>
	
	<tr>
	
	<td>
	<font size=+2>
	<strong>
	The Search for Supply</a>
	</strong>
	</font>
	<p>
	
	<a href="01a.html">
	Back to "Lustrous Performer"</a>
	<p>
	

	<img src="../gfx/search.jpg" alt="gold brick" align=right hspace=10 vspace=5>
	<p>
	
	The global supply picture in gold mining has changed dramatically. The biggest
	producers of yesteryear, South Africa, Canada, Australia, Russia and the 
	United States, are forecast to show declining or flat production in the 
	future. By contrast, South America is emerging as a new force.
	<p>
	
	Political uncertainty envelops Russia and South Africa. In the United States,
	and to a lesser extent in Canada and Australia, gold mining is being made less
	welcome by the regulatory climate. Canada's gold production is estimated
	to have peaked at 177 tonnes in 1991, and is expected to decline in the next
	eight years.
	<p>
	Canadian gold producers are increasingly taking their expertise and capital
	out of the country to develop mineral deposits offshore. This is shown by a 
	marked decline in total industry exploration spending in Canada -- a trend 
	reflected in Placer Dome's budgets as well.
	<p>
	The trend to invest outside the traditional producing countries will
	continue, particularly in South America, which is becoming the new
	Eldorado. In 1992, Latin America was the only region of the globe to
	show an increase (20%) in industry spending on mineral exploration.
	Placer Dome was at the forefront of this move to Latin America, and
	in Chile, the company already has a major gold and silver mine in
	operation.
	<p>
	Placer Dome was the first in the current wave of North American
	companies to move into gold exploration in Venezuela, where it has a
	major discovery. This success reflects the strategy of focusing on
	geologically attractive yet underdeveloped areas of the world.
	<p>
	In addition to South America, new sources of future supply are
	expected to come from Papua New Guinea, other Asian Pacific Rim
	countries -- especially Indonesia -- as well as West African
	countries like Ghana, as improved accessibility and technology make
	these places viable for gold mining.
	<p></td>


	</table>
	
	<a name="00">
	<table border=0></a>
	
	<tr>

	<td width=120></td>
	
	<td>	
	<img src="../gfx/menuba1.gif" alt="Placer Dome footer gif">
	<br>
	<center>
	<font size=-1>
	<a href="../02expl/02a.html">
	Explorers</a> |
	<a href="01a.html">
	Performer</a> | 
	<a href="../03world/03a.html">
	One  World</a> |
	<a href="../04prof/04a.html">
	Profile</a> |
	<a href="../07numb/07a.html">
	Numbers</a> |
	<a href="../05tech/05a.html">
	Tools</a> |	
	<a href="../08map/08a.html">
	Sites</a> |
	<a href="../06faq/06a.html">
	FAQ & Glossary</a> |
	<a href="../09latest/09a.html">
	Latest</a>
	<br>
	
	<font size=-1>
	<a href="../index.html">
	Home Page</a> |
