<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Performer - Jewelry</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	<br>

	
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/00a.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	<br>
		
	<table border=0>
	
	<tr>
	
	<td>
	<font size=+2>
	<strong>
	Jewelry: Two-Thirds of the World's Gold
	</strong>
	</font>
	<p>

	<a href="01a.html">
	Back to "Lustrous Performer"</a>
	<p>

	Jewelry demand has been described as the cornerstone of the gold market. While
	gold continues to be valued as a solid, long-term investment and is still an
	alternative international currency, the continuing desire of hundreds of millions
	of people to own and wear real gold jewelry is also a key factor in the future
	prosperity of the gold mining industry.
	<p>
	
	<img src="../gfx/piechart.jpg" align=right alt="Gold demand pie chart">
	<p>
	
	Over the past decade, some two-thirds of the newly-mined gold supplied
	to the market has been consumed by purchasers of gold jewelry. For the last four
	years, the amount of gold used in the fabrication of gold jewelry has exceeded the
	entire gold mining output of the Western world.
		<p>
	The motivations for purchasing gold jewelry can vary enormously, depending on
	culture and geography. In the developed markets of the West, it is
	bought primarily for adornment, and often for sentimental reasons; in the 
	developing markets of the Far East and Middle East, it is bought for investment
	as well as adornment.
	<p>
	Developing countries such as China, India, Thailand and Turkey represent
	the fastest growing markets for gold jewelry demand, and now account for 
	some two-thirds of worldwide consumption.
	<p></td>
	
	<tr>
	<td>
	<font size=+2>
	<strong>
	<a name="01">Know Your Karats</a>
	</strong>
	</font>
	<p>
	In the jewelry business, the fineness of gold is expressed in karats,
	also spelled carats. Twenty-four karats corresponds to "fine" or pure gold,
	while 18 karats indicates an alloy consisting of 18 parts pure gold and six
	parts other metal, often copper or silver. In North America, items of 
	jewelry can come in 24K, 22K, 18K, 14K, 9K and even 1K fineness. Karat is not
	to be confused with the carat used as a unit of gemstone weight (0.2 gram),
	as in a 5-carat diamond (1 gram), or with the vegetable, spelled carrot.
	</td>
	</table>
	
	<br><br>
	
	<a name="00">
	<table border=0></a>
	
	<tr>

	<td width=120></td>
	
	<td>	
	<img src="../gfx/menuba1.gif" alt="Placer Dome footer gif">
	<br>
	<center>
	<font size=-1>
