<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>One World - Reclamation</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	<br>

	<table border=0>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/00a.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a></td>
	<br>
	
	<td valign=top>

	<h2>
	Reclamation: Last, But Never Least 
	</h2>
	
	<a href="03a.html">
	Back to "One World"</a>
	<p>

	As large as our planet may be, it's the only one we've got. We've all
	taken "Mother Nature" for granted at one time or another and, if continued, abuses
	will become significant problems for future generations.
	<p>
	
	<img src="../gfx/03reclai.jpg" align=right alt="Bald Mtn. reclamation site" hspace=10 vspace=10>

	It is generally agreed that the increasing stresses placed upon the environment by
	modernization could cause irreparable harm. We've seen it in the extinction of entire
	species, the reduction of vital rain forests and the hole in the ozone
	layer.
	<p>

	Placer Dome predicts the effects of its operations on the
	environment before, during and after its operations. Plans for the decommissioning and
	reclamation process are outlined in mine feasibility studies as part of initial mine
	proposals. Once mines are operational, reclamation activities become an ongoing process
	and may commence as early as the first year of operation.
	<p>

	Upon closure of a facility, land disturbed by mining -- including waste dumps and
	tailings ponds -- must be returned to environmentally acceptable conditions. 
	Reclamation efforts are continued well past the mine's closure to increase the
	likelihood of success.
		<p>

	In recognition of our stewardship of sites where activities have ceased, Placer Dome
	received two Outstanding Reclamation Achievement awards: one for reclamation work
	carried out by its exploration staff in British Columbia and another for site
	rehabilitation at Equity Silver Mines. The latter award was for control of acid rock drainage
	and reclamation of rock piles.
		<p>

	These efforts are made in order to give something back to areas from which
	we've taken. It is our responsibility to remain accountable for our actions during
	and after business ventures. The benefits of such efforts go beyond the local area,
	beyond Placer Dome and even beyond the mining industry. The real winner is the
	environment and all it holds.
	<p></td>
	
	</table>
	
	<p>

		
	<a name="00">
	<table border=0></a>
	<tr>

	<td width=120></td>	

	<td>	
	<img src="../gfx/menuba1.gif" alt="Placer Dome footer gif">
	<br>
	
