<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - The Numbers</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">
	
	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>

	<table boder=0>
	
	<tr>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/02butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a></td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	
	<img src="../gfx/07head.gif" alt="The Numbers header gif">
	<p>
	
    <a href="07a.html">Back to "The Numbers"</a>


	<h2>
	Placer Dome reports improved quarterly performance
	</h2>
	<font size=-1>(all dollar amounts in U.S. currency)</font><P>
	<strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc. today reported a consolidated
	loss for the nine months ended September 30, 1996 of $8 million or
	$0.03 per share, compared with net earnings of $36 million or $0.15
	per share in the corresponding period of 1995.  Third quarter 1996
	earnings were $16 million or $0.07 per share compared with earnings
	of $24 million or $0.10 per share in the year-earlier period.
	
	<p>

	The Corporation improved its gold earnings performance in the third
	quarter compared with the disappointing first half of the year due
	to higher gold production and improved cash operating costs.  Third
	quarter gold operating earnings were $74 million compared with $77
	million in the year-earlier period, and with $41 million and $47
	million in the first and second quarters of 1996.  For the nine
	months, gold earnings were $162 million compared with $175 million a
	year ago.

	<p>

	The loss in the first nine months is attributed to a $43 million
	after tax provision against earnings representing the estimated net
	impact of the accidental escape of mill tailing at the Marcopper
	Mine in the Philippines.

	<p>

	Sales revenues for the first nine months of 1996 were $845 million
	compared with $735 million in 1995, and cash flow from operations
	amounted to $183 million compared with $157 million.  The average
	realized price for gold in the third quarter was $409/oz. and for
	the nine months $408/oz., compared with an average market price of
	$392/oz. in both periods of the prior year.

	<p>
	
	The Corporation's share of gold production for the third quarter was
	503,000 ozs., bringing production for the first nine months of 1996
	to 1,438,000 ozs., 6% higher than in the 1995 period.  Reflecting
	improved operating performance since June 30, the average cash
	production cost in the third quarter was $210/oz., bringing the cash
	cost for the nine months to $233/oz., compared with $246/oz. in the
	first half of 1996 and $215/oz. in the first nine months of 1995.
	
	<p>
	
	Significantly higher gold production compared with the first nine
	months of 1995 was achieved at the Granny Smith Mine in Australia,
	the Dome Mine in Canada and the Cortez and Golden Sunlight mines in
	the United States.
	 
	<p>
	
	Operating earnings from copper for the nine months were $17 million,
	and $5 million for the third quarter.  The average realized price
	for copper in the nine months was $0.92/lb.  Cash production cost
	for copper was $0.57/lb. for the nine months.  At the Zaldvar Mine
	in Chile, the share of production in the nine months was 27,520
	tonnes of cathode copper.  The Osborne Mine in Australia produced
	31,415 tonnes of copper in the first nine months of 1996.
	
	<p>
	
	Construction of facilities at the 60%-owned Cortez Joint Venture in
	the United States is three months ahead of schedule for start-up in
	April 1997 and is expected to be $50 million under budget.  Plant
	buildings have been completed, concrete work is virtually done, and
	structural, mechanical and electrical work is well advanced. 
	Low-grade ore from the deposit is being transferred to heap leach
	areas while stripping of waste is ongoing.  The Corporation
	announced an enhanced production profile for the project with output
	of 675,000 ozs. per year (PDG share 405,000 ozs. per year) during
	the first five years due to higher grade in the early years.  Over
	the 12-year mine life, gold production is forecast to average
	440,000 ozs. per year (PDG share 264,000 ozs. per year) at an
	average cash production cost of $152/oz.  Application has been made
	to the Nevada State Office of the Bureau of Land Management for
	approval of a Plan of Operations to integrate mining and processing
	of ore from the adjoining South Pipeline and Pipeline pits.
	
	<p>
	
	At the 68%-owned Musselwhite gold property in Canada, construction
	of a mine and processing facilities is ahead of schedule and on
	budget.  The goal of erecting and closing in essential structures
	before the onset of winter is expected to be achieved, with cladding
	of buildings currently 80% complete.  Underground development is
	progressing on schedule.  Commissioning of the power supply is
	expected to start in late January 1997 for gold production to
	commence in the second quarter of 1997 at a planned rate of 200,000
	ozs. per year (PDG share 135,000 ozs. per year) at an average cash
	production cost of about $200/oz.
	
	<p>
	
	The Corporation announced a positive development decision on August
	1 regarding the 70%-owned Las Cristinas Mine in Venezuela. 
	Construction will commence with finalization of shareholder and
	financing arrangements currently being negotiated.  The Government
	of Venezuela approved the Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) in
	early October, allowing financing arrangements for the project to be
	advanced.  Plans for the facilities and future reclamation have
	established a new benchmark for proactive environmental protection
	in a wet, tropical setting.  The mine is scheduled to produce gold
	at an average rate of 450,000 ozs. per year (PDG share 315,000 ozs.
	per year) following a two-year construction period.
	
	<p>
	
	The Corporation has completed a new resource estimate for its
	wholly-owned Cerro Crucitas gold property in Costa Rica.  The
	measured and indicated resource is now calculated to be 58 million
	tonnes of material averaging 1.2 grams gold per tonne, containing
	2.2 million ozs. of gold.  Exploration is continuing.
	
	<p>
	
	Drilling of several targets continues at the wholly-owned Donlin
	Creek property in Alaska, where a measured and indicated resource of
	45 million tonnes grading 2.5 grams gold per tonne containing 3.6
	million ozs. of gold has been identified.  Strong evidence is
	emerging of continuity between the main Lewis deposit and adjacent
	areas, Queen, 900 metres north of Lewis, and Rochelieu, 300 metres
	to the west.  Metallurgical testwork is being conducted on the
	dominant gold-bearing refractory material to determine the optimal
	processing options.
	
	<p>
	
	At the Marcopper Mine in the Philippines the Corporation remains
	engaged in repairing the drainage tunnel which caused the major
	escape of mill tailing in March, and in remediation of the river
	environment.  The introduction of concrete grout and heated bitumen
	through drillholes from surface has served to seal the tunnel
	pending the installation of a permanent plug.  Approval is being
	awaited from Philippine authorities and the affected communities to
	take action to remove tailing from the channel of the Boac River. 
	The Corporation is continuing negotiations with the majority
	shareholder of Marcopper with a view to divesting itself of its
	interest.
	
	<p>
	
	The Corporation's share of proven and probable reserves at the
	Porgera Mine in Papua New Guinea increased by 490,000 ozs. to 2.2
	million ozs. at June 30, 1996 following revisions based on
	substantially increased data from exploration drilling in 1996.
	
	<p>
	
	The Corporation tendered its 30.8% interest in Gibraltar Mines
	Limited to a successful take-over bid by Westmin Resources Limited
	of Vancouver for all of the shares of Gibraltar.  A gain of about
	$11 million after currency translation and income tax adjustments
	will be recorded in the fourth quarter.
	
	<p>
	
	For further information:<br>
	Investor Relations - Earl Dunlop - (604) 661-3779<br>
	Media Relations - Hugh Leggatt - (604) 661-1554<br>

	<p>
	
