<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - Mining Primer</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">
	
	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>

	<table border=0>
	
	<td valign=top>
	
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/03butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a></td>
	
	<td valign=top>

	<img src="../gfx/05head.gif" alt="The Tools header gif">
	<p>	
	
	
	
	<h2>
	Nuts & Bolts of a Placer Dome Project
	</h2>
	
	<a href="05a.html">Back to The Tools</a>
	<p>

	After years of drilling, testing, estimating, planning, negotiating and raising
	money, the mine development project is approved. "Let's go," says the Board of
	Directors. "Okay," says the Government and the local community. "Aye, Aye," says
	Placer Dome's in-house Project Development Division.
			<p>
	
	<img src="../gfx/lacoipa.jpg" align=right vspace=3 hspace=5>


	There are essentially two approaches that can be adopted in designing, purchasing
	and constructing a mine and metallurgical processing facility: * Completely design
	the whole installation or major elements and go out for a lump sum tender on
	supply and construction. This has the advantage of known costs at the start point
	but takes a lot more time. * Fast track the project from the time of approval to
	completion.
	<p>

	Placer Dome has elected to proceed on the basis of fast tracking,
	because the sooner we can get a plant into production, the sooner we can reverse
	the flow of cash from going out to coming in. By fast-tracking, we ourselves
	manage the design, engineering, purchasing and construction using in-house
	engineering and management expertise, supplemented by the specialized skills of
	consultants.
	<p>

	<img src="../gfx/millshell.jpg" align=right vspace=3 hspace=5>

	By doing all of our own purchasing, we usually arrange to take delivery at the
	manufacturing plant. We engage a shipping broker to handle shipments, including
	chartering vessels specifically for our project needs.
	<p>

	What are we looking for in our relationship with those providing services and
	equipment? There are three vital elements: Quality/Price, Delivery time, and
	Service.
	<p>

	Starting with Quality/Price, these go hand in hand. You get what you pay for and
	we do not necessarily buy on the basis of the lowest bidder. The other factor is
	that we expect the supplier to make a profit, otherwise he is really not much good
	to us in the long run.
	<p>

	We have, over the years of dealing with people in all aspects of our business,
	developed a knowledge of, and preference for, certain types of equipment and
	manufacturers which have proved to be reliable and have stood the test of time. A
	good product or innovative idea will always sell in the mining business, as ours
	is a wide-open forum for the exchange of operating information and new technology.
	Poor products get widely discussed to warn others of potential pitfalls.
	<p>

	<img src="../gfx/roaster.jpg" align=right vspace=3 hspace=5>

	We have from time to time been involved in the development of equipment with
	suppliers or manufacturers to meet specific needs in our mines, such as the
	introduction of "cherry pickers" at Endako in 1966 for removal of oversize rock
	from the primary crusher - an idea taken from a log loader.
	<p>

	

	The second element, delivery time, requires that we solicit bids very early on for
	items requiring long manufacturing lead times, such as mills, crushers, and
	autoclaves. The delivery of these items usually dictate the project time frame,
	along with seasonal considerations such as winter construction.
	<p>

	The most common shortcoming among suppliers is a lack of consistency between the
	sales department and the production department. Sales wants the order and makes
	optimistic estimates of delivery times. Once the order is placed, they sail off to
	bigger and better things and we find ourselves dealing with a hard-nosed
	production group who have a different shop schedule which does not meet our
	expectations.
	<p>

	To give us some insurance we have introduced penalty clauses for default on
	promised delivery dates.  This often becomes a sore point and has a tendency to
	strain relations when production has any sort of upset. In one instance a pipe
	fabricator was caught in a credit limit situation with his welding supplier which
	was not brought to his or our attention. The net result was that a purchase order
	was not processed and we had a potential three-week delay in taking delivery.
	Fortunately Placer Dome's Purchasing group was able to locate an alternative supply of
	welding supplies which were rush delivered to the pipe fabricator.
	<p>

	Thirdly, with regard to Service, we view most of our suppliers as potentially
	long-term associates who will fill our present as well as future requirements.
	Quite often we run into serious difficulties with a particular piece of equipment
	at the time of installation or during operations and require immediate assistance
	in rectifying the problem.
	<p>

	This is an area where some suppliers excel, because of the close relationship
	established between us, and where they know it is mutually beneficial to solve the
	problem. A supplier has an excellent opportunity to witness first-hand the
	deficiencies of his product in cases such as this and also to contribute to the
	solutions which will ultimately provide him with a better product. Other suppliers
	tend to get bogged down in procedural details and miss the opportunity to provide
	service that counts.
	<p>

	Placer Dome projects cover a wide range of requirements for services, equipment,
	supplies and fabrications. Orders for process equipment for the Porgera project in
	Papua New Guinea, for example, were placed in Australia, North America, Papua New
	Guinea and Germany. Of the North American content, about half the dollar value
	came from British Columbia for tanks, autoclaves and piping.
	<p>

	While North American suppliers currently have an edge in technology, innovation
	and experience, Pacific Rim suppliers are catching up, particularly those closer
	to the project sites, mainly because they can offer competitive labour costs
	related to productivity. We all must consider competitiveness. Trading blocks are
	becoming a fact of life and we must develop ways of working with the Asian block
	and the evolving USA-Mexico block. This may require joint ventures both at home
	and with offshore partners in servicing some of the upcoming projects.
	<p>
			
	</td>

	</table>
	<p>

			
