<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - Mining Primer</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">
	
	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>

	<table border=0>
	
	<td valign=top>
	
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/03butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a></td>
	
	<td valign=top>

	<img src="../gfx/05head.gif" alt="The Tools header gif">
	<p>	


	<h2>
	A New Way of Mining
	</h2>
	
	<a href="05a.html">Back to The Tools</a>
	<p>


<img src="../gfx/foxnativ.jpg" align=right vspace=3 hspace=5>


	Significant gold values were discovered 500km north of Thunder Bay, Ontario, near
	Opapimiskan in 1973. Since then, there has been a wide array of explorations and
	studies of the proposed mine to determine the effects it could have upon the
	region's people and environment. With completion scheduled for 1997, the
	Musselwhite project is a modern mine that is designed to address modern concerns.
	The Musselwhite Project, owned by Placer Dome Canada and TVX Gold, includes a mill
	fed by an underground mine and a small open pit. The total capital investment is
	about $250 million, generating 500 construction jobs and 282 positions when the mine
	is in full operation. Workers will travel by air to the mine from local First
	Nations communities and Thunder Bay.
	<p>

<h3>
Our Shared Vision for Musselwhite
</h3>

<strong>
1. Planning and Design
</strong>
<p>

The water, vegetation, fish, amphibians, birds and mammals in the Musselwhite area were carefully studied to determine the effects of the mine.
Musselwhite's design will ensure that:
<p>

<ul>
<li type=bullet>water quality in the rivers and lakes will continue to meet provincial standards during and following mine operation;
<li type=bullet>air emissions will be minimal;
<li type=bullet>the small amounts of fish habitat lost to tailing and polishing ponds will be replaced;
<li type=bullet>metal levels in fish will remain low;
<li type=bullet>there is limited temporary displacement of vegetation and wildlife; and
<li type=bullet>the land will be revegetated and returned as near to its original state as feasible.
</ul>
<p>

<strong>
2. Operation
</strong>
<p>

<img src="../gfx/123musel.jpg" align=right vspace=3 hspace=8>

	The project includes state-of-the-art engineering of effluent treatment, spill
	containment and air emission control. The gold will be recovered using an easily
	destroyed cyanide solution. Rock will be washed and treated to reduce contaminants
	to safe levels before it is deposited in a tailing pond.  
	<p>
	Potential increases in the harvesting of fish and wildlife will be minimized by
	limiting travel by employees and contractors, implementing a catch-and-release
	policy for fish and banning firearms on the property.
	<p>
	
<strong>
3. Closure
</strong>
<p>

Following closure, about 2010, Placer Dome Canada will accelerate its restoration efforts by:
<p>

<ul>
<li type=bullet>removing all structures, equipment, and materials;
<li type=bullet>establishing soil conditions conducive to plant life as well as stabilizing landscape, soil and other organic materials.;
<li type=bullet>contouring and replanting disturbed area with jack pine seedlings;
<li type=bullet>re-establishing natural drainage systems;
<li type=bullet>creating new fish habitat in the open pit and constructing a marsh;
<li type=bullet>ensuring no increase in metal/pollutant levels in wildlife or drinking water;
<li type=bullet>obstructing access road and removing bridges to limit use;
<li type=bullet>removing dams, re-establishing wetlands in treatment pond and creating new wetlands in the tailing pond and open pit; and 
<li type=bullet>monitoring the ecosystem for a minimum of five years after closure. 
</ul>
<p>

	Upon completion, vegetation will cover the site, a wide range of wildlife will
	return and  new small lakes will be established in the open pit and tailing pond.
	<p>

<strong>
An Historic Agreement: Local People, Local Concerns
</strong>
<p>

	The Musselwhite project is located on the traditional lands of the Windigo,
	Shibogama and Mishkeegogamang First Nations. First Nations elders identified a birth
	site, a spirit site and a burial site to be preserved in the area. Archaeological
	studies have been conducted for the minesite, powerline and road areas to ensure
	other culturally significant sites will not be disturbed. The social and
	environmental effects on the area bands and the people living in local communities
	were compiled through public consultation, meetings and reports prepared by the
	First Nations. Preserving the environment and heritage of the Musselwhite Project
	area is the overriding concern of the First Nations people, as well as ensuring that
	local residents receive economic and quality-of-life benefits from the mine. These
	concerns led to the signing of the Musselwhite Agreement in 1992. This accord
	between Placer Dome Canada, TVX Gold, the First Nations, Province of Ontario and
	Government of Canada is a step forward in the relationship between the mining
	industry and the aboriginal community. The Musselwhite Agreement defines how First
	Nations will benefit from the mine, provides a strategy to minimize any possible
	negative effects and establishes commitments to protect the environment. First
	Nations and Placer Dome Canada, will continue working together through the
	Musselwhite Co-ordinating Management Committee and the Public Liaison Committee
	about any aspects of the project that may be affecting local residents, fish or
	wildlife.
	<p>

<strong>
The Placer Dome Commitment
</strong>
<p>

	Studies, planning and working with local residents make the Musselwhite Project an
	example of the Placer Dome vision. Every Placer Dome project is
	examined from a profit/loss and an environmental perspective. A clean, healthy
	environment is in the best interests of the mining industry because it is in the
	best interests of everyone. Placer Dome and its partners take every precaution
	available to ensure our projects have a positive impact on all of our stakeholders
	while limiting the effects on the natural environment. We are committed to success
	through responsibility.
	<p>

<strong>
Our Environment, Our Responsibility
</strong>
<p>

	Placer Dome is one of the country's leading gold mining companies. Our
	success depends on our reputation. We are responsible, not only to our shareholders,
	but also to the people and the environment wherever we operate. It is not a
	responsibility we take lightly. The mining industry has changed forever the way it
	does business and Placer Dome is leading the way with its Musselwhite
	Project. Not only does the Musselwhite Project include a plan for opening and
	ongoing operations, our strategy for closing the mine will revitalize the land and
	limit environmental impacts. The care taken by Placer Dome will return the
	area to a bio-diverse state and allow the traditional pursuits of the First Nations
	people to continue for generations.
	<p>

	</td>

	</table>
	<p>

			
