<HEAD>
<TITLE>Sites - Detour Lake Mine</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">
	
	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>

	<table border=0>
	<tr>

	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/04butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a></td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<img src="../gfx/08head.gif" alt="The Sites header gif">
	<p>
	
	
	<a href="08a.html">
	Back to Sites Map</a>
	<p>

	<img src="../gfx/detourb.jpg" align=right alt="Detour Lake Mine" vspace=10 hspace=10>







	<font size=+2>
	<strong>
	Detour Lake Mine
	</strong>
	</font>
	<br>
	
	The Detour Lake underground gold mine is located in northeastern
	Ontario, Canada. The mine was brought into production by open pit mining in
	August 1983 which continued until May 1987. Startup of underground
	mining was progressive with major production starting in December
	1987.

	<p>
	
	<strong>
	Ownership Interest
	</strong><br>
	100%
	<p>

	<strong>
	Location
	</strong><br>
	200 kilometres northeast of Timmins, Ontario. Northeastern corner of Ontario.
	<p>

	<strong>
	Production
	</strong><br>
	Production in 1995 was 121,393 ounces of gold. From the start of
	operations in 1983, 1,334,358 ounces of gold has been produced.

	<p>

	<strong>
	Production Costs
	</strong><br>
	The 1995 cash cost was $368 per ounce of gold
	and the total cost was $440 per ounce of gold. The 1995 cash cost is
	broken down as follows: mine (58%), mill (19%), plant (6%) and other
	(17%).

	<p>

	<strong>
	Processing Plant
	</strong><br>
	Cyanidation and the carbon-in-leach (CIL) process to recover gold
	which is refined into dor&#233 on site. Mill throughput in 1995
	was 2,700 tonnes per day.

	<p>

	<strong>
	Ore Reserves
	</strong><br>
	The proven and probable ore reserves at
	December 31, 1995 contained 503,000 ounces of gold in 3,191,000
	tonnes of ore grading 4.9 g/t gold.

	<p>

	<strong>
	Mine Life 
	</strong><br>
	Three years at December 31, 1995 (based on the present ore reserves).
	Upgrading of mineralization to reserves in future is expected to add
	a further five or more years.

	<p>

	<strong>
	Mining Method
	</strong><br>
	Underground
	<p>

	<strong>
	Mineralization
	</strong><br>
	At December 31, 1995, the measured and
	indicated mineralization contained 76,000 ounces of gold in 276,000
	tonnes of material grading 8.6 g/t gold. 

	<p></td>
	
	</table>
	<p>

			
	<a name="00">
	<table border=0></a>
	<tr>

	<td width=120></td>
		
	<td>	

	<img src="../gfx/menuba1.gif" alt="Placer Dome footer gif">
	<br>
	<center>
