<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Sites - Osborne Mine</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">
	
	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>

	<table border=0>
	<tr>

	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/04butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a></td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<img src="../gfx/08head.gif" alt="The Sites header gif">
	<p>
	
	
	<a href="08a.html">
	Back to Sites Map</a>
	<p>
	
	<img src="../gfx/osborne.jpg" alt="Osborne Mine" align=right vspace=10 hspace=5>
	<p>




	<font size=+2>
	<strong>
	Osborne Mine
	</strong>
	</font>
	<br>
	
	The Osborne copper-gold mine is located in the state of Queensland in northeastern
	Australia. Construction of a one-million tonnes-per-year open pit and underground
	mine started in June 1994 and was completed over 11 months with one month
	allocated for commissioning. Full production commenced in August 1995 and at year
	end, copper production, recoveries and mill throughput were running ahead of plan.
	Open pit mining was completed in February 1996 and will supply ore to the mill
	until late 1996. Following the open pit mining operation, ore production will come
	from the underground operation which is now being developed. Underground mining
	will start in 1996 and continue for 10 years. Capital cost to date is $120 million
	and $50 million remains to be spent on underground development.
	<p>
	
	<strong>
	Ownership Interest
	</strong><br>
	75.4%
	<p>

	<strong>
	Location
	</strong><br>
	North-central Queensland, Australia. About 195 kilometres southeast of the inland
	city of Mt. Isa, and 720 kilometres west-southwest of the coastal city of
	Townsville.
	<p>

	<strong>
	Capital Costs
	</strong><br>
	The construction cost estimate to date is $120 million and includes the cost of
	open pit mine stripping, warehouse inventory and project commissioning.
	<p>


	<strong>
	Production
	</strong><br>
	Production in 1995 was 15,180 tonnes (33,466,000 pounds) of copper and 17,428
	ounces of gold. Total production is estimated to be 324,000 tonnes (715 million
	pounds) of copper and 416,000 ounces of gold over the original 11.5 year mine
	life.
	<p>

	<strong>
	Production Costs
	</strong><br>
	(including royalties): The 1995 cash cost was $0.41 per pound of copper and the
	total cost was $0.70 per pound of copper. The average cash cost over the original
	life of the mine is estimated to be $0.63 per pound of copper and the average
	total cost is estimated to be $0.81. Copper production costs are calculated by
	subtracting gold credits from operating costs.
	<p>

	<strong>
	Processing Plant
	</strong><br>
	The treatment plant includes a small gyratory crusher, a secondary cone crusher, a
	rod mill/ball mill grinding circuit, a copper flotation circuit and a circuit for
	additional gold recovery by pyrite/gold flotation and leach/carbon-in-pulp
	processing. Mill throughput in 1995 was 2,400 tonnes per day and for 1996, is
	estimated at 2,700 tonnes per day.
	<p>

	<strong>
	Ore Reserves
	</strong><br>
	The proven and probable ore reserves at December 31, 1995
	contained 319,912 tonnes (706 million pounds) of copper and 419,000 ounces of gold
	in 10,832,000 tonnes of ore grading 2.956% copper and 1.2 g/t gold.
	<p>

	<strong>
	Mine Life 
	</strong><br>
	11 years at December 31, 1995.
	<p>

	<strong>
	Mining Method
	</strong><br>
	Open pit and underground
	<p>

	<strong>
	Mineralization
	</strong><br>
	At December 31, 1995 the measured and indicated
	mineralization contained 7,454 tonnes (16 million pounds) of copper and 9,000
	ounces of gold in 475,000 tonnes of material grading 1.570% copper and 0.6 g/t
	gold.
	<p></td>
	
	</table>
	<p>

			
	<a name="00">
	<table border=0></a>
	<tr>

	<td width=120></td>
		
	<td>	

	<img src="../gfx/menuba1.gif" alt="Placer Dome footer gif">
