<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Sites - Zald&#237;var Mine</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">
	
	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>

	<table border=0>
	<tr>

	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/04butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a></td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<img src="../gfx/08head.gif" alt="The Sites header gif">
	<p>
	
	
	<a href="08a.html">
	Back to Sites Map</a>
	<p>
	
	<img src="../gfx/zaldavar.jpg" alt="Zaldivar Mine" align=right vspace=10 hspace=10>
	<p>


	<font size=+2>
	<strong>
	Zald&#237;var Mine
	</strong>
	</font>
	<br>
	
	The Zald&#237;var open pit copper mine is located in northern Chile.
	Construction of the processing plant was completed on schedule in
	May 1995 and the first cathodes were produced in June. Commissioning
	of the plant began in June and commercial production was delayed
	from August to November 1995 due to required modifications to some
	process equipment. The capital cost of the project was within budget
	at approximately $600 million.


	<p>
	
	<strong>
	Ownership Interest
	</strong><br>
	50%
	<p>

	<strong>
	Location
	</strong><br>
	Northern Chile. Approximately 1,400 kilometres north of Santiago and 175
	kilometres southeast of Antofagasta.

	<p>

	<strong>
	Production
	</strong><br>
	Production in 1995 was 19,914 tonnes (43,904,000 pounds) of cathode
	copper. Copper production is estimated to be 2.0 million tonnes
	(4,400 million pounds) of cathode copper over the 20-year mine life.

	<p>

	<strong>
	Production Costs
	</strong><br>
	The 1995 cash cost was $0.72 per pound of copper and the total cost
	was $1.01 per pound of copper. Over the 22 year mine life, the
	average cash cost is expected to be $0.49 per pound of copper and
	the average total cost is expected to be $0.67 per pound of copper.

	<p>

	<strong>
	Processing Plant
	</strong><br>
	Heap leaching followed by SX-EW is the treatment
	process for recovering copper. This process will produce readily
	saleable cathode Grade A copper.

	<p>

	<strong>
	Ore Reserves
	</strong><br>
	The proven and probable ore reserves at
	December 31, 1995 contained 2,790,436 tonnes (6,152 million pounds)
	of copper in 293,730,000 tonnes of ore grading 0.95% total
	copper and 0.34% acid soluble copper. Total copper comprises
	acid soluble (oxide) copper plus sulphide copper. The acid soluble
	copper or extent of oxidation determines upon which heap leach pile
	the ore will be treated.

	<p>

	<strong>
	Mine Life 
	</strong><br>
	Twenty years at December 31, 1995. Mining will be completed in year 20
	and leaching operations will continue for an additional two years.

	<p>

	<strong>
	Mining Method
	</strong><br>
	Open pit
	<p>

	<strong>
	Mineralization
	</strong><br>
	The measured and indicated mineralization
	contained 1,277,172 tonnes (2,816 million pounds) of copper in
	311,505,000 tonnes of material grading 0.41% total
	copper and 0.11% acid soluble copper. 

	<p></td>
	
	</table>
	<p>

			
	<a name="00">
	<table border=0></a>
	<tr>

	<td width=120></td>
		
