<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - Archives</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">
	
	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>

	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/07butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0
	align=left ismap></a>
		
	<table border=0>
	
	<tr>
	
	<td>
	
	<h2>
	From Lae Into the Blue 
	</h2>
	
	<strong>
	Placer's role in the search for Amelia Earhart
	</strong>
	<p>
	
	<a href="11a.html">Back to The Archive</a>
	<p>
	
		
	"At 10.00 a.m. the machine was taken off, the actual take-off being satisfactory for
	a loaded machine - the run taken was approximately 850 yards."
	<p>

	<img src="../gfx/amelia.jpg" align=right vspace=3 hspace=5>

	It was July 2, 1937 at Lae, New Guinea.  The silvery Lockheed Electra, its extra fuel
	tanks brimming with gasoline, sank away over the sea, before disappearing from sight
	bound for Howland Island en route to Honolulu across the broad Pacific. With Amelia
	Earhart at the controls and navigator Fred Noonan in the aft cabin, they set off on
	the most dangerous leg of their round-the-world flight, the first attempted by a
	woman pilot. The watching pilots praised the handling of the aircraft on take-off
	with such a heavy load. It was the last they, or anyone else, would see of Lockheed
	NR16020 and its famous aviators.
	<p>

	

	"As the machine was leaving the ground the following weather reports were received at
	the Lae Wireless Station: `EARHART LAE ACCURATE FORECAST DIFFICULT ACCOUNT LACK OF
	REPORTS YOUR VICINITY. CONDITIONS APPEAR GENERALLY AVERAGE OVER ROUTE NO MAJOR STORM
	APPARENTLY PARTLY CLOUDY WITH DANGEROUS LOCAL RAIN SQUALLS ABOUT 300 MILES EAST OF
	LAE AND SCATTERED HEAVY SHOWERS REMAINDER OF ROUTE ...  -  FLEET BASE PEARL
	HARBOUR'".
	<p>

	The quoted words are from a previously unpublished report in Placer Dome's possession
	relating to Amelia Earhart's stopover in Lae, which was at that time the jumping off
	point for Placer's Bulolo gold dredging operations, just as today it is the port of
	supply for the Porgera Mine. The report was written by Eric Chater, General Manager
	of Guinea Airways at Lae, three weeks after Earhart's departure, when a U.S. Navy
	search had turned up no trace of the flyers. Earhart and Noonan and their
	twin-engined plane had vanished. Now the Bureau of Air Commerce in Washington was
	asking for help in obtaining information about Earhart's departure. They cabled
	Placer.
	<p>

	<img src="../gfx/documnt1.jpg" align=right vspace=3 hspace=5>

	Bulolo, which in 1937 had been operating for five years, had been established by a
	massive airlift of dredging equipment over the mountains of New Guinea from Lae.
	Because of Bulolo, Lae was an outpost of aviation, served by Guinea Airways. That
	is why W.T. Miller of the Bureau of Air Commerce made a request to Frank Griffin
	of Placer Management Limited in San Francisco for "information of interest
	relative to Miss Earhart's visit and flight... for Government official record
	purposes." Griffin cabled Chater, who replied by telegram and followed up with an
	eight-page letter. 	
	<p>

	The original letter, carefully typed on Guinea Airways Limited notepaper, has been
	found, with the telegrams that requested it, in a file of correspondence marked
	"Bulolo Gold Dredging, Ltd./ Amelia Earhart" in Placer Dome's basement storage in
	Vancouver.
	<p>

	The disappearance of Earhart and Noonan has become one of aviation history's great
	enigmas, embroidered with fanciful theories about their fate and the subject of at
	least 30 books. The circumstances of their disappearance remain the most intensively
	researched mystery in aviation.
	<p>

	Today, foremost among the researchers is The International Group for Historic
	Aircraft Recovery (TIGHAR), who in a 1989 search of a remote Pacific island thought
	to have been Earhart's last landfall, discovered an aluminum navigator's bookcase
	consistent with the type that would have been aboard Earhart's plane.  In March 1992
	TIGHAR announced that after another sand-sifting search on the same island, it had
	found a piece of aluminum sheet likely to have been part of the underside of the
	Lockheed, as well as remains of a shoe and a medicine bottle cap which may have been
	Earhart's.
	<p>



	Placer Dome contacted TIGHAR in December 1991 about the Earhart file in the Company's
	storage and received the following reply from Richard Gillespie, Executive Director
	of the organization based in Wilmington, Delaware.
	<p>

	"This (Chater's report to the Bureau of Air Commerce) is an important, and as far as
	we know unpublished, piece of historical documentation which sheds important new
	light on the Earhart disappearance. Of particular interest are confirmation of the
	fuel load carried, and the fact that Earhart made an unsuccessful attempt to test her
	radio direction finder prior to that flight. Many other details contained in the
	report fill in gaps in our understanding of just what happened and why. Your
	vigilance and awareness in bringing forth this document is to be commended and we
	greatly appreciate Placer Dome's generosity in making it available to TIGHAR."
	<p>

	At a time when aircraft exploits gripped the popular imagination the way space travel
	would do to a later generation, Amelia Earhart was the first woman to attempt to fly
	around the world and the first person to try to do so around the equator. She was
	already the first woman to fly solo across the Atlantic Ocean and she held other
	aviation records. On radio, on movie newsreels and in the Herald Tribune, to which
	she sent dispatches of her progress, people around the world followed the stages of
	her journey with the same sense of history-in-the-making as attended Neil Armstrong's
	Apollo mission to the moon.
	<p>

	Starting at Oakland, California, she headed to Miami, Florida, where she announced
	she was making an around-the-world attempt and prepared her plane for the journey.
	She took off on June 1, 1937 bound for South America. During June she travelled
	eastward in stages, to Africa, India, Java, the top end of Australia, and landed at
	Lae on June 29. Earhart planned to refuel at Howland Island, fly on to Hawaii and
	then to arrive in Oakland from Honolulu to complete her circumnavigation on the
	Fourth of July. It was not to be.
	<p>

	<img src="../gfx/documnt2.jpg" align=right vspace=3 hspace=5>



	Her navigator, Fred Noonan, who had pioneered Pan American Airways routes across the
	Pacific Ocean, was acknowledged as one of the best aviation navigators of his day.
	But according to a reconstruction of the flight from Lae by TIGHAR, it was a
	combination of navigation and wireless problems that caused their disappearance.
	<p>

	Howland Island is on the equator, a speck of land in the immensity of the Pacific
	Ocean. It is 2,500 miles from Lae and over half way to Honolulu, making it an ideal
	refuelling point. As confirmed in Placer's document, Earhart had 1,100 U.S. gallons
	of fuel aboard. The flight to Howland Island was estimated to take about 18 hours and
	Earhart had fuel aboard for about 25 hours flying, a safe margin. But navigating that
	distance across trackless ocean to make a landfall was like trying to sink a 100-mile
	putt. There was little margin for error. This was the first over-water part of the
	trip that did not involve approaching a large land mass.
	<p>

	The first third of the flight went as planned and, as Placer's report bears out,
	communication with New Guinea was normal. According to the report:
	<p>

	"Arrangements had been made between the plane and Lae station to call at 18 minutes
	past each hour and arrangements made to pass any late weather information, but local
	interference prevented signals from the plane being intelligible until 2.18 p.m. The
	Lae operator heard the following on 6210KC - `HEIGHT 7,000 FEET SPEED 140 KNOTS' and
	some remark concerning `LAE' then `EVERYTHING OKAY'. The plane was called and asked
	to repeat position but we still could not get it. The next report was received at
	3.19 p.m. on 6210KC - `HEIGHT 10,000 FEET POSITION 150.7 EAST 7.3 SOUTH CUMULUS
	CLOUDS EVERYTHING OKAY'. The next report received at 5.18 p.m. `POSITION 4.33 SOUTH
	159.7 EAST HEIGHT 8,000 FEET OVER CUMULUS CLOUDS WIND 23 KNOTS'"
	<p>

	That was the last Lae heard of Amelia Earhart. But she was on course for Howland.
	That night a radio station on the island of Nauru heard her, and a crewman standing
	watch aboard a freighter putting in to port at Nauru heard the plane pass overhead.
	The final exchange of signals before the disappearance took place between Earhart and
	the U.S. Coastguard cutter Itasca, standing by off Howland Island to provide radio
	signals so that Earhart could use her radio direction finder to locate the island,
	and then to chase the birds off the runway when it came time for her to land.
	<p>

	The last signal heard by Itasca was "WE ARE ON LINE 157 337. WILL REPEAT MESSAGE. WE
	WILL REPEAT NORTH AND SOUTH THIS ON 6210 KILOCYCLES. WE ARE RUNNING ON LINE.
	LISTENING 6210 KILOCYCLES."
	<p>

	In air navigation terminology, "running on line" describes the accepted procedure for
	finding a destination when a pinpoint landfall has not been made. Earhart flew the
	Lockheed on a north-south line that ran through the Howland Island destination. She
	and her navigator did not know whether they were north or south of Howland Island, so
	they would run up and down the line until they found it. If they were north of
	Howland and they ran south they would see it; but if they were south of Howland and
	turned south they would miss it. The TIGHAR reconstruction speculates that,
	tragically, within only a 100-mile radius of Howland Island, they turned south
	instead of north, and because they were already south of the island missed it, and
	ran out of fuel before they could retrace the line northward.
	<p>

	In the report in Placer Dome's possession, Eric Chater concludes: "Miss Earhart and
	Captain Noonan spent a considerable time in the radio office and as previously
	mentioned it was learned that neither of them could read morse at any speed but could
	only distinguish letters made individually slowly and repeated often; in that case
	their direction finding apparatus would be useless or misleading unless they were
	taking a bearing on a station using a radiophone which could give the station
	position on voice. We understand the Itasca was to do this but if the plane was
	unable to pick up the Itasca it is doubtful if the direction finder would be any use
	to her."
	<p>

	In its editions of Saturday, July 3, 1937, the San Francisco Chronicle reported: "In
	what is surely one of the loneliest spots in this world, tousle-haired Amelia
	Earhart, America's first lady of the air, last night was down on a shark-infested
	ocean in a big, graceful airplane rendered useless by lack of gasoline."
	<p>

	A search fleet of seven U.S. ships, assisted by aircraft, failed to locate any trace
	of the Lockheed or crew. Adding further poignancy to the disappearance were reports
	of distress signals being heard with the Lockheed's call sign for three days after
	the disappearance. For the aircraft to have operated its transmitter, it would have
	had to run its starboard engine equipped with the generator. This means the plane
	would have had to have been on land in a wheels-down position for the propeller to
	turn.
	<p>

	Based on searches of Earhart's likely landfall, TIGHAR speculates that the plane
	ditched at Gardner Island, now called Nikumaroro and part of the Republic of
	Kiribati, south of Howland Island and on the same line of bearing as Howland. Earhart
	probably set the plane down on a flat beach area while the tide was out. With the
	tides, the Lockheed was floated and swept progressively over the edge of the coral
	reef into deep water offshore. No one knows for sure, 55 years later, what happened
	to the plane, or its brave aviators.
	<p>

	<font size=+1>
	<strong>
	"STAY TUNED"
	</strong>
	</font>
	<p>

	In today's world of the Internet, global TV, cellular phones and satellite navigation, it is hard
	to imagine the rudimentary nature of morse code, wireless and radio direction finder
	used by the flyers of the 1930s to keep in touch and find their way.
	<p>

	Amelia Earhart's Lockheed had two ways of transmitting and receiving messages: morse
	code, which neither she nor her navigator Fred Noonan could read, and voice radio on
	only two frequencies. Unlike the VHF (Very High Frequency) and UHF (Ultra High
	Frequency) signals used in aviation today, Earhart's transmissions were "bounced" off
	the ionosphere, making them susceptible to variables such as day and night, weather
	and sunspot activity. Hence the difficulty of keeping in touch. In the last hours
	before her disappearance, guidance from the ground was inadequate because either she
	could not hear the ground station, or they could not hear her.
	<p>

	The navigation technique for finding a tiny island on a large ocean was to use
	celestial navigation (working out a position from the sun or the stars) and using
	radio direction finding for the final run-in. Celestial navigation requires precise
	timekeeping because the sun and stars change position with the passage of time.
	Navigators' clocks had to be set at the correct time before departure and for this
	they depended on radio time signals.
	<p>

	The report in Placer Dome's possession describes how Earhart and Noonan's departure
	from Lae was delayed one day while they listened for a radio time signal, eventually
	from Adelaide, South Australia, to set the four clocks they had on board. Next
	morning they checked their clocks again, this time on an 8 a.m. signal from Saigon,
	and "expressed their complete satisfaction and decided to leave at 10 a.m."
	<p>

	The 10 a.m. take-off was carefully set to minimize the confusion involved in crossing
	not only two and a half time zones to get to Howland Island but the international
	dateline as well. Ten a.m. July 2 in Lae was 00.00 Greenwich Mean Time, so the
	flight's elapsed time would correspond to the GMT hour. Earhart and Noonan lost
	contact with ground stations at 20 hours and 15 minutes into the flight, which means
	it was 20.15 GMT, or 8.45 a.m. July 2 at Howland Island.
	<p>

	The radio direction finder navigation technique was based on a loop antenna fixed
	above the Lockheed's cockpit. Upon receiving a signal from the ground station, the
	pilot would slowly rotate the antenna. Because of its circular shape, a pronounced
	fade in the signal, known as a "null", would be heard by the pilot when the loop was
	oriented edgewise to the source of the signal. The loop was geared to a compass rose
	in the cockpit. When the pilot "got a minimum" (i.e. the "null") the pointer on the
	compass gave a relative bearing to the station.
	<p>

	The Placer Dome document reveals that when Earhart was at Lae, she carried out a
	30-minute air test of the direction finder. The Lae operator was requested by voice
	to send a long dash while Earhart "endeavoured to get a minimum" on her direction
	finder. "On landing Miss Earhart informed us that she had been unable to obtain a
	minimum and that she considered this was because the Lae station was too powerful and
	too close," wrote Eric Chater in the report.
	<p>

	In the critical final hours of her flight near Howland Island, one of Earhart's last
	messages said she was "unable to get a minimum". The ground station's direction
	finder could not home in on Earhart's frequency. This time it was not a test, with
	tragic results.
	<p>


	
	</td>
	<p>
	
		
		
	</table>
	
