<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - The Latest</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	
	<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/06butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	</td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<table border=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top colspan=2>
	<img src="../gfx/09head.gif" alt="The Latest header gif">
	</td>
	
	
	<tr>
	<td>
	

    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	
    <h2>Placer Dome welcomes acceptance by Highlands Gold</h2>
	
    <strong>January 23, 1997</strong>
    
    <p>

     <strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc. welcomes the announcement made
     today by Highlands Gold Limited that its Directors strongly recommend
     acceptance of Placer Dome's A$0.75 per share offer for all of the
     shares of Highlands Gold.  Highlands Directors have indicated that
     they will accept the offer for their own holdings.
    <p>
        Placer Dome looks forward to pursuing the proposed spin-off of
     Highlands Pacific Limited from Highlands Gold (see attached
     information) for the benefit of shareholders who have accepted the
     offer and those who plan to accept the offer.
    <p>
        "This deal satisfies everyone," John Willson, President and CEO,
     said.  "Highlands shareholders now have no reason not to follow their
     Directors' recommendation to accept our offer."  Placer Dome is
     entitled to 61.7% of Highlands Gold and has received undertakings to
     accept its offer from Papua New Guinea institutions which hold a
     further 12.3%.  Placer Dome has agreed to extend its offer to
     Saturday, February 8, 1997.


    <p>
    For further information:<br>
    Investor Relations: Earl Dunlop (604) 661-3779<br>
	Media Relations: Hugh Leggatt (604) 661-1554<br>
       
    <p>
    <hr align=center width=40%>
    <p>
	
     Text of statements by Highlands Gold
     Limited and Deputy Prime Minister and the Minister for Finance
     of Papua New Guinea.
 

     <h3>From Highlands Gold:</H3>
    
     <strong>Highlands and Placer agree to terms of restructuring</strong><p>
     <strong>Placer's offer extended to February 8, 1997</strong><p>
     <strong>Highlands board recommends Placer's offer</strong><p>
   <p>
   <strong>January 23, 1997</strong>
   <p>
        Highlands Gold and Placer today announced that they have reached
     agreement on the terms of a restructuring of Highlands Gold, including
     the formation of a new company, Highlands Pacific Limited, which is to
     hold the non-Porgera assets of Highlands Gold.
 <p>
        Under the revised proposal, which has Placer's full support, all
     Highlands Gold shareholders who accept Placer's offer will receive for
     each Highlands Gold share held $0.75 in cash, and it is proposed that
     they will participate in a renounceable entitlements issue to acquire
     shares in Highlands Pacific.  The precise terms of the proposed issue
     are yet to be determined.  It is proposed that shareholders who have
     already accepted Placer's offer also receive the entitlements to
     acquire Highlands Pacific shares.
 <p>
        It is intended that the restructuring will be effected at the
     conclusion of Placer's offer (now scheduled to close on 8 February
     1997) and will incorporate the following key features:
 <p>
     <li>Highlands Pacific will acquire the non-Porgera assets of
     Highlands Gold for a cash payment of approximately A$107 million
     (subject to balance day adjustments).  As a result, Placer's net
     acquisition cost for Highlands Gold 25% interest in Porgera (including
     the receivable from Orogen Minerals) will be approximately A$316
     million, equivalent to the top end of Baring's valuation range in its
     independent expert's report;
<p>
     <li>To finance the acquisition of the non-Porgera assets and to
     provide working capital of approximately A$50 million, Highlands
     Pacific will raise approximately A$190 million through an underwritten
     equity raising.  A consortium of Papua New Guinea financial
     institutions have committed to subscribe for up to A$110 million, and
     are expected collectively to have an interest of not less than 50% in
     Highlands Pacific at the conclusion of the equity raising; and
<p>
     <li>The proposed underwriters are Merrill Lynch (Australia) and
     Wilson HTM Corporate Services.
<p>
     <li>The proposed entitlement issue is subject to a number of conditions
     including the restructuring not requiring the approval of Highlands
     Gold shareholders, negotiation of detailed documentation to give
     effect to the restructure, entry into an Underwriting Agreement and
     compliance with a specified timetable.
<p>
     <li>The Board of Highlands Gold believes that this restructuring
     proposal, which has Placer's full support, is in the interests of
     Highlands Gold shareholders and accordingly strongly recommends that
     shareholders ACCEPT Placer's offer as the Directors of Highlands
     intend to do in respect of their own shareholdings.
<p>
     <li>In making their recommendation, the Highlands Gold Board point out
     that if the conditions attaching to the restructuring proposal are not
     satisfied or waived by Placer, then the proposed issue by Highlands
     Pacific may not proceed.
<p>
     <li>To reflect Placer's position as controlling shareholder of
     Highlands Gold, Ian Goddard, Geoff Applegate and Bill Hodgson have
     agreed to resign from Highlands Gold Board and will be replaced by
     three Placer-appointed Directors, Dick Zandee, Russell Barwick and Mel
     Togolo.  Clive Hildebrand and Sir Henry ToRobert have agreed to remain
     on the Board to represent the interests of minority shareholders.
<p>
     <li>Highlands Gold Managing Director, Ian Goddard, said today, "The
     restructuring proposal agreed with Placer represents a better outcome
     for Highlands shareholders who accept the offer as they will receive
     A$0.75 per share AND the possibility of participating in the
     development of Highlands' world class advanced base metal projects and
     Highlands' extensive exploration portfolio."
    <p>
     Please Note:<br>
     The Recommendation and Restructuring Agreement applicable
     to the following companies:
     <br>
     Highlands Gold Limited  (HGL)<br>
     Ballimore Pty Limited  (HPL)<br>
     Placer Dome Holdings Pte Ltd. (PDH)<br>
     is available at the ASX<br>

     <p>
     <strong>Media enquiries:</strong>
     <p>
     <strong>Highlands Gold</strong><br>
     Ian Goddard - Managing Director<br>
     Tel: (07) 3864 0720<br>
 <p>
     <strong>Rothschild Australia</strong><br>
     Richard Barker - Director<br>
     Tel: (07) 9323 2029<br>
 <p>
     <strong>Shareholder enquiries:</strong><br>
     1800 355 707<br>
     (sgd) Philip J. West<br>
     Company Secretary<br>
     Highlands Gold Limited<br>
 <p>

     <strong>From Hon. C. Haiveta, Papua New Guinea:</strong>
 <p>
        The Deputy Prime Minister, Mr. Chris Haivets today congratulated
     Placer Dome Inc. and Highlands Gold on the resolution of the
     outstanding matters relating to the takeover of Highlands Gold by
     Placer Dome.  Mr. Haiveta said that the agreement allows each Highland
     shareholder who accepts the current offer by Placer to receive 75
     cents, plus a right to purchase a share in Highlands Pacific, the
     company that will eventually hold the non-Porgera assets.  These
     rights should be valuable and give the Highland's shareholders more
     than the original Placer offer.
 <p>
     Mr. Haiveta said:<br>
     "The agreements between Placer and Highlands Gold, in co-operation
     with the PNG institutions, to allow the non-Porgera assets held by
     Highlands to be sold to Highlands Pacific is to be commended.  The
     restrucuture proposed by the parties will allow the orderly
     underwriting and placement of shares in the newly formed company and
     at the same time ensures that these non-Porgera assets will be dealt
     with on a timely basis.  The Government supports the proposed
     restructure.
 <p>
     "This deal was brokered by the PNG institutions and the underwriters
     McIntosh & Wilsons.  They have managed to satisfy the demands of
     diverse interests, including the State's legitimate interest in seeing
     that the non-Porgera assets currently owned by Highlands are given
     every oppportunity of being developed.  They have done a wonderful
     job."
 <p>
     Hon. C. Haiveta<br>
     Deputy Prime Minister &  Minister for Finance<br>
     Port Moresby<br>


    
        
    <br><br>
    </td>
    </tr>
	
