<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - The Latest</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	
	<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/06butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	</td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<table border=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top colspan=2>
	<img src="../gfx/09head.gif" alt="The Latest header gif">
	</td>
	
	
	<tr>
	<td>
	

    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	
    <h2>Placer Dome offers to cancel shares in Highlands Gold in return for 25% of Porgera Mine</h2>
	
    <strong>December 23, 1996</strong>
    
    <p>


	<strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc. has made an in-principle offer to
     Highlands Gold Limited to cancel its Highlands Gold stake in return
     for 25% of the Porgera Mine.  Any difference would be settled in cash.
    <p>
        Placer Dome President and Chief Executive Officer, Mr. John
     Willson, said the proposal was made in direct response to the Barings'
     valuation released by Highlands Gold yesterday.
    <p>
        "I see this as the only solution possible to deliver Highlands Gold
     shareholders the value that their independent expert believes is in
     Frieda-Nena, Ramu and the exploration assets.  Placer Dome cannot
     accept these valuations and is unable to justify any increase in its
     takeover offer, let alone the A$0.21 necessary to bring the offer into
     Barings' valuation range," Mr. Willson said.
    <p>
        "The Barings valuation of Highlands' 25% interest in Porgera is
     inconsistent with the valuation Barings completed just 18 months ago.
     However, we are prepared to concede that the issue regarding valuation
     of Porgera may be bridged and are making a proposal to do so.
    <p>
        "On the other hand, the Barings valuations of Frieda-Nena and Ramu
     are beyond my comprehension.  Based on the information we have
     available, Placer Dome cannot ascribe even a fraction of Barings'
     value to these assets.  Interestingly, the former majority owner of
     Highlands Gold could find no such value either."
    <p>
        Mr. Willson said Placer Dome would be prepared to buy 25% of
     Porgera at the mid-point of the Barings valuation range, or A$276.8
     million.  It would also purchase the receivable from the Papua New
     Guinea government relating to Porgera on the same terms.  A copy of
     Mr. Willson's letter to Mr. Hildebrand, Highlands' Chairman, is
     attached.
    <p>
        Mr. Willson described the proposal as a "win-win" solution.
     "Highlands Gold shareholders would get to keep the assets that
     Highlands' directors apparently value so highly but which Placer Dome
     cannot agree to pay for," he said.  "Placer Dome would buy 25% of
     Porgera, an operation it knows and understands at the value ascribed
     by the independent expert.
    <p>
    "If Barings' valuations are accepted, our proposal further boosts
     the value of the remaining Highlands shares.  I believe that the
     Highlands Board and its independent expert should therefore conclude
     our proposal to be fair and reasonable."
    <p>
        Placer Dome's offer is made subject to reaching agreement on
     detailed terms with Highlands and to there being no adverse
     transaction costs or triggering of pre-emptive rights under the
     Porgera Joint Venture agreement.
    <p>
        Mr. Willson has asked Mr. Hildebrand for a reply as to whether this
     proposal is of in-principle interest by Monday, January 6, 1997 so
     that Placer Dome may withdraw or close its takeover offer for
     Highlands Gold and proceed down this new course if it is of mutual
     interest.

      <p>
    For further information:<br>                                 
    Investor Relations: Earl Dunlop (604) 661-3779<br>           
    Media Relations: Hugh Leggatt (604) 661-1554<br>         


     <hr width=40% align=center>

    <p>
     December 23, 1996
    
    <p>
    
     Mr. Clive Hildebrand<br>
     Chairman<br>
     Highlands Gold Limited<br>
     167 Eagle Street<br>
     Brisbane, QLD 4000<br>
     Australia<br>
    <p>
     Dear Clive:
    <p>
     I have received a copy of your media release relating to the Barings
     valuation of Highlands Gold Limited and the extracts from the Barings
     report that were attached.  Obviously, I am keen to see the full
     Barings valuation and I will need to have my people review it
     thoroughly to understand the assumptions underlying it.  Whatever the
     detailed assumptions, however, I see a fundamental problem emerging.
    <p>
     The Barings valuation places a value of A$258.7 million to A$294.8
     million on Highlands' 25% of Porgera excluding the Porgera Sale
     Receivable (or A$0.458 to A$0.522 per share).  This is a surprisingly
     high valuation since Barings valued 25% of Porgera 18 months ago, in
     its role as independent valuer for Pancontinental Mining, at A$262.9
     to A$295.7 million.  Since that time, unfortunately, the gold price
     has fallen, production at Porgera has fallen, costs are higher and
     share prices of the Porgera Joint Venture partners have fallen
     sharply.  From the sensitivity analyses in the previous Barings
     valuation I would have expected their value to have fallen by many
     millions of dollars.  Nevertheless, I am prepared to concede that, in
     relation to Porgera, the value gap is not so large that it could not
     be bridged.  In fact, this letter contains a proposal to do so.
    <p>
     It is with the valuations of Highlands' other assets that I have the
     most difficulty.  As you know, Placer Dome has very little information
     on Frieda-Nena, Ramu, or your exploration assets.  Your independent
     expert is placing a value of A$289.7 million to A$358.2 million (or
     A$0.513 to A$0.635 per share) on these assets.  This is an
     extraordinary value for two greenfields projects.  Frankly, there is
     no way Placer Dome can acknowledge even a fraction of this value on
     the information we have available.  I can therefore see no way that
     Placer Dome could justify any increase in its offer for Highlands, let
     alone the A$0.21 increase necessary to bring our offer into Barings'
     valuation range.
    <p>
     Clearly, we have a fundamental problem.  There may, however, be a
     solution which gives your shareholders the value which the Highlands
     Board and its independent expert believe is there for Frieda-Nena,
     Ramu and your exploration assets on terms which Placer Dome can meet.
     Simply put, I am proposing a cancellation of Placer Dome's
     shareholding in Highlands in consideration for the 25% Porgera
     interest.  Highlands would continue as an independent entity following
     this cancellation and would keep Frieda-Nena, Ramu and its exploration
     assets.
    <p>
     The terms on which Placer Dome would be prepared to consider such a
     transaction are broadly:
    <br>
     <li>Placer Dome would agree to the effective cancellation of its
     shareholding in Highlands at a notional value of A$0.75 per share (a
     substantial concession, having regard to Barings' valuation of
     Highlands shares of A$0.96 to A$1.14 per share);

     <li>in conjunction with the cancellation, Placer Dome would purchase
     25% of Porgera for A$276.8 million, and the Porgera Sale Receivable
     for A$20.9 million, the mid-point of the Barings' valuation range; and

     <li>any difference (either way) would be settled in cash.
    <p>
     As an example, if Placer Dome had 50% of Highlands shares at the close
     of its offer it would agree to the effective cancellation of these at
     a total value of A$211.7 million.  It would purchase the 25% Porgera
     interest and the Porgera Sale Receivable for a total of A$297.7
     million and pay Highlands A$86 million in cash, representing the
     difference.
    <p>
     This example illustrates how Highlands shareholders might be
     substantially better off following our proposed transaction, providing
     the Barings' values are accepted.  Highlands would have the following
     assets (adopting the Barings' numbers for the sake of example):
    <p>
    <table border=1 width=475>
    <tr>
    <td></td>
    <td><font size=-1><strong>Barings Low Value</font></strong></td>
    <td><font size=-1><strong>Barings High Value</font></strong></td>
    
    <tr>
    <td><font size=-1>Example - Value Implications</td>    
    <td align=center><font size=-1>(A$ million)</td>    
    <td align=center><font size=-1>(A$ million)</td>
    
    <tr>
    <td valign=top>
    <font size=-1>
    Frieda-Nena<br>                                          
    Ramu       <br>                                           
    Exploration<br>                                           
    Net Other Assets (per Barings)<br>                        
    Cash Payment<br>                                          
    <strong>Total</strong><br>                               
    <p>
    Shares on Issue After Cancellation (million)<br>
    Value per Share for Remaining Shareholders<br>
    </font>            
    </td>
    
    <td valign=top align=center>
   <font size=-1>
    92.0<br> 
    161.0<br> 
    36.7<br>  
    (55.9)<br>
