    <p>

	
    <h2>Placer Dome forecasts higher gold production</h2>
	
    <strong>December 23, 1996</strong>
    
    <p>


	<strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc. said today its share of gold
     production is expected to increase to about 2.3 million ozs. in 1997,
     from 1.9 million ozs. in 1996, at a cash production cost of about
     $240/oz.  The Corporation's share of gold production is expected to
     increase to an average of 3 million ozs. per year by the end of the
     decade.
    <p>
        These amounts assume completion of the proposed acquisitions of
     Highlands Gold Limited and the Placer Pacific minorities.  Without
     these, the 1997 share of production is forecast to be about 2 million
     ozs. at a cash production cost of about US$235/oz.  All these
     estimates assume the sale of the Kiena and Sigma mines in Canada by
     the end of the first quarter.
    <p>
        The Corporation's share of production from Placer Pacific mines in
     1997 is expected to be about 10% higher than in 1996 at 900,000 ozs.,
     at a cash production cost of about US$280/oz.  Cash production costs
     are expected to be higher due principally to lower ore grades at the
     Misima and Porgera mines in Papua New Guinea.
    <p>
        Gold production from United States mines in 1997 is anticipated to
     increase by about 45% to about 450,000 ozs. at a cash production cost
     of less than US$200/oz.  The new mill at the 60%-owned Cortez Joint
     Venture will start commercial production early in the year.  Low-grade
     stockpiled ore from the Crescent pit at Cortez will be processed until
     mid-year when development of the Pipeline pit is expected to be
     sufficiently advanced  to meet all millfeed requirements.  In 1997,
     the Corporation's share of Cortez production is expected to exceed
     200,000 ounces at a cash production cost of less than $200 per ounce.
    <p>
        At the Golden Sunlight Mine in United States, a revised mine plan
     prepared following the reorganization announced in the third quarter
     no longer includes marginal heap leach material which was intended for
     treatment in the last four years of the mine life, thereby reducing
     ore reserves by 500,000 ozs. to 1.4 million ozs.
      <p>
        John Willson, President and Chief Executive Officer, commented:
     "Our operations profile is changing as we concentrate on
     higher-quality, longer-life gold mining assets and benefit from new,
     lower-cost gold output."

    <p>
    For further information:<br>                                 
    Investor Relations: Earl Dunlop (604) 661-3779<br>           
    Media Relations: Hugh Leggatt (604) 661-1554<br>             

    <br><br>
    </td>
    </tr>
	
