    </font>
    <p>
    In addition to the above operating assets, Placer Dome is also in the process of developing two new major projects and expects to start construction on a third shortly:
	<li>Musselwhite: a gold mining project under construction in Northwestern Ontario;
	<li>Pipeline/South Pipeline: a gold mining project under construction in Northeastern Nevada;
	<li>Las Cristinas: a gold deposit in Southeastern Venezuela where Placer Dome expects to start construction shortly.


    <h3>Intentions In Respect Of Highlands</h3>

    <strong>Intentions if 100% of Highlands acquired</strong><br>

	If Placer Dome Holdings becomes entitled to compulsory acquisition rights in respect 
	of Highlands shares, it intends to exercise those rights. Following the acquisition 
	of 100% of Highlands, Placer Dome Holdings intends to:
	<br>

    <strong>(a)</strong> maintain the interest in the Porgera Joint Venture, although 
    ownership of that interest may be changed to facilitate repatriation of 
    dividends;
    <br>
    <strong>(b)</strong> review Highlands' exploration program and make whatever 
    changes are necessary to make that program consistent with the global exploration 
    strategy of the Placer Dome group;
    <br>
    <strong>(c)</strong> consider whether the Nena project in Papua New Guinea is 
    economically viable and of sufficient quality to justify development and, if so, 
    continue to develop the project either alone or with joint venture partners;
    <br>
    <strong>(d)</strong> consider whether development of the Ramu nickel project in 
    Papua New Guinea is economically viable and of sufficient quality to justify 
    development and, if so, consider how the project may best be developed given that 
    the primary business of Placer Dome is gold mining;
    <br>
    <strong>(e)</strong> close the offices of Highlands in Brisbane and consolidate the office in Port Moresby with the existing office of Placer PNG Limited, which may involve retrenchment of Highlands employees whose functions overlap with those already performed by employees of PDH and its related companies;
    <br>
    <strong>(f)</strong> to review with Highlands' existing management the business, operations, management systems and strategy of Highlands in order to enhance its competitive position as a part of the Placer Dome group. This may involve the redeployment of employees of Highlands into the worldwide operations of Placer Dome and retrenchment off employees whose positions are no longer required once the review process has been completed.

    <p>
    <strong>If  less than 100% of Highlands is acquired</strong><br>

    If Placer Dome Holdings does not acquire 100% of Highlands shares, it proposes to 
    cause the Highlands board to be reconstituted to reflect its shareholding in 
    Highlands. This will involve the convening or a requisition for an extraordinary 
    general meeting of shareholders if Placer Dome Holdings is unable to reach 
    agreement with the current board of Highlands within a reasonable time. 
    Otherwise, it intends to undertake the same general review described above, with 
    a view to causing Highlands to focus on its existing assets and to maximize 
    dividends to its shareholders, rather than conducting exploration at its current 
    levels.

    <p>
    <strong>Shareholding of Placer Dome Group in Highlands</strong><br>

	As at December 2, 1996, the shareholding of subsidiaries of Placer Dome in Highlands 
	was 187,755,458 ordinary shares representing (33%) of the issued shares made up as 
	follows:

	<li>Placer Dome Holdings held (directly or through nominees) 56,397,458 shares
	<li>Posadas Investments Pte Ltd, a Singapore company and the holding company of placer Dome Holdings held (directly or through nominees) 131,358,000

    <p>
    <strong>Relationship of Placer Dome Holdings to Placer (PNG) Pty Ltd</strong><br>
    <p>
    Placer Dome Holdings is an indirectly wholly-owned subsidiary of Placer Dome.
    <p>
    Placer Pacific Limited (Placer Pacific), a company listed on the Australian Stock 
    Exchange, is an indirectly 75.4%-owned subsidiary of Placer Dome. Placer (PNG) 
    Pty Ltd is an indirectly wholly-owned Papua New Guinea subsidiary of Placer 
    Pacific and is the manager of the Porgera joint venture.

    <p>
    <strong>Proposed takeover by Placer Dome of Placer Pacific</strong><br>

    On November 28, 12996, Placer Dome announced its intention to make a takeover offer for all of the shares in Placer Pacific  which it did not own., representing 24.6% of the capital of the company. Offer documents relating to the takeover proposal are expected to be dispatched to the shareholders of Placer Pacific in mid-January 1997.

    <p>
    <strong>Identity of Directors of Placer Dome Holdings</strong><br>

    The directors of Placer Dome Holdings include: Mr. J.M. Willson, President and 
    Chief Executive Officer of Placer Dome; Mr. I.G. Austin, Senior Vice President 
    and Chief Financial Officer of Placer Dome; Mr. B.B. Nicol, Controller, Placer 
    Dome; Mr. S.J. Smith, Director Treasury Operations, Placer Dome; Mr. G.L. Brack, 
    General Manager Corporate Development, Placer Dome; Mr. R.C. Barwick, Managing 
    Director, Placer (PNG) Pty Limited.
    <p>
    Mr. J.M. Willson is also Chairman of Directors of Placer Pacific and Mr. I.G. 
    Austin is a director of the company.
    
    <br><br>
    </td>
    </tr>
	
