<TITLE>Placer Dome - The Latest</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	
	<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/06butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	</td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<table border=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top colspan=2>
	<img src="../gfx/09head.gif" alt="The Latest header gif">
	</td>
	
	
	<tr>
	<td>
	

    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	<h2>
	Placer Dome announces Pipeline expansion plan
	</h2>
	
	<strong>
	September 24, 1996
	</strong>
	<p>
	
	<strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc. announced plans
	today to integrate development of the 2.5 million-ounce gold
	deposit, South Pipeline, with the adjacent 4.3 million-ounce
	Pipeline deposit.  Facilities to treat ore from the deposits are
	currently under construction at the 60%-owned Cortez Joint Venture
	in the United States with approved expenditure of US$320 million. 
	Placer Dome U.S. Inc. has applied to the Nevada State Office of the
	Bureau of Land Management for Approval of a Plan of Operations for
	South Pipeline.
	<p>

	Ore reserves at South Pipeline are estimated to be 44 million tonnes
	grading 1.75 grams of gold per tonne, bringing total Pipeline/South
	Pipeline reserves to 76 million tonnes grading 2.8 grams of gold per
	tonne, containing a total of 6.8 million ounces of gold.  Ore from
	both deposits will be treated in the new carbon-in-leach (CIL) gold
	recovery plant currently under construction, the capacity of which
	has been increased to a nominal 7,250 tonnes per day from 4,200
	tonnes per day.  Total combined gold production is expected to
	average 440,000 ounces of gold per year over a 12-year mine life, up
	from 310,000 ounces per year for Pipeline alone, at a cash
	production cost of US$152/ounce.
	<p>

	Construction of facilities for the combined project is three months
	ahead of schedule and is expected to be materially under budget.  By
	integrating South Pipeline, economic returns from the project are
	being enhanced by the increased throughput of ore.  The first gold
	from Pipeline is expected to be poured in the spring of 1997.
	<p>

        For further information:<br>
