<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - The Latest</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	
	<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/06butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	</td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<table border=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top colspan=2>
	<img src="../gfx/09head.gif" alt="The Latest header gif">
	</td>
	
	
	<tr>
	<td>
	

    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	
    <h2>Las Cristinas gold mine project approved</h2>
	
    <strong>August 1, 1996</strong>
    
    <p>

	<strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc., 70% owner, and Corporacin Venezolana de 
	Guayana (CVG) today announced approval for expenditure of US$536 million for design 
	and construction of a gold mine at the Las Cristinas property in south-eastern 
	Venezuela.  The approval is subject to completion of a financing and risk management 
	plan, the cost of which is not included in the capital cost estimate.  Inclusion of a 
	US$40 million contingency gives a total estimated project cost of US$576 million.  
	Construction is expected to start in late 1996 for gold production to commence during 
	the fourth quarter of 1998.
	
    <p>

	The mine is projected to produce an average of 450,000 ozs. of gold per year (PDG 
	share 315,000 ozs. per year) for at least 16 years.  Ore reserves are currently 
	estimated to be 233 million tonnes of ore grading 1.21 grams of gold per tonne, 
	containing 9 million ozs. of gold.   An open pit will be mined at a rate of 55,000 
	tonnes per day (tpd) in the first year, rising to more than 100,000 tpd when bedrock 
	is reached.  The average waste to ore ratio is expected to be 1.14:1.
	
    <p>

	The combined flotation/carbon-in-leach processing plant is being designed to treat 
	40,000 tpd, or 14.6 million tonnes of ore annually.  About half of the planned 
	production of 7.4 million ozs. of gold will be produced in dor bullion form.  The 
	rest will be contained in a copper concentrate.  Copper production is expected to 
	average 36 million lbs. per year.  
	
    <p>

	According to the feasibility study recently revised by Placer Dome, cash production 
	costs are forecast to average US$205 per oz. of gold, including copper credits.  In 
	the early years, production will average about 530,000 ozs. per year at an average 
	cash production cost below US$200/oz.  The processing circuit has been optimized to 
	reduce costs and to make water and tailing management cleaner and safer.  
	Construction is expected to require a workforce of 2,500 and the mine will employ 
	about 985 people.
	
    <p>

	John Willson, President and Chief Executive Officer, characterized Las Cristinas as a 
	large, low-cost gold deposit.  "This profitable, long-life mine that we are about to 
	build represents the successful application of our growth strategy.  As a result of 
	our own exploration activity, it adds substantial value.  Its considerable scale as 
	one of the largest precious metals producers in Latin America will strongly augment 
	our production and cash flow levels.  And through the high probability that further 
	exploration will add gold reserves, it contributes to our long-term future."
	
    <p>

	The financing and risk management plan being pursued involves both private sector and 
	multilateral lenders.  Financing will have limited recourse to Placer Dome upon 
	project completion.  Discussions with potential lenders are well advanced, and the 
	Corporation expects project construction to commence in the fourth quarter.    	
	
    <p>

	A recent addition of higher-grade reserves from an area separate from the main 
	deposit further improved the project economics and will contribute to early 
	production.  A series of recent exploration drillholes has extended ore-grade 
	mineralization down dip along the length of the main Conductora orebodys western 
	margin.  As much as 100 million tonnes of new resource of similar grade may be added 
	by year end.
	
    <p>

	Las Cristinas will become the third gold mine project to start construction in the 
	Placer Dome Group in 1996, after Musselwhite in Canada and Pipeline in the United 
	States.  Two more gold projects, Mulatos in Mexico and Mt. Rawdon in Australia await 
	approval, and a further two properties, Cerro Crucitas in Costa Rica and Donlin Creek 
	in Alaska are in advanced stages of evaluation.

    
    <p>

	
	For further information:<br>
    Investor Relations: Earl Dunlop (604) 661-3779<br>
	Media Relations: Hugh Leggatt (604) 661-1554<br>

	<br><br>
    
    </td>
    </tr>
	
