	<tr>
	<td>
	

    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	
    <h2>Sigma Mine renewal plan under way</h2>
	
    <strong>June 25, 1996</strong>
    
    <p>
    
     <strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc. advises that a major renewal plan
     is under way to improve the economics of its high-cost Sigma gold mine
     in Canada.  The Corporation regrets that, as part of the strategy, the
     workforce is being reduced by about 100 employees from 325 effective
     July 10.
     <p>
        Sigma, which had an average cash production cost of US$488 per
     ounce of gold in the first quarter, has been striving for
     profitability since a rockburst in June 1995 limited access to its
     primary ore zone.  Studies have since shown that accelerated
     development of several alternative gold veins will not compensate for
     the shortfall sustained.  The average cash production cost in May rose
     to US$550/oz., necessitating action to stem losses in the short-term.
    <p>
        The initial element of the renewal plan entails reducing ore
     production from underground, which accounts for the lay-off of
     employees, and increasing ore production from the Sigma II open pit
     mine.  Mining of higher grade stopes underground will partially offset
     the effect of lower grades from the open pit.  With mill throughput
     continuing at 1,800 tonnes per day, production in 1996 is expected to
     be 72,000 ozs. of gold, 13,000 ozs. less than originally budgeted,
     compared with 78,000 ozs. in 1995.
      <p>
        The longer term elements of the plan are still being studied,
     including access to the ore isolated by the rockburst and the mine's
     future exploration potential.


    
    <p>

	
	For further information:<br>
    Investor Relations: Earl Dunlop (604) 661-3779<br>
	Media Relations: Hugh Leggatt (604) 661-1554<br>

	<br><br>
    
    </td>
    </tr>
	
