	<tr>
	<td>
	

    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	
    <h2>Placer Dome increases exposure to gold price movements</h2>
	
    <strong>May 27, 1996</strong>
    
    <p>

		<strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc. reports that in order to provide its 
		shareholders with greater exposure to the gold price, it has completed a programme to 
		close out 1.7 million ounces of its gold hedge position which would have required the 
		Corporation to deliver gold at prices of $450 per ounce or less.
         <p>
        As a result, Placer Dome's gold hedge programme now aggregates 3.8 million 
        ounces compared with 5.5 million ounces at March 31, 1996 and the average 
        price has increased to $482 per ounce from $462 per ounce. (Amounts represent 
        the Corporation's share and details are in the attached table.)
        <p>
        In closing out these positions, the Corporation has locked in pre-tax gains 
        totalling $23 million which will be included in reported earnings from the 
        third quarter of 1996 to the fourth quarter of 1997.  In addition, it is 
        expected that gold hedging activities will contribute $10 million to the 
        Corporation's operating earnings in the second quarter of 1996.
        <p>
        Placer Dome's approach to hedging is a balanced one.  It is intended to 
        enable the Corporation to benefit from the higher price realizations that can 
        be achieved in the forward market, while still retaining significant exposure 
        to upside gold price movements.  To date the programme has realized in excess 
        of $400 million.  Beyond this, the Corporation's remaining hedge position has 
        unrealized gains, at today's prices, exceeding $100 million.
        <p>
        The reduction in the hedge position is consistent with this approach.  Given 
        the fundamental strength of the gold market, the Corporation has concluded 
        that the balance it seeks is currently best achieved by hedging only when 
        realizations will exceed $450 per ounce.  As
a result almost all positions below this level have been closed out.


    
    <p>

	
	For further information:<br>
    Investor Relations: Earl Dunlop (604) 661-3779<br>
	Media Relations: Hugh Leggatt (604) 661-1554<br>

	<br><br>
    
    </td>
    </tr>
	
