	<td>
	

    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>


	<h2>
	Placer Dome's first quarter below target
	</h2>
	
	<strong>
	April 15, 1996
	</strong>
	<p>
	
	(all dollar amounts in U.S. currency)
	<p>
	
	<strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc. advised at its annual meeting of shareholders
	in Toronto today that due to production shortfalls at some of its gold mines, the
	Corporations share of first quarter production at 458,000 ounces of gold was
	below the planned level of 495,000 ounces, although higher than the 1995 first
	quarter level of 400,000 ounces.
		<p>
	Costs were also adversely affected and the average cash cost of production for the
	Corporations share was $245 per ounce compared with $235 per ounce in the first
	quarter of 1995.
		<p>
	The operating shortfalls reflect previously disclosed conditions at the Porgera
	Mine in Papua New Guinea and the Detour Lake and Sigma mines in Canada, as well as
	lower-than-expected recoveries and grades at the Golden Sunlight and Bald Mountain
	mines in the United States.
		<p>
	At Porgera, difficult ground conditions have restricted the availability of
	several high-grade underground stopes and resulted in the rescheduling of
	production from these stopes until later.  Reinterpretation of the model of the
	main ore zone at Detour Lake reduced ore reserves by about two years of millfeed,
	and resulted in lower grades and development constraints which are limiting the
	mines ability to feed the mill at capacity.  Operations at Sigma are being
	affected by two major rock bursts in 1995 which resulted in a loss of scheduled
	high-grade ore and a shortfall in development.
		<p>
	In spite of these results, Placer Dome expects to meet its 1996 objective of
	producing 2 million ounces of gold for its account.
		<p>

	For further information:<br>
	Investor Relations - Earl Dunlop  (604) 661-3779<br>
	Media Relations - Hugh Leggatt  (604) 661-1554<p>


	<br><br>
    
    </td>
    </tr>
	
