	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/06butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	</td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<table border=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top colspan=2>
	<img src="../gfx/09head.gif" alt="The Latest header gif">
	</td>
	
	
	<tr>
	<td>
	

    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	<h2>	
	Placer Dome discloses updated plans for five more mines
	</h2>
	

	<strong>
	February 26, 1996
	</strong>
	<p>

	(all dollar amounts in U.S. currency)
	<p>

	<strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - During the next 12 months, Placer Dome Inc. expects to start
	construction of five mines which in aggregate will contribute an average of 
	800,000 ozs. of annual gold production and substantially elevate its production
	base from the two million ounce level expected in 1996, John Willson, President
	and CEO, will tell securities analysts at briefings which start in major North
	American cities today.
	<p>

	"During this period, production from some of our existing mines will decline but
	clearly this will be eclipsed by the incremental output from new projects," he
	said. They are the Musselwhite gold project in Canada, a major expansion of the
	Cortez Joint Venture (CJV) in the United States, the Las Cristinas gold project in
	Venezuela, the Mount Rawdon heap leaching project in Australia and the Mulatos
	gold project in Mexico.
	  <p>

	"If we begin construction as we expect, we will meet our strategic target of 2.5
	million ozs. in 1998 and exceed it in 1999.  Further growth beyond this is likely
	as we continue to make excellent progress on other projects such as South Pipeline
	in the United States and Cerro Crucitas in Costa Rica."
	 <p>

	On February 22, Placer Dome announced it was starting construction of a mine and
	processing facilities at the 68%-owned Musselwhite gold property in northern
	Ontario. Willson said the Corporation's share of pre-tax operating earnings from
	Musselwhite is projected to average $8 million per year based on feasibility study
	assumptions.  He added that while current ore reserves are 9.8 million tonnes, the
	feasibility study is based on processing approximately 12 million tonnes of ore
	and other mineralized material over the mine life.  Furthermore, he said there is
	a good probability of identifying an additional 7 million tonnes to extend the
	life of the operation by six years.  "This additional tonnage would have a
	substantial impact on the value of the project."
	  <p>
	
	He added, "Musselwhite will be profitable and over time as we pursue its upside
	potential it may be very profitable.  It is a strategic investment in what we see
	as Canada's next gold camp."
	 <p>

	A decision to expand operations at the 60%-owned Cortez Joint Venture (CJV) in the
	United States is expected in March following the issue of mine permits expected
	from the federal Bureau of Land Management.  "This will be, without question, one
	of the best gold projects ever undertaken by Placer Dome," said Willson.
	 <p>
	
	At Cortez, development plans have been updated to build maximum flexibility into a
	planned new metallurgical plant, in order to capitalize on the exploration
	potential of the CJV.  The plant is designed to facilitate expanded production at
	nominal cost should this become possible.  The capital cost of the project, which
	includes development of the Pipeline gold deposit,  is now estimated to be $320
	million.
	  <p>

	Pipeline will be an open pit mine with 4.3 million ozs. of reserves.  At an
	average cash production cost over the 12-year mine life of $110/oz., it is
	expected to be Placer Dome's lowest-cost gold producer.  Output is planned to
	average about 310,000 ozs. per year for 12 years, based on a 4,200 tonnes of ore
	per day processing plant.  Production is expected to
	begin in mid-1997.
	 <p>
	
	"Pipeline is a great project," said Willson.  "Based on a gold price of $375 per
	ounce, the mine is projected to contribute operating earnings in the order of $43
	million per year to Placer Dome over its first three years."
	  <p>

	The CJV has been mining and milling several deposits since 1968 and owns
	facilities to treat a number of types of gold ore.  Following discovery of the
	Pipeline deposit in 1991, step-out drilling encountered the South Pipeline deposit
	800 metres south.  As at year-end 1995, 1.5 million ozs. of gold from South
	Pipeline have been placed in the ore reserves of the CJV.  In 1996, the CJV will
	spend in excess of $1 million on drilling around the South Pipeline deposit.
	 <p>

	Willson said the feasibility study for development of the 70%-owned Las Cristinas
	gold property is due to be completed in March.  "This is a great discovery that we
	are all very proud of, and we are committed to making the project a success.  The
	question is not if Las Cristinas will become a mine, but how, and when.  Our
	engineers have now largely finalized the plant concepts and mine design that we
	believe are right for this exceptional deposit," said Willson.  "What remains is
	to resolve outstanding business issues related to the investment climate in
	Venezuela."  Willson said current plant concepts will increase the rate of gold
	production above previous projections and also increase the capital cost although
	final estimates are not yet available.
	 <p>

	A feasibility study for the Mount Rawdon project will be completed in the second
	quarter of 1996 and before the end of 1996 a feasibility study is expected to be
	completed on the Mulatos project.
	 <p>

	"Assisted by new mines which began operations in 1995, in 1996 our operations
	should be generating cash at a rate in excess of $350 million per year at current
	metal prices," Willson told the analysts.  "We anticipate increasingly strong cash
	flows in future from mines we will start to construct in the coming months." 
	Placer Dome expects to fund its future growth from these cash flows, from its cash
	and short term investments exceeding $300
	million and from some debt financing.
  <p>

	Noting that Placer Dome's ore reserves have increased to 21.0 from 19.8 million
	ozs., Willson said a further increase in reserves is projected for this year as
	decisions are made on more projects.  Measured and indicated mineralization
	increased to 29 million ozs. from 24.6 million ounces at the end of 1994. 
	Inferred mineralization increased to 14.6 million ozs. from 10.1 million ozs. at
	the end of 1994 (see attached table).
	 <p>

	
	For further information: <br>
	Investor Relations - Earl Dunlop  (604) 661-3779<br>
	Media Relations - Hugh Leggatt  (604) 661-1554	 
	<p>




	<br><br>
    
    </td>
    </tr>
	
