	<td>
	
    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	<h2>Placer Dome earns $74 million in 1995</h2>
	
    <strong>February 22, 1996</strong>

    <p>
    
    <font size=-1>(all dollar amounts in U.S. funds)</font>
    
    <p>

        <strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc. reports consolidated net earnings for 
        1995 of $74 million or $0.31 per share compared with net earnings of $105 
        million or $0.44 per share in 1994.  Fourth quarter net earnings were $38 
        million or $0.16 per share, compared with $26 million or $0.11 per share in 
        the year-earlier period.  Fourth quarter gold sales volumes were 18% higher 
        than a year ago.
         <p>
        In 1995, mine operating earnings increased for the fifth consecutive 
        year to $308 million from $271 million in 1994, reflecting higher 
        realized gold prices and sales volumes and increased earnings from 
        molybdenum.  Notwithstanding the improvement in mine operating 
        earnings, net earnings declined primarily as a result of a higher 
        level of exploration expense, including $42 million on a project in 
        Kazakstan and the $17 million after-tax write-off of a venture 
        capital investment.
         <p>
        Sales revenues in 1995 were $1,029 million compared with $899 million 
        in 1994.  The average realized price of gold for 1995 was $392/oz. 
        compared with $388/oz. in 1994.  The average London market price for 
        gold in 1995 remained unchanged from the 1994 average spot price of 
        $384/oz.
          <p>
        Cash flow from operations amounted to $229 million compared with $225 
        million the previous year. The Corporation continues to maintain a 
        strong financial position, in spite of capital expenditures in 1995 
        of $451 million.  The year-end cash and short-term investments 
        balance was $321 million compared with $312 million at the end of 
        1994, and debt amounted to $563 compared with $276 million.  The 
        Corporation issued $300 million of long-term and medium-term notes in 
        1995 to build liquidity in advance of anticipated capital 
        expenditures.
         <p>
        Consolidated gold production in 1995 was 2.2 million ounces of which 
        the Corporation's share was 1.9 million ounces at an average cash 
        production cost of $217/oz compared with $198/oz. in 1994.  The 
        higher average cost in 1995 was due to the mining of lower grades, 
        the start-up phase of the expanded facilities at the Dome Mine, and 
        operating difficulties at the Detour Lake and Sigma mines.  The 
        higher production in 1995 was primarily the result of increased 
        output at the Dome Mine in Canada following completion of a major 
        expansion project, and the normalization of operations at the Golden 
        Sunlight Mine in the United States. Our most profitable gold 
        mines were the Campbell and Dome mines in Canada, the Misima and 
        Porgera mines in Papua New Guinea and La Coipa Mine in Chile.  Seven 
        of 13 gold mines recorded either higher production or lower costs or 
        both.  The Campbell Mine set a new production record of 323,775 ozs.  
        The Corporation's share of gold production in 1996 is expected to be 
        2 million ozs. at an average cash production cost of about $210/oz.
          <p>
        Mine operating earnings from molybdenum at $67 million were 
        significantly higher than in 1994 due to much higher prices in the 
        first half of 1995.  The average Metals Week Dealer Oxide quoted 
        price for 1995 was $7.42/lb. compared with $4.50/lb. in 1994.
         <p>
        The Corporation's share of proven and probable ore reserves at 
        December 31, 1995 is estimated to be 21.0 million ozs. of gold, 
        compared with 19.8 million ozs. a year earlier.  In addition, the 
        Corporation's share of other mineralized material in the measured and 
        indicated category is estimated to contain 8.0 million ozs. of gold 
        at mines and 21.0 million ozs. at exploration properties.  The most 
        significant reserve additions come from the inclusion of new reserves 
        of 1.5 million ozs. from the South Pipeline deposit on the 60%-owned 
        Cortez Joint Venture property in the United States and 1.2 million 
        ozs. at Musselwhite in Canada.  The Dome, Campbell and Bald Mountain 
        mines also increased reserves.
         <p>
        The increase in gold estimated to be contained in other mineralized 
        material is accounted for chiefly by inclusion of results from the 
        Donlin Creek exploration project in Alaska and the Cerro Crucitas 
        project in Costa Rica.  Donlin Creek is estimated to contain 3.6 
        million ozs. of gold in 44.6 million tonnes of material grading an 
        average 2.5 grams of gold/tonne, based on a 1995 drilling programme 
        which is to be followed up in 1996 at a cost of $6 million.  The 
        Cerro Crucitas property, where further drilling is under way, is 
        estimated to contain 1.8 million ozs. of gold.  The Corporation 
        expects exploration expense for 1996 to be about $100 million, 
        compared with $110 million in 1995.
         <p>
        The Corporation today announced it will proceed with development of 
        the Musselwhite Mine in Canada.  (See separate news release issued 
        simultaneously.)  In 1995, our project development teams completed 
        the construction of the Zald&#237;var Mine in Chile and the Osborne Mine 
        in Australia, as well as expansion of the Dome Mine in Canada and the 
        Porgera Mine in Papua New Guinea.  Construction decisions are to be 
        considered in 1996 on the Pipeline project in the United States, Las 
        Cristinas project in Venezuela and Mt. Rawdon in Australia, while 
        also this year a feasibility study is to be completed on the Mulatos 
        gold deposit in Mexico and a pre-feasibility will start on the Cerro 
        Crucitas gold property in Costa
        Rica.

	
<p>

	For further information:<br>
    Investor Relations - Earl Dunlop  (604) 661-3779<br>
	Media Relations - Hugh Leggatt  (604) 661-1554<br>
	
    <br><br><br>

