	<tr>
	<td>

    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	<h2>
	Placer Dome approves construction of new gold mine in Canada
	</h2>

	<strong>
	February 22, 1996
	</strong>
	<p>
	
	(all dollar amounts in U.S. currency)
	<p>
	
	<strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc. announces that a positive decision has been
	made to construct a new gold mine at the Musselwhite property in northern Ontario,
	Canada, at a capital cost of $190 million.
		<p>
	Development of a mine and construction of processing facilities will start
	immediately on site, 500 kilometres north of Thunder Bay, in order to commence
	production in the second quarter of 1997.  Musselwhite is 68% owned by Placer Dome
	in a joint venture with TVX Gold Inc. of Toronto.  A feasibility study estimates
	total proven and probable reserves of 9.8 million tonnes of ore grading an average
	5.6 grams of gold/tonne, containing 1.8 million ozs. of gold.  The mine is
	forecast to produce 200,000 ozs. of gold per year for 10.6 years at an average
	cash production cost of $200/oz.  Other mineralized material identified at
	Musselwhite amounts to 3 million tonnes with an average grade of 5.8 grams
	gold/tonne containing 554,000 ozs. of gold.  Significant exploration potential
	exists to prolong mining beyond the 11-year mine life.
		<p>
	The feasibility study envisages a two-stage mining plan.  In the first stage a
	decline ramp will be developed to access ore in the top levels of the mine, using
	truck haulage to the mill, followed in later years by deeper underground mining
	requiring shaft access and ore hoisting.  In addition, lower-grade ore from a
	small open pit will be developed early to create an ore stockpile.  Processing
	facilities will be based on a mill with a nominal capacity of 3,300 tonnes of ore
	per day employing the conventional gravity separation, cyanide leach and
	carbon-in-pulp processes.  The ore is free-milling, providing gold recoveries of
	about 95%.
		<p>
	The project will employ about 500 people in its peak construction period.  When
	the mine starts operations in 1997 it will provide 282 new jobs in the region.  A
	key element of the project is an agreement ensuring the active participation of
	local First Nations communities.  Environmental impact and reclamation plans,
	including measures to protect water quality in rivers and lakes, have been
	approved by the Province of Ontario and the Government of Canada.
		<p>
	
For further information:<br>	
Investor Relations - Earl Dunlop  (604) 661-3779<br>	
Media Relations - Hugh Leggatt  (604) 661-1554<br>	
Thursday, February 22, 1996<br>	

	<br><br>
    
    </td>
    </tr>
	
