<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - The Latest</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	
	<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/06butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	</td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<table border=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top colspan=2>
	<img src="../gfx/09head.gif" alt="The Latest header gif">
	</td>
	
	<tr>
	<td>
	
    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	<strong>
	Marcopper Update #4
	</strong>
	
	<h2>
	Progress continues on repairs and mitigation
	</h2>

	<strong>
	September 23, 1996
	</strong>

	<h3>
	The Story so Far
	</h3>
	

	Placer Dome Inc. owns 40% of Marcopper Mining Corporation which operates a copper
	mine on Marinduque Island in the Philippines where a major escape of mine tailing,
	a mixture of sand and water, occurred on March 24, 1996, closing the mine.  A
	drainage tunnel plugged with concrete in order to impound tailing in a mined-out
	open pit gave way, spilling 4 million tonnes of material into the environment. 
	Fortunately no lives were lost and the tailing is not toxic to humans. 
	Independent studies, principally by United Nations teams, have confirmed that no
	persons became sick as a result of the accident, the main consequence of which was
	the overwhelming presence of silt in the river which smothered aquatic life. 
	Placer Dome is committed to rectifying the damage, and took a US$40 million charge
	against earnings in the second quarter to cover financial obligations for
	Marcopper, including US$15 million for the cost of repairs and environmental
	mitigation.
	<p>

	<h3>
	The Latest News
	</h3>

	Placer Dome reports that work continues on sealing the drainage tunnel from which
	the tailing escaped into the Boac River system.  The flow of tailing from the
	drainage tunnel has stopped, though water continues to flow.  A second tunnel is
	being advanced past the area of rock failure in the drainage tunnel to install a
	permanent plug.  Dredging of a channel at the mouth of the river is complete in
	order to capture tailing moved downstream in the wet season which is now in
	progress.
	<p>

	Following a meeting between the President of the Philippines, Fidel Ramos, and the
	President and Chief Executive Officer of Placer Dome, John Willson, on September
	16, Mr. Ramos expressed satisfaction with Placer Dome's ongoing efforts and said
	the Company is welcome to continue its involvement in the Philippines mineral
	industry.
	<p>

	Three Marcopper officials, two of them Placer Dome employees on secondment who
	have since resigned from Marcopper, have been charged with criminal offences in
	connection with the spill.  At a court hearing on September 5, 1996, the judge
	agreed to a motion filed by John Loney, formerly President of Marcopper, Steve
	Reid, formerly Resident Mine Manager, and Senior Manager Pete Hernandez, to
	dismiss the charges.  He gave the prosecution 20 days to respond.  Defence counsel
	will have another 20 days after that to reply.
	<p>

	The judge ruled that as the accused were exercising their rights to apply to
	dismiss the charges, there could be no arraignment until the outcome of the
	application is determined.  The Philippines Government meanwhile lifted Hold
	Departure Orders against Mr. Loney and Mr. Reid, allowing them to depart the
	Philippines pending their court appearances.  Mr. Loney remains Placer Dome's
	senior manager in the Philippines and Mr. Reid has taken up a position with Placer
	Dome in Vancouver, Canada.
	<p>

	Placer Dome has been negotiating with the major shareholder of Marcopper a
	survival plan that gives Marcopper the best structure for a real opportunity to
	re-open the mine and therefore provide:
	<p>

	<li type=bullet>ongoing well-paid employment;
	<li type=bullet>economic and social benefits for the citizens of Marinduque;
	<li type=bullet>the best chance of Marcopper meeting its remaining financial obligations.
	<p>

	In order to achieve these objectives, Placer Dome will acquire the financial
	obligations of the US$21 million Asian Development Bank loan to Marcopper and will
	be surrendering its 40% interest in Marcopper back to Marcopper.  Placer Dome will
	also be providing for development of an Environmental Reclamation Plan for the
	mine site to ensure that Marcopper can meet its future legal environmental
	rehabilitation requirements.  The cost of these obligations was included in Placer
	Dome's charge to earnings recorded in the second quarter.
	<p>

	<h3>
	Environmental Report
	</h3>
	
	<strong>
	Remediation of the Boac River
	</strong>
	<p>
	
	The first critical step towards the remediation of the Boac River, the dredging of
	a 1,000-metre-long channel near the river mouth, began July 27 and was completed
	earlier this month.
	<p>

	Dredging serves two purposes:

	<li type=bullet> The six-metre deep channel will act as a trap and permanent
	underwater storage facility for the coarse tailing which washes down the river,
	preventing it from reaching the sea;
	<p>

	<li type=bullet> The channel is also designed to reduce the additional risk of
	flooding which would be created if the tailing were allowed to build up in the
	delta area.
	<p>

	In order to remove the tailing from the river, Placer Dome has proposed a
	programme to continue to use the river as the main transport mechanism to remove
	the tailing from the Boac and Makulipnit channels and to transport the tailing to
	the dredged channel where the coarse fraction will settle out under safe disposal
	conditions.  Under this proposal, the fine material would continue to the ocean
	where it will disperse naturally over time in a manner which contains no long-term
	risk and which allows for the recovery of the marine environment. 
	<p>

	To minimize impacts and risks in the river system, it is proposed that mechanical
	methods be used to ensure tailing stored along the river channel is removed during
	the current rainy season.  The river has the ability to be restored quickly once
	the tailing has been removed from the channel, thus enabling normal aquatic and
	human activities to resume with minimum disruption to ongoing life in the river
	valley.  In comparison with other alternatives such as land-based disposal, the
	proposed programme will not take valuable land out of production or create any
	long-term impacts or risks.  Placer Dome will conduct community consultations on
	the proposed programme and its alternatives and seek Government permission before
	any action is taken.
	<p>

	<strong>
	Plugging the tunnel
	</strong>
	<p>

	For 12 consecutive weeks no tailing has been detected in the intermittent flow of
	water from the tunnel.  Work is under way to re-seal the tunnel.  The installation
	of a temporary plug by injecting mixed hot bitumen and concrete down bore holes
	into the tunnel where it will harden is continuing.  A second, fully engineered
	permanent plug has been designed and should be installed in the first quarter of
	1997 after physical access is gained through a second tunnel.
	<p>

	<h3>
	Environmental studies
	</h3>

	A series of environmental studies have been initiated to measure the impact of the
	spill and design measures to protect the health of the local residents.
	<p>
	
	<li type=bullet>A team of marine experts are monitoring effects on fish and
	aquatic life, and tailing dispersal in the ocean, to satisfy human health concerns
	and to predict long-term recovery.
	<p>

	<li type=bullet>Thirteen river monitoring sites are now being sampled on a
	fortnightly basis and a large database to aid scientific analysis has been
	established.  Tailing samples have been collected at one-metre intervals down the
	river and are being analyzed in Australia.  Results continue to show that the
	water and tailing material are not toxic to humans.
	<p>
	
	<li type=bullet>Residue quality studies include analysis of 17 agricultural soil
	samples collected from the flood plain of the Boac.
	<p>
	
	<li type=bullet>River behaviour studies involve the monitoring of sediment
	transport on a constant basis with the aid of 14 beacon sites, an aerial survey of
	the Boac and Mogpog rivers and a hydrographic survey of the marine environment
	offshore from the Boac River.
	<p>

	<li type=bullet>Environmental studies under way associated with the delta and
	dredge channel include:
	<p>
	
	-groundwater saline intrusion study,<br>
	-river water saline intrusion study,<br>
	-beach profiling,<br>
	-beach sand particle size distribution analysis,<br>
	-plume monitoring,<br>
	-tide monitoring.
	<p>
 
	<h3>
	Humanitarian aid
	</h3>

	Although no illnesses relating to the spill have been detected, medical missions
	funded by Placer Dome have been extended to 10 communities to continue monitoring
	human health and to provide medical treatment as required.
	<p>

	A social impact assessment is being conducted jointly by the University of the
	Philippines and the University of British Columbia, Canada.  It will provide a
	comprehensive, systematic and factual description of the impact of the tailing
	spill on local communities and will make recommendations regarding compensation
	and sustainable development options.  The study results from extensive community
	consultations, data collection and analysis.  It will be available to the public
	on request after mid-October.
	<p>

	For Further Information:<br>

	Hugh Leggatt<br>
	Placer Dome Inc., Vancouver, Canada<br>
	(604) 661-1554; Fax (604) 684-7261

	<br><br><br>
    
    </td>
    </tr>
	
