    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	
    <h2>Philippines charge Marcopper's Placer Dome managers</h2>
	
    <strong>June 21, 1996</strong>
    
    <p>

	<strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc. has been advised that three managers employed by
40%-owned Marcopper Mining Corporation in the Philippines are to be charged on Monday
with alleged criminal offences relating to the accidental escape of sand and water from a
containment at the mine in March.
  <p>
    They are John Loney, President of Marcopper, Steve Reid, Resident Mine Manager,
both Australian citizens, and Pedro Hernandez, manager of mining operations and a Philippine
citizen.  Mr. Loney and Mr. Hernandez are charged with reckless imprudence, violation of the
water code and violation of the Mining Act.  Mr. Reid also faces these charges, as well as an
additional allegation of violation of the Pollution Control Law.  Mr. Loney and Mr. Reid are
employees of the Placer Dome Group of Companies on secondment to Marcopper.  The
charges will be appealed immediately.
  <p>
    Placer Dome stands by those charged and will defend them in court.  The escape of
tailing (ground-up rock and water which was not toxic) was an accident, no injuries occurred
and there was limited property damage.  The accident should not be the subject of criminal
prosecution, particularly as there has been no opportunity for a technical investigation to be
conducted into what went wrong.  
<p>
    Placer Dome deplores the fact that in spite of the goodwill shown in its commitments to
the Philippine Government, the current work programme to clean up the river impacted by the
spill, and the efforts to assist residents affected by the spill, that the Philippine authorities are
proceeding with criminal charges against Marcopper employees.


    
    <p>

	
	For further information:<br>
    Investor Relations: Earl Dunlop (604) 661-3779<br>
	Media Relations: Hugh Leggatt (604) 661-1554<br>

	<br><br>
    
    </td>
    </tr>
	
