<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - The Latest</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	
	<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/06butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	</td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<table border=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top colspan=2>
	<img src="../gfx/09head.gif" alt="The Latest header gif">
	</td>
	
	<tr>
	<td>
	
    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	<strong>
	Marcopper Update #3
	</strong>
	
	<h2>
	The Marcopper spill: what is being done now
	</h2>

	<strong>
	June 21, 1996
	</strong>



    <h3>Background</h3>

	Marcopper Mining Corp. is a Philippine company incorporated in 1964 in which 
	Canada-based Placer Dome Inc. has a 39.9% shareholding.  Placer Dome acquired an 
	interest after an association with exploration of the mine property dating from 1956.  
	Marcopper has operated a copper mine on Marinduque Island in the south-central 
	Philippines since 1968.  During the development of the San Antonio orebody which 
	started production in 1992, Marcopper was directed by the Philippine Department of 
	Energy and Natural Resources (DENR) to cease the permitted disposition of tailing in 
	the ocean.  It was agreed by Marcopper and the DENR that the abandoned Tapian open 
	pit should be utilized for tailing disposal.  The Tapian Pit was used for this 
	purpose without incident for four years.
	
	<h3>What happened?</h3>
	
	On March 24, 1996, a fracturing of the rock around a concrete plug in a drainage 
	tunnel leading from the Tapian Pit to the Makalapnit River allowed a mixture of 
	ground-up rock and water, known as tailing, to escape from the Tapian Pit into the 
	Makalapnit and Boac Rivers.
	
    <p>

	The mine ceased operations on March 24 and remains closed.
	
    <p>

	Marcopper, with the assistance of engineers from the Placer Dome Group, quickly 
	succeeded in reducing the flow by 90%.  Placer Dome Technical Services Limited, 
	working under contract with Marcopper, is now coordinating all remedial work on the 
	tailing problem.
	
    <p>

	On April 17, 1996, Marcopper transferred funds from a 5.18-million-peso (US$207,000) 
	Environmental Guarantee Fund, established by the Company in compliance with its 
	Environmental Compliance Certificate, into a bank on Marinduque.  The fund is 
	administered by a committee comprised of Marinduque Governor Jose Carrion, Boac 
	Municipal Mayor Roberto Madia, the DENR Technical Director S.E. Tolentino and Senior 
	Marcopper Manager Ralph Ante.  The committee is chaired by the DENRs Environmental 
	Bureau Director Manual S. Gaspay.
	
    <p>

	Independent studies conducted by the United Nations and the Philippine Department of 
	Science and Technology have concluded that the escaped tailing is not toxic and does 
	not pose a health hazard.  In addition, it was concluded that the levels of heavy 
	metals do not exceed standards set by the DENR.
	
	
	<h3>Solving the tunnel problem</h3>
	
	<strong>What has been done?</strong><p>
	
	As a result of work done to date, the amount of material discharging from the tunnel 
	has been reduced from a volume of 140 litres of tailing per second when the accident 
	first occurred to an intermittent discharge of about 12 litres per second.  Two 
	emergency measures were undertaken to reduce the amount of materials escaping from 
	the tunnel.  First, water was pumped out of the Tapian Pit to reduce the hydraulic 
	pressure of the tailing.  Second, geotextile bags filled with concrete were installed 
	to partially seal the tunnel to reduce the flow.
	
	<h3>What is being done now?</h3>
	
	Placer Dome Technical Services with the support of Marcopper has assembled a team of 
	international specialists who will live and work on Marinduque Island until a 
	permanent plug in the tunnel is in place.  In order to stop the flow they are 
	devising unique solutions to a unique engineering challenge.  Twenty bore holes have 
	been drilled from the ground surface to the tunnel.  Grout and concrete have been 
	pumped into the tunnel area to seal the fractured rock and restrict the flow.  Next, 
	engineers will use a high pressure pump to force a liquid bitumen/cement mixture at 
	high temperatures through these holes into the tunnel where the mixture will solidify 
	to form a seal.  It is anticipated that this work will be completed in July.  A fully 
	engineered second plug is being designed and should be installed by year-end after 
	physical access to the area is gained through a second tunnel or shaft.
	
	
	<h3>Rehabilitating the river</h3>
	
	<strong>What has been done?</strong><p>
	
	As an emergency measure to prevent the tailing deposited in the Boac River bed from 
	spreading and to minimize the annual flooding which naturally occurs in the area, 
	crews of mine workers have built 22 kilometres of levees along the riverbank above 
	the town of Boac.
	<p>

	<strong>What is being done now?</strong><p>
	
	With the containment plan  the construction of levees along the riverbank  nearly 
	completed, the first phase of river rehabilitation can begin.  The Company has 
	formulated dredging plans which are currently being discussed with relevant 
	Government authorities prior to a permit being sought. Studies are currently being 
	conducted of the river system to determine the options for the removal and 
	disposition of the tailing currently in the river bed.  Once those options have been 
	determined, Marcopper will present its findings to members of the local community and 
	seek approval from the relevant authorities.
	
	
	<h3>Protecting and helping members of the community affected by the spill</h3>
	
	<strong>What has been done?</strong><p>
	
	A total of 158 core shelters are under construction to house community members who 
	have chosen to relocate after the accident to higher ground to minimize the risk from 
	flooding.  These sturdy, all-weather dwellings built by local workers feature a 
	cement floor, concrete block foundation and metal roofing.
	
    <p>

	Construction of 16 kilometres of new, all-weather roads has been completed to connect 
	residents isolated by the spill to the rest of the island.  The surfacing of these 
	new roads is nearly complete.
	
    <p>

	A medical mission was organized to monitor the health of the five affected 
	communities and to provide regular medical care.  In addition, another five 
	communities not affected by the spill have asked to receive free medical care and 
	medicines.  Although no illnesses connected to the spill have been diagnosed by the 
	attending physicians, members of the 10 communities are receiving medical care and 
	health education for other health problems to which they are normally exposed.
	
    <p>

	Marcopper staff continue to distribute food and household supplies to residents of 
	six communities.  As of May 31, 1996, the Company had distributed over 1.5 million 
	pesos (US$60,000) worth of supplies to affected families.
	
	<h3>What is being done now?</h3>
	
	Programs to ensure the health and safety of local residents in affected areas 
	continue.  Groundwater and drinking water is being tested regularly.  An independent 
	community-based committee continues to review compensation claims and establish a 
	priority for disbursements.


	<p>

	For Further Information:<br>

	Hugh Leggatt<br>
	Placer Dome Inc., Vancouver, Canada<br>
	(604) 661-1554; Fax (604) 684-7261

	<br><br><br>
    
    </td>
    </tr>
	
