<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - The Latest</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	
	<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/06butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	</td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<table border=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top colspan=2>
	<img src="../gfx/09head.gif" alt="The Latest header gif">
	</td>
	
	<tr>
	<td>
	
    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	<strong>
	Marcopper update #2
	</strong>
	
	<h2>
	Placer Dome makes commitments to remedy mine spill
	</h2>


	Placer Dome Inc. owns 40% of Marcopper Mining Corporation which operates a copper 
	mine on Marinduque Island in the south-central Philippines where a major escape of 
	mine tailing, a mixture of sand and water, occurred on March 24.  This is our second 
	update on developments.
	
	
	<h3>The flow has stopped</h3>
	
	After flowing intermittently and at a much reduced rate after the first four days of 
	unimpeded escape, the discharge of tailing stopped of its own accord.  This may be 
	temporary as flows have resumed before.  It is believed that the drainage tunnel 
	leading from the mined-out Tapian pit from which the escape occurred is blocked with 
	the flow of solids. 
	
    <p>

	Because the flow stopped without human intervention, it remains necessary to install 
	a temporary concrete plug in the tunnel, then to determine what exactly happened to 
	cause the escape and to design a permanent solution.  Four holes have been drilled 
	from surface to intersect the tunnel and an attempt is being made to pump concrete 
	down the holes to form a temporary new plug.  Alternatives for a lasting solution are 
	being sought with the help of Philippine and international geotechnical consultants.
	
	
	<h3>Charges said to be filed</h3>
	
	The Department of Environment and Natural Resources has recommended to the Justice 
	Department that charges be filed against five Marcopper executives for reckless 
	imprudence resulting in damage to property, and violations of the Water Code, 
	Pollution Control Law and the 1995 Mining Law.  They are John Loney, an Australian, 
	President of Marcopper, Steve Reid, an Australian, Resident Mine Manager (both 
	seconded from the Placer Dome Group), and Filipino senior operations managers Pedro 
	Hernandez, Manuel Quing and Ralph Ante.
	
    <p>

	It is Placer Domes understanding that the Justice Department must determine whether, 
	if charges are brought, there is sufficient evidence for the charges to succeed in 
	court.  Hearings to make this determination were due to be held this week, but to 
	date there has been no notification either to Marcopper or the individuals involved 
	that charges relating to the accident have been filed.
	
    <p>

	Placer Dome does not believe criminal charges are appropriate as the escape of 
	tailing was an accident.  If charges are filed, Placer Dome will defend against them 
	and provide every support to its employees in the Philippines.  
	
    <p>

	It is important however that the Department of Environment and Natural Resources and 
	Marcopper cooperate in reaching appropriate solutions to the accident.  This would be 
	facilitated by a stay of proceedings.  Marcopper is working towards this goal in the 
	interests of improving dialogue in order to expedite remedial actions.
	
	
	<h3>Commitments to remedy damage</h3>
	
	The accident has imposed hardship on the lives of many Filipinos (about 600 families 
	have been directly affected) as well as government administrators and Marcopper and 
	Placer Dome employees.
	
    <p>

	While no injuries or illness are attributable to the accident, the residents of 
	Marinduque have suffered personal inconvenience or damage.  They will be quickly and 
	fairly compensated.  Marcopper had previously established an Environmental Guarantee 
	Fund adjudicated by a broadly representative committee.  Placer Dome will use its 
	best efforts to ensure that this fund receives the financial support of Marcoppers 
	shareholders.  If  the fund proves less than adequate for the compensation required 
	to be paid, Placer Dome will provide supplementary contributions as needed.
	
    <p>

	Government expenses incurred because of direct assistance to people affected by the 
	accident should be reimbursed from the fund.
	
    <p>

	While Placer Dome and Marcopper remain certain the material that escaped is not 
	harmful to human health, Marcopper will continue to monitor the health of residents 
	affected and their drinking water.  A third party will conduct an independent 
	assessment of the health effects of the accident and Placer Dome, if requested, will 
	pay for the work.
	
    <p>

	Once the flow of tailing is permanently halted, a comprehensive environmental 
	rehabilitation programme will be conducted to remedy impacts on the river, to improve 
	road access to villages, to implement flood protection, to monitor long-term health 
	and the environment and to develop a plan to ameliorate conditions in the ocean at 
	the mouth of the river.
	
    <p>

	For these purposes a Marcopper Rehabilitation Fund will be established by Marcopper 
	with an initial contribution from Placer Dome.  In addition, it has been proposed 
	that Marcopper in consultation with the Government, will appoint an independent, 
	widely recognized, technical research organization to advise on the rehabilitation 
	programme.
	
    <p>

	Because the people of the Philippines have a right to know what went wrong, Placer 
	Dome and Marcopper will cooperate fully in any commissions of inquiry convened by 
	government to establish the causes of the accident and to prevent a recurrence. Mr. 
	A.M. (Sandy) Laird, Senior Vice-President, Placer Dome Group, who was a member of the 
	Marcopper project team during construction and the first Resident Mine Manager from 
	1968, has been appointed by John Willson, President and CEO, to take management 
	control of Placer Domes interests with respect to the Marcopper situation.
	
	
	<h3>Placer Dome will retain its leadership status</h3>
	
	Placer Dome has been commended for providing information in a spirit of open 
	communication with all interested parties whatever their point of view.
	
    <p>

	The Governments of the Philippines and of Canada as well as United Nations agencies 
	have become involved in the aftermath of the accident and calls have gone out from 
	critics for stricter environmental laws to control Canadian mining companies working 
	internationally.  
	
    <p>

	We point out that this regrettable event was an accident arising from a failure of a 
	designed installation and that conceivably the same failure could have arisen 
	anywhere in the world, including Canada, in spite of laws and standards.
	
    <p>

	Perfection cannot be legislated; it must be strived for.  Placer Dome has made 
	repeated commitments to become a leader in the mining community in environmental 
	protection, in minimizing the impact of mining, and reclaiming land upon mine 
	closure.  Placer Dome has received many environmental awards in recognition of its 
	leadership in Canada, the Philippines, Australia, Chile and the United States.
	
    <p>

	We will continue, with even greater intensity of commitment to environmental and 
	social ideals, to gain acceptance for our activities world-wide.

	<p>

	For Further Information:<br>

	Hugh Leggatt<br>
	Placer Dome Inc., Vancouver, Canada<br>
	(604) 661-1554; Fax (604) 684-7261

	<br><br><br>
    
    </td>
    </tr>
	
