<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - The Latest</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	
	<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/06butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	</td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<table border=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top colspan=2>
	<img src="../gfx/09head.gif" alt="The Latest header gif">
	</td>
	
	
	<tr>
	<td>
	

   	<br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>
    
    <strong>
	Marcopper Update #4
	</strong>
	
    <h2>Environmental accident involves Placer Dome</h2>
	     
    <strong>April 9, 1996</strong>
    <p>

        Marcopper Mining Corporation, 39.9%-owned by Placer Dome, has operated a 
        copper mine on Marinduque Island in the south-central Philippines since 1968.
          <p>
          On March 24, 1996 a massive flow of mine waste called tailing, a 
          mixture of sand and water, started escaping from a drainage tunnel 
          into the environment, in the most regrettable environmental accident 
          in which Placer Dome has been involved.


          <h3>Source of the Problem</h3>

          During the development of the San Antonio orebody, Marcopper was 
          directed by the Philippine Department of Energy and Natural Resources 
          (DENR) to cease the permitted disposition of tailing in the ocean.  
          It was agreed by Marcopper and DENR that the abandoned Tapian open 
          pit should be utilized for tailing disposal and permits were granted 
          on this basis.  A concrete plug in a disused drainage tunnel was 
          designed and installed by Marcopper personnel.  The Tapian pit has 
          been used as a reservoir without incident for four years.
          <p>
          However, in August 1995 water seeps were observed above the mouth of 
          the tunnel and, as a precautionary measure, equipment was mobilized 
          to drill holes into the tunnel to place a second concrete plug at the 
          midpoint.  Access had just been achieved when the tailing discharge 
          occurred.  On March 24, the flow of tailing out of the mouth of the 
          tunnel started at a rate of 5 to 10 cubic metres per second.  This 
          continued for four days, increasing to higher water flows as the 
          tailing density dropped. During this period approximately 2.4 million 
          tonnes of tailing solids discharged into the river. The tailing is a 
          mixture of sand, water and traces of copper minerals and is non-toxic 
          (no cyanide is used in the copper-recovery process).  Water analysis 
          is being conducted continuously at 15 points along the 24-kilometre 
          length of the river.  No threat to the health and welfare of local 
          inhabitants has been detected.  Residents in the area do not depend 
          on the river for drinking water and use it mainly for irrigation and 
          washing clothes.
          <p>
          The most serious environmental effect of the accident is the build-up 
          of sediment on the river banks and at crossing places.  There have 
          been a number of confirmed reports of fish deaths caused by the flows 
          of silt.  To mitigate the effect of the sediment build-up on access 
          by local residents, the Company has hired helicopters to help people 
          cross the river where necessary.  The helicopters are also taking 
          medical teams to the affected areas to monitor the health of local 
          residents.


          <h3>Subsequent Situation</h3>

          The flow of tailing stopped on its own after four days and has 
          subsequently flowed intermittently at reduced volume and variable 
          density at about half a cubic metre per second, discharging between 
          50,000 tonnes to 100,000 tonnes per day of solids.
          <p>
          The immediate priority is to install a temporary plug in the tunnel, 
          then to determine the cause of the escape of tailing and with the 
          help of independent experts to design and implement a permanent 
          solution to secure the tailing impoundment.
          <p>
          Tailing has been confined to the river bed except for a spill over 6 
          to 10 hectares of banana and coconut plantation.  Heavy sedimentation 
          has occurred in the first 14 km of the Boac river while fine-grained 
          material has been washed out to sea at the mouth of the river, 25 km 
          downstream from the mine.  Equipment continues to work in the river 
          bed to ensure the tailing does not impede the river flow and that the 
          flow is contained within the river banks.
          <p>
          Since the access track to communities upstream follows and crosses 
          the river bed, assistance has been provided to local residents who 
          have been stranded by the deposition of solids on the river bed. 
          Marcopper, supported by government agencies, has transported water, 
          food and medical supplies to isolated families.  Foot bridges have 
          been built where appropriate.  No one has been injured and no adverse 
          health effects have been confirmed.  An assessment of property damage 
          is under way.
          <p>  
          On the Island of Marinduque cooperation between Marcopper and 
          National, Provincial and local officials has been and continues to be 
          at a high level.
          <p>
          Employees who can perform useful and necessary work are being 
          retained at the mine while those who are unessential are being 
          temporarily terminated but with continuing financial support.  An 
          effort will be made to rotate employees in jobs as circumstances 
          permit.

          <h3>Relations with Government</h3>

          The Philippine Government has reported to the media that Placer Dome 
          is banned from working in the Philippines although Marcopper has 
          received no official communication to that effect.  Officials have 
          confirmed, however, that Placer's expatriate employees assisting in 
          the recovery operations are welcome and will not be subjected to any 
          sanctions.
          <p>
          The Government has announced commissions of enquiry and Marcopper 
          will assist and will cooperate fully with any investigations into the 
          incident.  The Government has also stated that criminal charges may 
          be laid against Marcopper and its management and may take action to 
          cancel the Environmental Compliance Certificate and the Mining Lease.
          <p>
          Concurrently, the Government of Canada has agreed to a request by the 
          Chairman of the Philippine Senate Committee on Environment to provide 
          the standards applicable in Canada and to provide Placer Dome's 
          environmental record.  We are cooperating with the Canadian 
          Departments of Environment and Foreign Affairs in this matter.
          <p>
          Simultaneously, the Government of Canada has received an enquiry from 
          the United Nations Department of Humanitarian Affairs in Geneva, 
          prompted by the United Nations Development Program in Manila, as to 
          whether the Canadian government would provide technical assistance in 
          the remediation of the Marcopper spill.  The Government of Canada has 
          decided not to provide technical assistance, on the basis that 
          Marcopper and Placer Dome have the capacity and willingness to do the 
          remediation.


          <h3>Prognosis</h3>

          When permanent repairs have been made to the tailing impoundment, or 
          an alternative storage is identified, Government approvals will be 
          sought to re-open the mine.  This may occur within six months.
          <p>
          It is probable that much of the tailing solids in the river will be 
          flushed out to sea during the next typhoon season (about October) and 
          any that remains will lie on the river bottom or on the banks where 
          it will be revegetated.  It is unlikely that any long term 
          environmental damage will occur.  However, an independent, 
          scientifically oriented third party will review long term remediation 
          plans.
          <p>
          The accident is likely to remain politically prominent in the 
          Philippines for some time to come, with commissions of investigation, 
          as well as possible criminal charges and civil suits.  Although the 
          long term environmental consequences will be minimal, this will 
          continue to be a significant black mark against Placer Dome, its 
          environmental practices and its engineering standards.
          <p>  
          Immense effort goes into maintaining high environmental standards 
          throughout the Placer Dome Group and a strong record of protection 
          has been achieved.  While an incident has occurred that should not 
          have happened, it is not representative of Placer Dome's striving to 
          apply the best environmental management practices.

    <p>

	
	For further information:<br>
    Investor Relations: Earl Dunlop (604) 661-3779<br>
	Media Relations: Hugh Leggatt (604) 661-1554<br>

	<br><br>
    
    </td>
    </tr>
	
