<HEAD>
<TITLE>Placer Dome - The Latest</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	
	<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/06butbar.gif" alt="Button links - image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	</td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<table border=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top colspan=2>
	<img src="../gfx/09head.gif" alt="The Latest header gif">
	</td>
	
	<tr>
	<td>

    <br>
    <a href="09c.html">Back to "Current News Releases"</a>
    
    <p>

	<h2>
	Progress made to control Marcopper spill
	</h2>
	
	<strong>
	March 29, 1996
	</strong>
	<p>

	<strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome advises of measures being taken to control the
	major escape of mill tailing from an impoundment at the 39.9%-owned Marcopper Mine
	in the Philippines.  Sand and water residue from the copper recovery process
	stored in a mined-out pit started escaping through a drainage tunnel in the pit
	when a concrete plug failed on March 24, discharging sediment into the Boac River.
		<p>
	Late on March 28 the tailing discharge stopped of its own accord, bringing some
	relief to the situation. Engineers are studying the reasons for the stoppage. 
	Preparations are being made to instal a new temporary plug while a long-term
	permanent solution is being sought.
		<p>
	Marcopper is implementing the following measures:
		<p>
	<li type=bullet>Water is being pumped out of the mill residue stored in the pit to
	reduce the pressure and mobility of the tailing mix.  The most secure methods of
	sealing the drainage tunnel are being considered by a technical team comprising
	experts from the Philippines, South Africa, Australia and Canada.
		<p>
	<li type=bullet>The Company has started a monitoring programme with the Department
	of the Environment and Natural Resources (DENR) to ensure there is no danger to
	human health. The tailing is not toxic.  Chemical analyses of the discharge have
	confirmed that it has no toxicity for people or livestock.  Marcopper and DENR are
	continuing to conduct independent tests of the discharge and will share their
	findings.
		<p>
	<li type=bullet>While there is no threat to the health and welfare of local
	inhabitants, access to and from villages has been restricted as a result of
	sediment build-up in the river.  The Company is minimizing the build-up by
	deepening the river channel and constructing levee banks to safeguard agricultural
	land.  Food is being supplied to affected communities and this will continue until
	normal access across the river is restored.
		<p>
	
	For further information:<br>
	Investor Relations - Earl Dunlop  (604) 661-3779<br>
	Media Relations - Hugh Leggatt  (604) 661-1554<br>
	
	<br><br><br>
    </td>
    </tr>
	
    <tr>
