    <p>
						

	<h2>Environmental incident at Philippine mine</h2>
    
    <strong>March 26, 1996</strong>
    
    <p>

    <strong>Vancouver, Canada</strong> - Placer Dome Inc. advises that a major escapement of mill tailing has occurred at the 39.9%-owned Marcopper Mine in the Philippines.  The health and welfare of local inhabitants is not believed to be at risk, but their safety is being continuously monitored.  The Company is deeply concerned about the effects on the area and urgent and intensive measures are under way to bring the situation under control.
	 The tailing left after the extraction of copper is a mixture of sand and water 
	containing traces of copper mineral.  It is impounded in a mined-out pit at the 
	copper mine operated on the Island of Marinduque.  The material is discharging from a 
	tunnel that was developed to drain the pit when it was being mined.  The tunnel was 
	plugged with concrete before residues were deposited in the pit and it has been 
	secure for four years.
	
	Routine monitoring detected seepage of water in the tunnel area late last year and 
	plans were progressing toward installing a second concrete plug.  The escape of 
	tailing, which was detected on March 24, occurred before this procedure could be 
	completed.  A number of measures to stem the flow are being attempted.  Meanwhile 
	mill operations have been suspended.
	
	The environmental effects are chiefly a build-up of sediment in the Boac River, with 
	mud deposited on the banks and at crossing places.  Residents are not dependent on 
	the river for drinking water.  The Company has hired helicopters to assist residents 
	at river crossings and to help in other ways as required.  All relevant authorities 
	have been informed of the situation. 


		<p>
	
	For further information:<br>
	Investor Relations - Earl Dunlop  (604) 661-3779<br>
	Media Relations - Hugh Leggatt  (604) 661-1554<br>
	
	<br><br><br>

