	<p>
	

	<h2>
	Corporate Strategy: Focus on the Gold Industry</a><br>
	</h2>
    
    <font size=-1>
    <strong>CIM 1997 Mineral Economics Society Symposium Cordilleran Roundup<br></strong>
    January 27, 1997<br>
    Hotel Vancouver<br>
    Vancouver, Canada<br>

    <p>
	<strong>Written by John M. Willson, President & CEO,  Placer Dome Group<br> 
	Delivered by A.M. (Sandy) Laird, Senior Vice-President, 
	Placer Dome Group</strong>
    </font>

    <p>


    John was tempted to name this talk "The Throne Speech".   This is 
    not because he thought he had the best strategy here today, but 
    because his speech outline was composed while he was locked in the 
    washroom at his office.
    <p>
     The inside door handle came off in his hand and our CEO was 
     marooned for 25 minutes while someone was found to rescue him.  
     So once his assistant had squeezed documents and a pen under the 
     door, he had lots of time to read the briefing notes for this 
     conference and to ponder his strategy.
    <p>
     It struck us when reading the list of participants who are here 
     today, that we should have some others here also, to talk about 
     their strategies.  We had in mind people like Peter Munk, Robert 
     Friedland, Norman Keevil, Michael Sopko.  After all, these are 
     the people who are breaking the norms, no pun intended, Norm.
    <p>
     For myself, it is a pleasure to be here, to be numbered among this
     august set of speakers.
    <p>
     To talk strategy is an easy topic.  After all, that is what CEOs are
     supposed to worry about all the time.  First of all, what is strategy,
     what does it mean?  For Peter Munk - and we have read some of his book
     - it is the be-all and end-all.   He says it doesn't matter what you
     pay, what matters is what you do, what strategy you apply.  The trick
     these days may perhaps be how you get to pay at all, with Munk
     pre-empting the best deposits the way he is.
    <p>
     From this insight, one could ask does strategy mean how you go about
     leading the company?  Does it mean what vision of the future you
     develop?  What your big picture is?
    <p>
     Does it mean how the Company goes about its business?  Its value
     system and the way it is applied?
    <p>
     The background material on the purpose of this discussion suggests
     that what we are focusing on here is the strategy applied by a company
     to get its hands on more mineral reserves.
    <p>
     Much of John's experience in leading a company has been in the gold
     industry, first with Pegasus in Spokane, and from 1993, with Placer
     Dome.  Gold mining is not base metal mining, it has a different
     alchemy.  This alchemy is what I will try to explain today as one of
     the biggest gold players here - no disrespect to Clive or Milt.
    <p>
     In the course of being a CEO with gold mining companies, John has been
     fortunate to be able to put into practice some of the ways of
     developing a strategy.  At Pegasus he conducted a process that
     involved senior employees in devising the strategy the company would
     adopt.
    <p>
     When he came to Placer Dome, he joined a company that already had a
     well-defined strategy and very good people to implement it.  We
     fine-tuned the strategy however by conducting a similar but much
     deeper employee consultation process, involving employees, managers,
     senior managers and the Board of Directors.
    <p>
     We basically asked employees: What kind of company do you think Placer
     Dome should be in five years' time and how should it get there?  This
     proved to be an excellent way of determining what is important.
    <p>
     In the end, we concluded that Placer Dome will focus on gold
     exploration, development and production, and because copper often
     occurs with gold we would produce that metal also, but no more than
     the equivalent of 25% of revenues.  We set a target for gold
     production which has since been revised upwards.  We set a cash cost
     goal in the lower tercile. And we set out a business philosophy and
     values statement to govern our conduct.
    <p>
     There has been very good buy-in to the result, but as usual we failed
     to provide enough good feedback and reinforcement within the Company
     and now we must revive the process.
    <p>
     Currently our strategy has taken a new turn with renewed focus on
     improving the quality of our gold production by concentrating on
     developing and operating large, long-life, low-cost gold mines.  This
     is what has been driving the asset sales we announced late last year.
    <p>
     The underlying thought in setting a strategy is finding out what is
     important, given the business we are in and the nature of our market
     and shareholders.
    <p>
     A couple of years ago, we were provided with a survey on what is
     important to investors who buy, or are considering buying, gold
     shares.  The survey was thorough and targeted analysts and fund
     managers.
   <p>
     <strong>GROWTH POTENTIAL</strong><br>
     At the top of the chart [on the screen] is Growth Potential.  If 
     you ask Frank Mirsh at Altamira what is the key issue for good 
     miners, he will say it is growth.  Well, you say, what does that 
     mean?
    <p>
     Earnings growth, cash flow growth, reserves-resources growth, what
     growth?  It is production growth that counts.  He is very clear on
     that.  Does quality of the growth not matter? Well, yes, but only if
     it is seriously poor quality.
    <p>
     So if you have growth potential, you probably have good reserves, you
     probably have clever explorationists, you probably have good mine
     builders in-house, and operators and mine reclamation people, all of
     which give you the ability to convince the market that you can go on
     forever, which is the assumption they must implicitly make to accord
     you, the gold company, the kind of magnificent multiples that we get
     as good long-term gold miners.
    <p>
     So perhaps the Growth word in fact means much more than one's
     likelihood of growing, it also implies excellence in many areas.
    <p>
     <strong>MANAGEMENT QUALITY</strong><br>
     Management quality must be good, durable, deep, modern, conservative
     in reporting, entrepreneurial in action, flexible, steady and
     believable as leaders to the market and the employees of the company.
    <p>
     <strong>ABILITY TO DEVELOP MINES</strong><br>
     This means to turn exploration into production at the least cost, to
     mine the ever-lowering average grade of ore, to design and build
     reliably.  We at Placer Dome have all this probably more than anyone
     else.
    <p>
     <strong>RESERVE ESTIMATES</strong><br>
     As we all know there are reserve estimates, and reserve 
     estimates. Ounces in the ground are not all equal, and despite 
     efforts to standardize, estimates vary.  Some companies are known 
     for putting the best face on reserves, others are known to be 
     conservative and the market will therefore credit variability to 
     different companies based on their track records.
    <p>
     Reserve estimates are a piece of the growth equation and the longevity
     equation, so it is not surprising they are important.
    
     <p>
     <strong>OVERALL FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE</strong><br>
     The gold community is, in my personal opinion, little troubled by low
     earnings, so long as they are not chronically low or negative.
     Write-downs appear to be relatively easily forgiven.  They appear to
     look through the earnings to cash, and they like to see it spent, not
     on yield, but on growth.  Growth is exploration, acquisitions and more
     mines.
    <p>
     <strong>EXPLORATION TEAM - QUALITY</strong><br>
     In our business, exploration is where the value is added and a quality
     exploration team is what one needs if you are to "out-multiple" the
     competition.  Quality, and lower down the list you see up on the
     screen, high activity in exploration, is not easy to come by.  Much of
     the entrepreneurial talent has "gone junior", and good mine finders
     like David Lowell are in short supply.  In fact, they are likely the
     most critical shortage in our industry.
    <p>
     Exploration quality is not, of course, merely a matter of having the
     very best mine finders and geologists.  It is also very much a matter
     of strategy and the way you are organized.  Our exploration strategy
     mirrors the way our whole international company is organized, such
     that there is a great deal of autonomy at the local/regional level
     with scope at that level for initiative and freedom of action, but, on
     the other hand, we reprioritize our considerable exploration
     expenditures four times a year on a worldwide basis in accordance with
     the manner in which projects are developing.
    <p>
     This is not easy to do effectively.  Not easy because good
     entrepreneurial geologists do not like to have their pet projects
     closed down in favour of someone else's pet project in a different
     part of the country or of the world.  To achieve such prioritization
     effectively, the whole exploration team must be focused on the
     ultimate success of the parent company, Placer Dome Inc.  And there is
     also a very strong need for a fearless leader of the worldwide
     programme who is willing to call the shots as he sees them following a
     participative process in which all senior geological managers agree on
     the geological and commercial merits of the projects being compared.
    <p>
     Another strategy for exploration executives is to get your geological
     talent in the field.   Organizing moving vans, visiting ambassadors or
     currying favour with government officials is not in the job
     description.

     <p>
     <strong>MANAGEMENT CONTINUITY</strong><br>
     Once a management group is formed and settles down and is successful,
     it is a  good idea to have it stick around for a while.  It represents
     an opportunity for it to carry out a consistent strategy and succeed
     at it.  Much could be said about this.  Some would say top management,
     or its leadership, needs to be turned over fairly regularly so that it
     does not become set in its ways.
    <p>
     We agree to some extent with that thought, and some turnover in the
     top is appropriate, but only if there is a centre of stability in
     management and the Board that keeps the ship steering a pretty steady
     course.  At Placer, we have achieved a stable senior management team
     with a very stable Board of Directors which agree on and adhere to the
     Company's strategies and policies, while not ceasing to cast around
     through an annual Strategic Planning Review for new and more
     shareholder beneficial paradigms.
     <p>
     <strong>MANAGEMENT DEPTH</strong><br>
     In order to be able to grow as our shareholders want us to, and to run
     our exploration, mine-building and operations well, we need to
     continuously develop all our people.  Particularly, perhaps, we need
     to develop our technical people who will form the backbone of our
     activities, and our financial people who make it possible to optimize
     our activities and to find the money necessary to take the quantum
     leap when we occasionally identify those opportunities.
    <p>
     Depth of management is particularly important when an opportunity like
     Busang comes along.  To design and build and operate Busang will
     require an enormous commitment of resources of the human and financial
     kind.  In this sense, to be able to move top class people into the
     activity without compromising other ongoing corporate priorities is a
     huge strength that nobody in the gold industry can match.  Placer Dome
     can deploy a world class team to implement this project immediately,
     despite the fact that it is in the closing stages of two mine-building
     programmes in North America and in the opening stage of a third and
     very large one in South America.  Such an ability illustrates great
     management depth, as I say, second to none in the gold business.
    <p>
     Do I make a relevant and topical point?  I hope so!
    
     <p>
     <strong>EXPLORATION TEAM - HIGH ACTIVITY</strong><br>
     Not far below the quality of the team comes its level of activity.
     This can be measured by the budget with which it is endowed, in Placer
     Dome's case one of the most aggressive in our business, and the volume
     of projects at all different stages from pure grassroots to
     feasibility study status.
    
     <p>
     <strong>LIQUIDITY</strong><br>
     In the sense of the survey, this relates, of course, to the ability of
     the shareholders of the corporation to buy and sell its stock, in
     large lumps, rapidly and with minimal market impact.  This has come
     about in our Company as a result of what has been achieved, and along
     with the other high market cap gold stocks, it tends to make us a part
     of most fund's portfolios, and also a so-called trading stock.
    <p>
     We are lucky to be there.
    <p>
     <strong>
     ACQUISITION STRATEGY</strong><br>
     It is surprising to me that this is so low in the field of what is
     important, since it is evident that if one is successful at
     acquisition the Company can do very well indeed.  A successful
     acquisition is obviously an acquisition where one does not pay too
     much for what the project eventually becomes.
    <p>
     Barrick's Goldstrike is the one acquisition that no one will argue was
     a brilliant one.  It has formed the foundation and backbone of the
     company.  So many people turned it down, then Peter Munk took the risk
     and paid what everyone said was a silly price, and it came up trumps!
    <p>
     But analysis shows that while acquisitions are good for the acquiree,
     they are rarely good for the acquirer.  Too often, especially right
     now, the competition is so fierce that a reasonably priced acquisition
     simply cannot be made.
    <p>
     That is why, in my opinion, exploration success is put so much higher
     up the list.  It is patently obvious that if we can find good quality
     reserves at $36/oz, then that will beat good quality reserves
     purchased at $130/oz.
    <p>
     We have a capable and considerable Corporate Development department
     which has been beavering away for a few years in its post-Mount
     Milligan form.  We do not make a lot of noise about it - in fact we
     frequently get letters from frustrated shareholders wishing that we
     made a lot more noise - but you see some of what we are doing fairly
     clearly at the moment.
    
     <p>
     <strong>RESPONSIBILITY</strong><br>
     It is good to see this so high up the list, much higher than I would
     have expected it.  One has the feeling that fund managers and analysts
     do not much care how the company achieves its goals of higher
     shareholder return, so long as it does it.
    <p>
     But over the years we have come to be encouraged by the fact that some
     of them really do care about the image of the company they own.  More,
     unfortunately, do not.  Stocks are simply chips to play in the
     business of improving returns.
    <p>
     Anyway, more and more today, responsibility is quite properly expected
     of our industry.  As time goes on, this will become increasingly
     important as standards quite rightly continue to become higher.
    <p>
     My company prides itself on being a responsible one, and nowhere is
     that better illustrated than in the Philippines where Marcopper had an
     unfortunate accident resulting from a concrete plug placed in a tunnel
     many years ago that failed.  While no persons or domestic animals were
     killed, the Boac river was filled with tailing, and it will take years
     to recover.
    <p>
     Despite the fact that we own only 40% of the company, we are paying
     for 100% of the remediation, the Marcopper company having no money and
     the other shareholders being unwilling to contribute.  It would have
     been easy to walk away, but not only would that have been extremely
     contrary to the responsible stance that we take, but more
     pragmatically it would have made life very difficult for us whenever
     we next tried to permit a mine.  In fact, at this moment, one of our
     competitors is highlighting our Marcopper problem in its own interest.
    <p>
     <strong>INTERNATIONAL OUTLOOK</strong><br>
     This is an essential feature, we believe, in the never-so-open world
     that is mining today.  We had a good start at this, with operations in
     Papua New Guinea in the 1930s, and we are now more diverse
     geographically than any of our peers.  We regard this as a critical
     strategic advantage.
    <p>
     It takes many years to develop the skills needed to be effective
     internationally.  One does not develop an experienced and seasoned
     cadre of commercial and technical people overnight, who can be relied
     upon to go wherever they need to go, to be effective when they arrive,
     and to hold up the Company's values through it all.
    <p>
     It is not cheap to develop this international cadre of people.  Much
     training and job exposure is needed in different environments.  Much
     sensitivity training is necessary so that the customs and
     sensitivities of the host nation are respected in word and in deed by
     our people.
    <p>
     Cross fertilization, cross-training, language training, international
     transfers, international training exposure, compensation for foreign
     conditions, home leave, is all expensive but necessary in an
     international company.  Chileans in Canada, Australians in the United
     States, Americans in Australia, Canadians all over the world since
     Canada is still our biggest employer, it all costs but there is no way
     to do without it.
    <p>
     Sometimes there is a reluctance to accept international assignments.
     To try to resolve this inflexibility, we are very actively recruiting
     those young and promising professionals who truly express an interest
     in getting a lot of varied international experience, to pick up
     foreign languages, to learn to respect other peoples' ways, their
     customs, their religions, their sensitivities, in short, to have an
     international outlook.
    <p>
     Just a couple more comments on these strategy points.

     <p>
     <strong>QUALITY OF THE INVESTOR RELATIONS EFFORT</strong><br>
     This is one of the more lowly issues according to this survey, but we
     would argue with this conclusion.  If you had been at Pegasus in 1989
     when the realization came that the good grade at Montana Tunnels was
     not as good as it was supposed to be,  and you had to deal with that
     problem effectively, and you had seen your market capitalization drop
     by 10% in two days, you might understand why we think it is very
     important.
    <p>
     We contend that as long as it is well done, great additional frills
     and fanciness do not benefit anyone much, but if it is badly done, you
     will pay for it in spades.  The difference between a good Investor
     Relations programme and a bad one can easily be 25% of the stock
     price, or more.
    <p>
     So, at Placer Dome, we give very full and regular disclosure, we are
     sensitive and responsive to the information needs of our market, and
     we think it is very, very, important.
     <p>
     And now, at the very bottom, we come to .....

     <p>
     <strong>YIELD</strong><br>
     Well, as everyone except a few individualists know, dividends are 
     irrelevant in the North American golds.  We pay 30&#162; per 
     share, more people pay 10&#162;, and others pay nothing.  And 
     Newmont pays a little more than we do.  But people are just not 
     there for dividends, in the main.  They are there for total 
     return, which, being translated, means stock appreciation.
    <p>
     By now you are bored, I can see the eyes glazed and the heads bowed,
     or nodding, so I will desist after a couple more points.

     <p>
     <strong>ONE IS THE ENVIRONMENT</strong><br>
     We feel we do a fairly good job, but Marcopper was a loud wake-up call
     for us.  Now we have a renewed commitment not only to be good, but to
     be a leader in the field, and be recognized as such.  It takes so long
     to build a reputation, and with one incident you can lose it all.

     <p>
     <strong>THE SECOND IS EMPOWERMENT</strong><br>
     Empowerment has little to do with focus on the gold industry, what I
     am here to talk about.  It is a newish word for making people's lives
     more interesting, more rewarding, more autonomous and more fulfilling.
      It is what we are trying very hard to bring about at Placer Dome.
    <p>
     First, we have a so-called decentralized structure, with Placer Dome
     Canada, Placer Dome U.S., Placer Dome Latin America and Placer
     Pacific.  Those are our regional companies that have their own CEO,
     CFO and other officers, as well as their own Boards.  Then we have
     P.D. Exploration, and the Project Development Division, each run by a
     Senior Vice-President.  In the middle of all this, becoming by design
     less and less visible, is Placer Dome Inc., the little mother, as I am
     sure it is often called!
    <p>
     To fit all of this, we have finally almost completed the installation
     of a fully modern Human Resources department which spreads its web
     throughout the world of Placer Dome, concentrating on career
     development, succession planning, nurturing the culture, ensuring fair
     and equitable competitive compensation, among many other critical
     activities.  While it is a central service organization, the regions
     and other groups have their own Human Resources organizations which
     reflect the nature and location of the activities undertaken.
    <p>
     Training is a large part of empowerment.  Most people want to run
     their own jobs just as they want to run their own lives.  To run their
     own jobs they need to be trained to do them.  Therefore, training is a
     key component of empowerment and we are working hard at it.  We are
     even training miners in finance, and financiers in mining.   Not easy!
    <p>
     Finally, to help with the motivation that should come with
     empowerment, we have programmes to encourage employee ownership of
     stock, both through option awards, and the award of options for
     holding PDG stock.
    <p>
     How did I get so far off track?  After all this was to be about our
     strategy, particularly for finding and developing gold resources.
    <p>
     We would obviously submit that a set of strategies and tactics may be
     very wisely and cleverly conceived, but without the depth of
     experience, knowledge and commitment of the people who make the
     company work, the company will never succeed.  At Placer, we will.


	<br><br><br>

