	<tr>
	<td>
	<a href="09d.html">Back to "Speeches and Presentations"</a>
	
	<p>
	

	<h2>
	 Corporate codes of conduct: Are there limitations?</a><br>
	</h2>
    
    <font size=-1>
    <strong>Human Rights & Trade Forum</strong><br> 
    Amnesty International<br>
    Toronto Organization<br>
	November 26, 1996<br>
  
    <p>
	<strong>Presentation by: James P. Cooney, Director, International and Public 
	Affairs, Placer Dome Inc.</strong>
	</font>
    <p>

	Today multinational corporations, such as Placer Dome, are going to 
	places where a few years ago we would not have dreamed of going.  
	Economic pressures combined with ideological evolution has forced - and 
	is forcing - countries which were communist, or nationalistic, or 
	protectionistic, or simply heavily indebted to turn to multinational 
	corporations for investment capital and economic growth.  
	International agreements such as NAFTA and the WTO are instituting 
	legal structures that encourage trade and investment by multinational 
	corporations. Multinational corporations are being actively courted 
	by many governments that once spurned us, and we are responding.  
	Rightly can we describe the 1990s as the decade of globalization.
    <p>	
	What do we find when we cross those once forbidding frontiers, in 
	Eastern Europe or the Former Soviet Union, in much of Latin America, 
	or Africa, or Southeast Asia, or China?  We encounter rampant 
	corruption in many governments and court systems.  We face in most 
	cases, if not the absence of environmental legislation, then a 
	complete lack of government capacity to monitor and regulate the 
	environmental impact of industrial activity. In some places, our 
	presence in the midst of sensitive ecosystems triggers issues related 
	to rainforest preservation, biodiversity protection, or 
	desertification prevention.  We are coming into contact with 
	indigenous populations, whose rights of land ownership and usage 
	generally remain undefined in their countries' laws and who are often 
	ignored or oppressed by their national governments.  Our projects are 
	sometimes surrounded by communities of impoverished people, 
	particularly in rural areas, such as landless peasants, or migratory 
	workers, or small scale miners, communities which are often 
	dysfunctional and in desperate need of medical and educational 
	services.  We are confronting labour unions which may be totally 
	controlled by their governments, or totally corrupt, or totally 
	politicized.  We are entering into contracts with governments, whose 
	willingness or capacity to abide by the terms of a legal agreement is 
	often sorely deficient.  Finally, we are dealing with governments who 
	may have opened their economies to multinational enterprises, but 
	politically remain dictatorial, denying their citizens their civil 
	rights and liberties.  Most fundamentally, and underlying the 
	foregoing specific conditions, we are relating across cultures to 
	value systems and customary practices which at various points conflict 
	with our own basic beliefs and principles as to what is right, 
	acceptable and conducive to everyone's best interest.
	<p>
	If this is globalization, why are multinational companies so keen on 
	it? Why are we rushing into places that pose such enormous challenges?  
	The main answer, of course, is that there are enormous opportunities 
	in these challenging places for doing business as it has not been done 
	before: opportunities for markets, for investments, for profits.  In 
	many of the more difficult jurisdictions competition may be weaker, 
	total costs less burdensome, regulations less constraining and 
	resources more available and less exploited than in the more developed 
	and attractive regions of the world.  To some extent, a foreign 
	company may be able to ignore or circumvent or insulate itself against 
	the social and environmental deficiencies it encounters, but should 
	it?  What responsibility should a company assume in remedying those 
	deficiencies, in becoming constructively engaged in bringing about 
	social and environmental improvements in the society where it is doing 
	business? To define the responsibility of multinational corporations 
	we must first acknowledge the essential nature of business.  From one 
	point of view the paramount, if not sole, objective of business is to 
	create wealth, to maximize the return on capital.  Part of that new 
	wealth is captured by the country where it is generated through taxes 
	and business expenditures.  As countries become richer they become 
	more able to attach priority to and deal with social and environmental 
	issues.  The encounter with foreign businesses may itself help 
	stimulate new thinking in a citizenry as to what is possible and 
	desirable.  Solving a country's problems can be viewed as the 
	responsibility not of the foreign company, but of the people in the 
	country itself.  Foreign capital, foreign technology and foreign 
	business practices merely provide a stimulus and perhaps an 
	opportunity to change.
	<p>
	From another point of view, it is the very nature of business to act 
	as a change agent in society: first in the marketplace, then with 
	respect to technology, production processes, management practices, and 
	so forth, and then on the periphery through interaction with local 
	communities, with the natural environment and with national 
	governments.  Companies cannot function in society without causing 
	change.  Progressive companies endeavour to solidify public and 
	political support by providing to local communities social and 
	physical infrastructure (schools, clinics, sports facilities, roads 
	and bridges, etc.), by showing respect for the natural environment 
	which may be affected by their operations, and by persuading 
	governments to adopt policies supportive of good business practices 
	and a stable operating environment.  The driving objective of 
	increasing shareholder value can itself be understood as the 
	consummate change, the end result of many specific internal and 
	external changes.  Companies which perceive themselves essentially as 
	change agents respond to the expectations not only of shareholders but 
	of numerous stakeholders: employees, communities, governments, 
	environmentalists, human rights advocates and others.  The differences 
	among companies is whether they consider themselves passive change 
	agents, focussed exclusively on shareholder interests, or active 
	change agents, fully engaged in developing constructive responses to 
	the social challenges around them.
	<p>
	This distinction between passive and active change-agents raises a 
	critical question.  Is it appropriate for a code of conduct to respect 
	the limits of corporate social responsibility implied in the role 
	definition of passive change-agent?  The inclination of those who wish 
	to accelerate positive change in societies around the world is to 
	press all corporations in the direction of becoming active change-agents.  
	Must a code of conduct go beyond restraining corporations 
	from doing evil?  Should codes of conduct actually direct 
	multinational corporations towards doing good, towards taking 
	positive actions to bring about social, political and economic 
	improvements in the societies where they are operating?  What are the 
	appropriate limits to a multinational corporation's active efforts to 
	bring about constructive change in the countries where it operates?
	<p>
	There are many voices proclaiming that globalization, and the growing 
	influence of multi-national corporations, presents a threat to, rather 
	than an opportunity for, positive social change.  The anti-globalizers 
	seek to reassert the national sovereignty, economic protectionism, and 
	barriers to the entry of multinational corporations, which have been 
	diminished through globalization.  They see the evils of globalization 
	as: a threat to the powers of local and indigenous communities and 
	even nations to control their futures as power is transferred to 
	multinational corporations; an acceleration of modes of economic 
	development that give scant attention to issues of equity or 
	environment; a widening of the gap between rich and poor, particularly 
	in developing countries; an invasion of the earth's remaining 
	wilderness places with a loss of biodiversity, natural resources, and 
	the planet's life support systems; and a worldwide homogenization of 
	diverse, local and indigenous cultures, social and economic 
	structures, as well as values and living patterns to reflect the 
	efficiency needs of the new global monoculture (IFG Position 
	Statement, January 1995). For the anti-globalizers multinational 
	corporations cannot be agents for positive change, no matter what 
	their codes of conduct may say.
	<p>
	Is a multinational corporation's code of conduct only a public 
	relations ploy, targeted at governments, communities, social activists 
	and concerned shareholders?  Certainly, such codes are useful in 
	deflecting the attacks of the anti-globalizers.  They help the 
	corporation put the best image on its intentions, irrespective of 
	whether it defines its social responsibilities narrowly or broadly.  
	Codes of conduct may in fact serve to strengthen a corporation's 
	competitive advantage.  When governments or potential partners have to 
	choose among bidders for a particular project, they may be inclined to 
	select that company which has the best reputation with respect to 
	environmental performance or community relations or even human rights 
	practices.  A code of conduct expresses and promotes those corporate 
	attributes.  Companies that have a code of conduct can present 
	themselves as more predictable and desirable partners, investors, or 
	operators.
	<p>
	Of course, by adopting a comprehensive code of conduct, a 
	multinational corporation invites increased public scrutiny of its 
	actions against its own self-imposed standards.  The risk of 
	attracting attention and generating criticism may limit the interest 
	of corporations in developing a comprehensive code of conduct.
	<p>
	Is it sufficient then for a multinational corporation simply to adopt 
	or reference statements of principles that have been developed by 
	multilateral institutions, such as UN declarations, ILO conventions, 
	World Bank guidelines, or the benchmarks of the Canadian, U.S. and 
	U.K. Task Forces on Corporate Responsibility?  Despite the excellence 
	of these documents and the effort that has gone into them, they remain 
	external admonitions. Often such principles are difficult for 
	corporations to internalize, as they seem not to reflect real-life 
	experience with the hard choices companies are often confronted with 
	in the field.
	<p>
	The usefulness of a code of conduct to a corporation is probably 
	proportionate to the effort it has expended in developing the code.  
	When a corporation without an explicit code of conduct is confronted 
	by complex social issues, it relies on its best judgment as 
	represented by personnel on the scene and by senior management.  The 
	corporation's best judgment generally represents enlightened corporate 
	self-interest.  The principles or rules underlying its choice of 
	actions are either expressed ad hoc or remain unstated.  Articulating 
	those underlying principles may help a corporation structure its 
	judgments in a more consistent and effective manner, and facilitate 
	the transfer of lessons from one experience to other situations.  
	Developing a code should be a corporate learning experience. However, 
	the task of producing a comprehensive set of principles or rules which 
	apply globally and respect the interest of all stakeholders may exceed 
	the capability of all but the most determined corporations.
	<p>
	Let me offer a few examples of the difficulty of formulating 
	comprehensive, globally applicable principles.  Many multinational 
	corporations have codes that deal with corruption, these prohibit 
	employees from paying gratuities, commissions, inducements or other 
	compensation to government officials for services rendered or 
	expected.  Generally, however, allowance is made for "facilitating 
	payments" to induce government officials to perform routine tasks for 
	which they are normally responsible in order to accommodate the 
	reality of conditions in much of the developing world. Even the U.S. 
	Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, the one piece of U.S. extra-territorial 
	legislation which one cannot fault, allows for the payment of 
	facilitating payments.  Corporations which are used to honest 
	government officials who discharge their duties without facilitating 
	payments, in countries such as Canada, rightly find this pervasive 
	form of corruption in the developing world to be repugnant.  Yet it 
	may be virtually  impossible to operate without making such payments 
	in countries where the government underpays officials in the 
	expectation that they will supplement their incomes with money 
	received from users of their services. As long as corporations are not 
	paying government officials bribes to exercise discretionary authority 
	in major decisions in their favor, corporations may consider 
	themselves to be abiding by the general rules against corruption.  In 
	countries like Canada those rules are black and white, but in many 
	developing countries the rules are varying shades of gray, which 
	challenges corporations to determine the limit between facilitating 
	payments and major corruption.
	<p>
	Are there not cases, however, where even the principle against large 
	scale corruption might justifiably be broken?  Would it be allowable, 
	for example, for a corporation to pay an inducement to a government to 
	make a human rights concession, such as the release of a political 
	prisoner?  It is debatable.  Who, after all, should decide that such 
	an infraction of an important principle is permissible?
	<p>
	Some corporations in Canada, the U.S. and Australia have developed 
	codes of conduct dealing with their relations with indigenous people.  
	Can the principles intended to guide Canadian corporations in relating 
	to our First Nations be applied to indigenous people throughout the 
	Americas and the rest of the world?  Up to a point, possibly; but 
	there may be limits.  At least one multi-national corporation received 
	a sharp surprise when the government of an African country challenged 
	its statement of principles on aboriginal relations as threatening to 
	promote tribalism.  That African country had during the past 30 years 
	made great progress in transcending tribalism, to the point that its 
	citizens truly identify themselves with their nation rather than with 
	their tribe.  There may also be a problem in defining who is 
	indigenous.  In Canada the law provides a clear definition; in many 
	other countries, it is far less clear.  These difficulties might deter 
	corporations but they have not deterred  multilateral institutions 
	from attempting to develop globally applicable principles regarding 
	indigenous peoples, notably the I.L.O. Convention, the U.N. Draft 
	Declaration, and the World Bank's guidelines.
	<p>
	Frequently it is recommended that principles regarding the rights of 
	employees and organized labour should be included in multinational 
	corporate codes of conduct.   The union-promoting codes of the I.L.O. 
	are held up as a model.  In some countries, however, large national 
	unions have extensive control over who is hired for industrial 
	operations anywhere in the country, and jobs tend to be awarded on the 
	basis of favouritism and corruption.  In such circumstances a 
	corporation's intention to maximize the hiring of people from the 
	local community risks being thwarted by the national union.  The 
	question then rises as to whether the company should seek to impede 
	the national union's effort to control the worksite so as to enhance 
	employment opportunities for the local community, or abdicate 
	community responsibility to remain consistent with principles 
	respecting the rights of unions.
	<p>
	These examples are meant only to illustrate the potential limitations 
	of globally applicable principles, whether on corruption, aboriginal 
	relations, labour rights, or environment, social development, or even 
	human rights.  The difficulty of developing principles which are truly 
	applicable without reservation in all situations which a company may 
	find itself in around the world is perhaps the principal reason (in 
	addition to the reluctance to invite greater scrutiny and possible 
	criticism)  why corporations may be hesitant to develop comprehensive 
	global codes of conduct.
	<p>
	It may be that the concern of many who advocate multinational 
	corporate codes of conduct is wrongly focused.  They are mostly 
	concerned about individual corporations doing evil or contributing to 
	persistent evils in countries where they operate.  Perhaps, a more 
	productive focus would be not on individual corporations but on 
	processes that bring about positive change.
	<p>
	In my view, to promote positive change and prevent harmful actions by 
	multinational corporations, codes of conduct need ultimately to take 
	the form of specific guidelines for individual countries.  Moreover, 
	the potential for positive change will be greatly enhanced if there is 
	consistent action by a group of like-minded corporations, and possibly 
	allied non-governmental organizations.  Multinational corporations 
	may benefit from the self-educating process of attempting to develop 
	their own comprehensive set of globally applicable principles, but 
	they may benefit more from educating each other by developing specific 
	codes of conduct for those countries in which they collectively face 
	challenging social conditions.  Such country specific codes will 
	clarify the ambiguities inherent in global principles, and provide 
	real guidance on difficult issues for all the corporations and 
	organizations that adopt the code.
	<p>
	The human rights agenda, to which Amnesty International is dedicated, 
	may be the most difficult for multinational corporations to address 
	in a code of conduct.  Individual corporations should certainly abide 
	by human rights principles in situations where they have some control, 
	such as their own operations.  However, it is nearly impossible and 
	possibly inappropriate for individual corporations to directly 
	influence governments in the broader areas of human rights, such as 
	freedom of expression, of assembly, from oppression, from torture, and 
	so forth.  There is a serious question as to how far a foreign 
	corporation, essentially a guest in the country where it is operating, 
	should go in influencing government policy in areas outside its own 
	business interests.  Public statements of disapproval may represent 
	the appropriate limit of intervention by a multinational corporation 
	in the domestic politics of its host country.  Even then, I would 
	suggest such statements should be logically linked to identifiable 
	corporate self-interest.
	<p>
	Collective action, even if only in the form of remonstrations, may if 
	it is broad-based and strong-willed enough, be far more effective in 
	bringing about improvements in human rights practices.  Collective 
	action by a number of multinational corporations and allied 
	organizations may go beyond words and include specific initiatives 
	which might advance the human rights agenda more than would be 
	possible for an individual corporation. Did not the collective 
	action of the well-intentioned corporations that subscribed to the 
	Sullivan principles help bring about eventual change in South Africa?  
	I would suggest that Amnesty International should promote that 
	multinational corporations active in a country where there are 
	significant human rights abuses, jointly develop (with groups such as 
	Amnesty) a code of conduct specific to that country, which concerned 
	corporations adopt and implement, with a view to acting collectively 
	to bring about positive change.
	<p>
	There is a model for such an approach.  The movement known as 
	Transparency International (of which a Canadian chapter has just been 
	established) is a coalition of business and other organizations formed 
	to deal with the matter of corruption.  Transparency International 
	members undertake to work collaboratively with each other, with other 
	like-minded organizations and (where possible) with the government to 
	bring about progressive elimination of corruption in countries where 
	they are operating.  The principle guiding Transparency International 
	is that "the approach has to be evolutionary, as one cannot change the 
	way the world is operating at a stroke of the pen". The same 
	collective approach could be productive in other areas of 
	multinational corporate activity, including community development, 
	aboriginal issues, labour relations and human rights.
	<p>
	Let me sum up.  Codes of conduct can be useful for multinational 
	corporations, and beneficial to the countries where they operate, but 
	they have their limits.  Global principles are subject to varying 
	interpretations and applications in different countries and under 
	different circumstances.  Therefore, globally applicable comprehensive 
	codes of conduct are difficult, if not impossible, to develop; but the 
	effort may be very enlightening to corporations which try.  Individual 
	corporations, however compelling their code of conduct, however 
	well-intentioned and powerful they may seem, have limited ability to 
	change overall social conditions in their countries of operation.  
	Collective action by corporations and other institutions in accordance 
	with country-specific codes of conduct which they jointly develop 
	offer the best hope of bringing
	about positive social change.



