	<td>
	<a href="09d.html">Back to "Speeches and Presentations"</a>
	
	<p>
	

	<h2>
	Managing an environmental crisis</a><br>
	</h2>
    
    <font size=-1>
    <strong>Vancouver Mining Investment Conference</strong><br> 
    November 15, 1996<br>
    Westin Bayshore Hotel<br>
	Vancouver, British Columbia<br>
  
    <p>
	<strong>Address to the Randol by Hugh Leggatt, Manager, Corporate 
	Communications, Placer Dome Inc.</strong>
	</font>
	

	<p>
	
	I want you to know at the outset that Placer Dome's reputation is as 
	solid as the gold we mine.  This year for the first time we tarnished 
	our record. But we're making every effort to reclaim it.
	<p>
	In March, after many years of good performance, we suffered a major 
	environmental mishap.  We have done our best to face up to the 
	situation, act responsibly, make restitution and ultimately acquit 
	ourselves with honour.
	<p>
	Still, in some quarters we were pilloried as environmental bandits.  
	This came as a shock to the system, because we are a strongly 
	principled company.  We have thought through our values, and we are 
	committed to doing the right thing.  So our regret was absolute.
	<p>
	Today I'd like to tell you what happened, what we have done about it 
	and what we have learned from it.
	<p>
	The spill took place in the Philippines, at the Marcopper Mine, of 
	which we own 40%.  In accord with the environmental compliance 
	certificate issued by the Government, this decommissioned open pit was 
	being used to store tailing, the ground-up rock and water left after 
	the copper is extracted.
	<p>
	Back in the 1970s, to prevent storm water from accumulating in the pit 
	when it was being mined, a two-kilometre-long tunnel was drilled from 
	the pit bottom through a mountain to the headwaters of the Boac River.
	<p>
	To ready the pit for tailing storage, in 1991 the upstream end of the 
	tunnel was collapsed, and the downstream opening was sealed with an 
	eight-metre-long concrete plug, secured to the rock by steel rods.
	
	In 1992, four years ago, the pit began to fill with tailing from the 
	new San Antonio mine.  In 1995, in the course of studies into future 
	tailing disposal, seepage was detected from the mountainside near 
	where the tunnel was plugged.
	<p>
	As a precautionary measure, on the advice of a consultant, it was 
	decided to drill into the tunnel and plug it further by pumping in 
	more concrete. The first borehole had been drilled, when on March 24 
	this year the tunnel gave way and tailing began pouring out into the 
	environment.
	<p>
	All told, three to four million tonnes of material escaped through the 
	tunnel into the Boac River system.  It was a very serious and 
	regrettable situation. It could have been worse, however.  Fortunately 
	the tailing was not toxic to humans.  No lives were lost, and a United 
	Nations investigation has independently confirmed that no one was made 
	sick.  We believe the damage to the river is reversible.
	<p>
	Still, the river is heavily silted, resulting in a significant impact 
	on aquatic life.  The lives of more than 20,000 people were disrupted.  
	Crops, commerce and community life were affected.
	<p>
	Our response was swift.  We tended to the immediate needs of the 
	nearby communities and were absolutely frank about what had happened.  
	We adopted a policy of full disclosure of all information to anyone 
	who might conceivably be interested, including admitting friend and 
	foe to the site to take a look.
	<p>
	We also sought to make amends.  Although only a 40% shareholder, we 
	assumed 100% responsibility.  We took a US$40 million charge 
	against earnings to cover financial obligations for Marcopper, 
	including US$15 million for repairs and environmental 
	mitigation.  As a result, Placer Dome posted a loss for the first six 
	months and first nine months of 1996.
	<p>
	We are now doing our best to clean up and to make restitution.  We 
	have installed a plug in the tunnel using a mixture of heated bitumen 
	and concrete.  The mixture was pumped down a fence of 20 boreholes 
	into the voids of the tunnel and surrounding rock.
	<p>
	This water running clear from the tunnel in May has stopped.  The 
	bitumen and concrete is holding while we drive another tunnel parallel 
	to the first to gain physical access to put in a permanent plug.
	<p>
	We have dredged a kilometre-long channel across the river at its 
	mouth. This will trap the coarse tailing moving along the river bottom 
	and prevent it from silting up the delta.  The finer material floating 
	down the river will disperse naturally in the ocean and the river 
	should over time return to normal.  Underwater disposal renders the 
	material inert and is regarded as the safest long-term solution.
	<p>
	We are compensating fisherfolk for the temporary effects on fisheries.  
	We are compensating others for loss of income, damage to property and 
	inconvenience.  We are moving people in danger of flooding to new 
	houses on higher ground.
	<p>
	 We are establishing a sustainable development programme projected for 
	 at least 10 years into the future.  This is to improve the condition 
	 of affected communities through upgraded infrastructure, better 
	 education and health facilities and technically more advanced 
	 fisheries and farms.
	<p>
	Local wells are being scientifically monitored, the health of 
	inhabitants is being scrutinized, and politicians are taking an 
	interest in the area.
	<p>
	As awful as it was, the tailing spill has triggered significant 
	benefits for the people of Marinduque Island. For our part, we 
	have given up our operational role.  The Mine Manager and the 
	President, who are Placer Dome employees, have resigned from 
	Marcopper. And we are divesting ourselves of our interest in the 
	company.  But we will complete the remedial work.
	<p>
	We faced up to this with our best effort - full disclosure and 
	everything possible in the way of mitigation and compensation.
	<p>
	<strong>What have we learned?</strong><br>
	From the international perspective, the incident created 
	communications challenges, especially regarding news reporting in 
	different cultures.
	<p>
	The Filipino media have only recently emerged from a long era of 
	government control.  As a consequence, some reporters and editors 
	don't follow courtesies like balancing allegations of wrongdoing with 
	replies from those who stand accused.
	<p>
	Although the spill was not toxic to humans and no one became sick, the 
	Manila media was full of reports of sick and injured people, dead 
	animals and general devastation.  They always described the tailing as 
	toxic. While we fully acknowledged that the silt in the river channel 
	was bad enough, it was made to seem much worse than it was.
	<p>
	The problems arose for us here in Vancouver when international news 
	agencies picked up exaggerated or incorrect reports in Manila and ran 
	them as straight wire stories in North America.  We found ourselves 
	continually on the defensive in responding to errors of magnitude 
	throughout the coverage.
	<p>
	The only useful response was full disclosure.  Every time the word 
	"toxic" came up, we had to call up and clarify.
	<p>
	In telling a mining story to the public you clearly start at a 
	disadvantage.  The nature of mining makes us easy targets.  We move 
	dirt and rock to make pits.  We use chemicals.  We create hazardous 
	waste.  We make rather large holes in the ground.
	<p>
	This makes for images that are graphic and disturbing to most people.  
	We live in a popular-movie-and-TV culture that prizes image and 
	presentation over reasoned analysis.  In this, ugly equals bad.
	<p>
	An additional factor is that the battle is fought by the power of 
	communications on the Internet, so that for example an accident in the 
	Philippines immediately becomes ammunition to oppose new mine 
	developments in far-off places like South America.
	<p>
	We also live at a time when industry is not trusted, but 
	environmentalists are considered credible.  The reason is 
	understandable: in spite of all the benefits conferred on humanity 
	since the Industrial Revolution, goods-producing industries like ours 
	went through a long phase in which no one cared about the environment.
	<p>
	The fact that industry has learned its lesson and has changed over the 
	past generation is not generally accepted.  Today we build mines to 
	much higher standards of environmental protection than when Marcopper 
	was built in the late 1960s.  Our mine in Venezuela will have 
	tremendous tailing dam safety factors and a process to recycle the 
	cyanide.
	<p>
	The only way to counter opposition is to operate mines that do not 
	pollute, and to operate them that way for a long, long time.
	<p>
	In the meantime, every medium of communication -- including the 
	Internet -- should be used to counter misinformation with verifiable 
	facts. Ultimately, good information should drive out bad.
	<p>
	At Placer Dome, we welcome public scrutiny of our activities and are 
	prepared to respond constructively to criticism.  Our future success 
	as an international mining company depends on maintaining our 
	credibility as being environmentally responsible.
	<p>
	The countries and communities that host our mines need to know that we 
	at Placer Dome will protect and preserve their interests.  The 
	authorities who have decision-making power over our projects have 
	every right, indeed a duty, to question whether we will be good 
	corporate citizens.
	<p>
	The millions of dollars we are spending in the Philippines, and the 
	effort we have made to tell the  truth about what happened, are in 
	keeping with our ethical standards and an investment in our future 
	ability to develop mines worldwide.
	<p>
	Another investment we want to make is to improve relationships with 
	special interest groups, especially those with environmental agendas.
	<p>
	We genuinely care about their concerns.  We are prepared to address 
	their worries about our projects and mines in a spirit of open 
	communication.  We want to find what is the right thing to do; what is 
	acceptable to a broad range of special interests.  We want to go 
	forward with more supporters and fewer enemies.
	<p>
	Mining companies and environmentalists really have much in common.  
	Most people today, including those of us employed by mining companies, 
	possess strong environmental values as individuals.  Environmental 
	sensitivity is part of today's culture.
	<p>
	A large part of our intended growth will depend on how well we manage 
	the environmental and social dimensions of international mining.
	<p>
	Good neighbouring with good mining is the way to go.  The accident at
	Marcopper has only strengthened our resolve to be the best.


	<br><br><br>

