	<td>
	<a href="09d.html">Back to "Speeches and Presentations"</a>
	
	<p>
	

	<h2>
	Mining and sustainable social development</a><br>
	</h2>
    
    <font size=-1>
    <strong>Social Investment Organization</strong><br>
    Sixth Annual Conference on Corporate Responsibility in a Global 
    Economy: Owning Up & Taking Stock<br>
    Panel on Canadian Corporations 
    in the Americas<br>
    November 15, 1996<br>
    Park Plaza Hotel<br>
	Toronto, Ontario<br>
  
    <p>
	<strong>Presentation by: James P. Cooney, Director, International 
	and Public Affairs, Placer Dome Inc.</strong>
	</font>
	
	<P>
	The new opening in Latin America to foreign investment in mining that 
	has occurred during the past five years is driven by a powerful 
	combination of economic necessity and ideological evolution in many 
	countries of the region.  One by one, beginning with Chile in the late 
	1980s, countries in Latin America have revised their mining codes, 
	taxation regimes and foreign investment laws so as to become more 
	attractive to multinational mining companies.  The result has been a 
	veritable rush of mining companies from the industrialized world into 
	Latin America in pursuit of mineral exploration and mine development 
	opportunities.
	<P>
	As we enter these countries, which have for many years been 
	effectively closed off to us, we are encountering unfamiliar and 
	difficult challenges. The quest for minerals often takes us to the 
	frontier zones of countries. There we find migratory populations of 
	small scale miners (garimp&#233;iros), working the surface of the same 
	lands for which the large scale developmental rights are being granted 
	by governments to the newly-invited-in foreign mining companies.  In 
	many countries of Latin America, we are coming into contact with 
	indigenous populations, whose rights of land ownership and usage 
	generally remain poorly defined in their countries' laws.  Frequently, 
	we face environmental issues, related to the impact of our activities 
	on sensitive ecosystems newly exposed to our presence, such as 
	tropical rain forests.  Generally, we find ourselves relating to 
	governmental regulatory agencies whose mandates and responsibilities 
	often greatly exceed their managerial and technical capacity.  More 
	fundamentally, we are communicating across cultures, confronting 
	values and habits which may at various points conflict with our own 
	basic beliefs and principles as to what is right, acceptable and 
	conducive to everyone's best interests.  Finally, as extractors of a 
	depleting resource, we are inevitably prompting questions from various 
	quarters as to how mining can possibly contribute to long-term 
	sustainable development.
	<P>
	Responding to these challenges is imposing extensive demands on our 
	resources of time, talent and effort, as well as on our capacity for 
	flexibility, ingenuity and strategic thinking.  Each situation and set 
	of circumstances requires its own, often unique, response.  However, 
	at least three generalizations appear appropriate.
	<p>
	First, multinational mining companies need the support of other 
	organizations which can bring talent and expertise to addressing the 
	social challenges around mine development.  For example, national or 
	multilateral aid agencies may have a role to play in optimizing the 
	developmental potential of a mine in the surrounding area.  
	Non-governmental organizations (NGOs), focused for example on 
	environment (assuming they are scientifically oriented and not purely 
	political), or on social and economic development, or on particular 
	interests, such as indigenous people, may also complement and add 
	credibility to a company's efforts to deal with issues relating to the 
	development of a mine.  Most importantly, foreign mining companies 
	need to be clearly allied to the interests of surrounding communities 
	in a strong spirit of cooperation with their local institutions.  Not 
	uncommonly in frontier zones, foreign companies run the risk of 
	becoming surrogate governments, directly providing goods and services 
	to neighbouring communities, which the government may have the 
	responsibility but not the capacity to deliver.  Our role as foreign 
	mining companies should be not to replace community or national 
	governments but rather to strengthen, and sometimes help create, local 
	institutions that are able to foster community growth and improvement.
	<p>
	Secondly, multinational mining companies need to clearly recognize and 
	respect the ethical principles that relate to our activities.  
	Corruption, human rights and social issues in many developing 
	countries raise ethical challenges.  These have the potential to 
	become as demanding of the industry's attention and its ability to 
	respond as have been environmental challenges during the past couple 
	of decades.  We need to think through our role with respect to 
	combatting official corruption, to promoting political change in 
	support of human rights, and towards acting as a catalyst for local 
	and national economic and social progress.  Ultimately, I think we 
	will need to articulate our global ethical principles and hold 
	ourselves accountable to acting in conformity with those principles.
	<p>
	Thirdly, multinational mining companies need to define our activities 
	in the framework of "sustainable development".  This policy 
	orientation, following the Rio Convention of 1992 (referred to as 
	Agenda 21), has been embraced by many governments in Latin America.  
	The concept of sustainable development, however, is open to various 
	definitions; but key elements for the mining industry include 
	effective public consultation with populations affected by mine 
	development, equitable distribution of wealth generated by mining to 
	local communities, and effective management of the environmental and 
	socio-economic impacts of mining both during operations and after mine 
	closure.
	<p>
	Let me offer you a specific example of Placer Dome's social 
	investment at one of our projects in Latin America, namely the Las 
	Cristinas mine in Venezuela.  Las Cristinas is located in a 
	frontier zone in Southeastern Bolivar state, near the border with 
	Guyana.  At Las Cristinas Placer Dome has entered into a 70/30 
	joint venture agreement with the CorporationVenezolano de Guayana 
	(CVG) to explore and eventually mine the surface and bedrock gold 
	deposits of the contract area.  Until now gold production in 
	Bolivar State has been derived mainly from small-scale operations 
	by local artisanal miners (garimp&#233;iros), whose activities 
	have been practised in an environmentally disruptive way.  The Las 
	Cristinas project once developed would be the first large scale 
	gold mine in Venezuela, and could serve as a model of 
	environmentally and socially responsible private sector mining. 
	The Las Cristinas mine will be developed at a capital cost of 
	US$576 million, with a projected production rate in excess of 400,000 
	ounces per year, and a mine life of at least 13 years.  During its 
	operating life, the mine is expected to employ 850 people, most of 
	whom will be hired within Venezuela. Placer Dome's  long-term 
	objectives go beyond the construction and operation of a 
	successful mine, and include the creation of new business 
	opportunities in the region and the sharing of the benefits of 
	success with both the government (national and state) and local 
	communities representing 4000 people.
	<p>
	Las Cristinas is a prime example of a mine on the frontier of a 
	developing country.  There is an indigenous population of over 20 
	villages located within a 50 kilometre radius of the project, with the 
	two closest villages (10 and 25 km away) having together a population 
	of approximately 500.  In general, the recent influx of international 
	mining companies into the area has been a cause of concern, 
	particularly for those indigenous communities which are sandwiched 
	between contract areas.  While the Las Cristinas contract area does 
	not abut or encroach on native claimed lands, other companies' areas 
	do.  This has lent increased momentum to indigenous efforts to clarify 
	the legal status of their traditional use areas and secure legal 
	recognition from both the federal and state governments, efforts which 
	thus far have met with limited success.
	<p>
	Indigenous village economies are typically mixed, based on both 
	traditional activities (agriculture, hunting and fishing) and 
	commercial activities (forest products, carpentry, artisanal mining, 
	poultry farming, ecotourism and handicrafts).  For the past few years, 
	local village leadership has been actively promoting the expansion and 
	diversification of the non-traditional cash economy with the explicit 
	goal of increasing autonomy and providing resources for the 
	strengthening of traditional activities and social institutions.  As a 
	result of their longer history and more cohesive social and political 
	organisation, both their physical and social infrastructures are 
	better developed and of higher quality than those of the 
	non-indigenous communities.  This is especially so with regard to 
	housing stock, roads, water supply, sanitation, educational and 
	recreational facilities.
	<p>
	Of all the communities in the general area, the indigenous communities 
	are best positioned to take advantage of new economic opportunities 
	provided by the presence of foreign mining companies.  Two communities 
	have already secured carpentry and forest product supply contracts 
	from the Las Cristinas project. It should be noted, moreover, that 
	these indigenous communities are shielded from the direct impacts of 
	our proposed mine, due to their physical distance and social isolation 
	from the Las Cristinas site.
	<p>
	The non-indigenous communities in the Las Cristinas region present a 
	much more difficult challenge for Placer Dome.  The Las Cristinas 
	contract area was inhabited and mined by Venezuelan nationals and 
	foreign migrants (referred to collectively as "criollos") on a 
	quasi-legal basis from the 1950s until 1990/1991.  At this time, the 
	area was cleared of inhabitants by the CVG, with about 2800 people 
	being relocated to a site approximately 5 kilometres east of the 
	contract area.  Today the displaced communities are home to around 
	1700 people, living in two villages, Santo Domingo and Ciudad Dorada 
	(also known as Nuevas Claritas).  The majority of inhabitants continue 
	to derive their livelihood from small-scale mining activities. Since 
	no "legal" mining areas were assigned to the small miners by the 
	government at the time of relocation, this activity now occurs 
	illegally. Miners continue to work in areas where they have 
	historically operated, i.e. contract areas now assigned to the 
	international mining companies. Such "unauthorised" mining provides a 
	livelihood for 42% of the economically active population within the 
	general area, and for 65% and 45% of the Santo Domingo and Ciudad 
	Dorada workforces respectively. The "criollo" communities near to Las 
	Cristinas (in contrast to the indigenous communities) are politically 
	disorganised and lack social cohesion.  Almost all economic activity - 
	both formal and informal - derives from the "illegal" mining of gold, 
	an activity that has become increasingly difficult to practice both 
	locally and regionally within the past few years.  This is due both to 
	the lack of a supportive legal and institutional framework and to the 
	re-assignment of lands to international mining companies.
	<p>
	The situation of these "criollo" communities does not lend itself to 
	social stability.  Living conditions remain primitive for most 
	residents. Unfortunately, local and regional governance has 
	historically worked to benefit not the communities overall, but rather 
	selected individuals.  As such, these communities have been left 
	largely to their own devices for the delivery of essential public 
	services.  Central government intervention in the area is limited to 
	basic law enforcement via the National Guard. Rudimentary health care 
	facilities and services (a walk-in medical clinic) are provided free 
	of charge by the State Government.  Recently the State Government 
	announced its intention to abandon fiscal support of the two public 
	elementary schools in the area due to budgetary constraints.
	<p>
	Social and economic baseline studies have identified a number of 
	critical feature of the criollo communities, including:
	<p>
	<li>low educational and skill levels among the local populations,
	<li>lack of alternate economic activities and work opportunities, 
	<li>lack of property rights and security of residential tenancy, 
	<li>deficient and insufficient housing stock, 
	<li>inadequate or absent basic public services (health, 
	sanitation, potable water supply, communications, electrification, 
	education, recreation, etc.),
	<li>lack of access to mineral resources for artisanal mining, 
	<li>endemic public health problems, including malaria, intestinal 
	parasites, and venereal diseases.
	<p>
	These existing conditions, along with the displacement experience, 
	underlie much of the mistrust and anxiety within the local "criollo" 
	communities. The establishment of large-scale mining operations in the 
	area by international mining companies will have the potential to 
	intensify certain of these negative conditions, while ameliorating 
	others.  In the first instance, the limitation of access to old mining 
	areas enforced by some of the mining companies has already adversely 
	affected livelihood and life in some of the communities, exacerbating 
	already high levels of tension and anxiety.  In late May-early June 
	1995, one local community blockaded the main road into the mining 
	areas.  This action was the community's response to intensified 
	harassment from the National Guard and to the hard-line attitude of 
	one of the Canada-based junior mining companies operating in the area.  
	The community confronted the National Guard at that company's mining 
	property and eventually overran the property.
	<p>
	In sharp contrast, we have decided to countenance small-scale 
	artisanal mining activity on parts of the Las Cristinas property, 
	while also initiating a social investment program during the final 
	stage of the exploration program.  For example, assistance was 
	provided to expand the local school, improve the local clinic and 
	install a new water storage tank.  During the recent roadblock, only 
	vehicles of the Las Cristinas project were allowed unhindered passage 
	by the townspeople.  As a result of this affirmative and conciliatory 
	approach to the communities, the Las Cristinas project and the company 
	are positively viewed and its early efforts at social investment 
	appear to be appreciated.
	<p>
	Building a positive relationship with the local "criollo" communities 
	through limited social investment during the exploration stage is, 
	however, only the first step towards effectively addressing the 
	challenges of mine development on the frontier.  Maintaining social 
	stability in the area around the mine through an on-going program of 
	community improvement throughout the life of the mine will be a key 
	success factor for the Las Cristinas project.  Sustaining those social 
	and economic improvements after the mine closes will be the ultimate 
	challenge.
	<p>
	We recognize that the impact of the Las Cristinas project on the local 
	communities will be mixed.  There will be positive impacts in the form 
	of jobs, business opportunities, and mine related improvements in the 
	local physical and social infrastructure.  However, there will also be 
	negative impacts, such as: inflationary pressures on local commerce; 
	an influx of outsiders through migration towards a "growth pole"; an 
	increase in social problems such as alcoholism, gambling and 
	prostitution; a loss of livelihood by many artisanal miners; an 
	increase in political opportunism and local corruption; pressures on 
	the cultural integrity of local indigenous communities; and the list 
	goes on.  These are the potential downsides of mine development in an 
	already rough-and-tumble frontier zone.
	<p>
	To optimize the potential benefits and counter the possible adverse 
	effects of the mine development, a long-term socio-economic 
	improvement program is beginning to be implemented by the Las 
	Cristinas project designed to strengthen community capabilities and 
	institutions.  Over the life of the mine, the programme aims:
	<p>
	<li>to improve the general level of income within the local communities 
	and its equitable distribution within communities,
	<li>to facilitate the creation of a sustainable, diversified 
	economy, 
	<li>to encourage local initiatives and the development of stable 
	communities, 
	<li>to increase the level of education and training within 
	communities,
	<li>to improve quality of life and access to essential public 
	goods and services.
	<li>to minimise environmental impacts of new and existing 
	activities,
	<li>to increase the participation of women in the development 
	effort.
	<p>
	To describe the details of this socio-economic program would take us 
	beyond the time available for this presentation; but one point must be 
	stressed. We are implementing this social investment strategy in line 
	with these principles I stated at the beginning by: (1) collaborating 
	with government agencies and non-governmental organizations focused on 
	economic and social development; (2) acting according to ethical 
	principles in addressing social challenges around our mine operations; 
	and (3) structuring our overall social investment in the context of 
	sustainable development.
	<p>
	Recently we have entered into an agreement with CIDA (September 20, 
	1996) under the Industrial Co-operation program, to complete the 
	viability study for a project referred to as "Local Economic 
	Diversification Initiatives (Social Economic Improvement Program)" 
	related to the Las Cristinas mining project.  The objective of the 
	viability study is to create a strategic and action oriented framework 
	for promoting the long-term social, economic and environmental 
	sustainability of the local community through the activities of 
	Venezuelan NGO's strengthened by Canadian NGOs, with support from 
	Placer Dome.  We already have an alliance with the local Catholic 
	church NGO, Fe y Alegria, and have entered discussions with other 
	Venezuelan NGOs. The viability study, which is scheduled to be 
	completed by May, 1997, will set out the terms of reference for a 
	program of implementation, which it is envisaged will also take the 
	form of a continuing Placer Dome-CIDA partnership.
	<p>
	The Placer Dome-CIDA "Local Economic Diversification Initiatives" 
	project is designed to augment and realize the potential of a number of 
	possible developmental projects, such as ecotourism expansion in the 
	area, aviculture facility upgrading, technical assistance for small 
	scale mining, sewing workshops for local communities, cement block 
	fabrication and many other possible projects.  The viability study 
	will focus on defining specific needs related to these proposed 
	projects, such as training and education, local organisational and 
	leadership capacity enhancement, micro-enterprise financing through 
	revolving funds, and so forth.  The viability study will help resolve 
	uncertainty within the local communities as to what types and forms of 
	assistance and partnerships with respect to new or alternative 
	business development they might reasonably expect during the 
	construction and operating life of the mine.
	<p>
	The partnership model of social investment (Placer Dome with CIDA and 
	with Venezuelan and Canadian NGOs) positions the company as one player 
	among many in the community development field.  Moreover, it holds out 
	the hope of creating an institutional structure in support of 
	continuing community improvement which can go on after the closure of 
	the mine.  Finally, this model also gives the company allies, which 
	may act as defense mechanisms against future political risk, as the 
	mine will not be an isolated foreign company presence in southeast 
	Bolivar state, which some future Venezuelan government may for 
	whatever political purpose target.
	<p>
	In conclusion, let me say that I know of no perfect solutions for any 
	of the many challenges posed to mine development in the frontier zones 
	of Latin America.  What matters most is the correct orientation.  What 
	we can achieve may be limited to incremental improvements in the right 
	direction. However, over the life of a mine, the accumulation of those 
	improvements can become truly significant.  A key factor in making 
	sustainable progress will be the involvement of international aid 
	agencies and non-governmental organizations, whose institutional 
	presence can help support and maintain the levels of development 
	achieved, even beyond the life of the mine.  Our intention is to bring 
	about social, environmental and economic improvements which make a 
	lasting contribution to the development of the country where we are 
	operating.  At the end of the day, we recognize that mining can only 
	be judged in the context of sustainable development by what remains 
	after the mine closes.


	<br><br><br>

