	<td>
	<a href="09d.html">Back to "Speeches and Presentations"</a>
	
	<p>
	

	<h2>
	Marcopper analysts conference call</a><br>
	</h2>
    
    <font size=-1>
    June 27, 1996<br>
	Vancouver, British Columbia<br>
  
    <p>
	<strong>Remarks by John M. Willson, President and Chief Executive Officer,
	Placer Dome Inc.</strong>
	</font>
    <p>

        Good Morning Ladies and Gentlemen, and thank you for joining 
        us. My name is John Willson and I am the President and Chief 
        Executive Officer of Placer Dome.  With me are Sandy Laird, 
        Senior Vice-President, Placer Dome Group, and Ian Austin, 
        Senior Vice-President and Chief Financial Officer.
    <p>
        By now you will have seen the press release we issued this 
        morning with regard to the Marcopper mine, announcing a 
        provision of US$40 million against second quarter earnings as 
        a result of the accidental escape of tailing.   We are here 
        today to give you some background and fill in some blanks.  
        There are a few things I believe it is important that you 
        understand.
    <p>
        All of us at Placer Dome highly value our environmental track 
        record and are saddened to have it tarnished by this accident. 
        Those of you who know us will appreciate how distressing this 
        has been -- especially when so many other things are going 
        right for the Company.
<p>
        The Pipeline and Musselwhite mine projects are off to 
        excellent starts and it appears the very least they will do is 
        come in on schedule and budget.  The puzzle at Las Cristinas 
        is getting quite complete and exploration drilling on the 
        Sofia and Mesones targets is progressing well and producing 
        encouraging results that we will be telling you about before 
        too long.
<p>
        We feel very strongly that Placer Dome should do everything it 
        can to correct the situation at Marcopper.  That is why we are 
        incurring what seems to be a very large amount given that we 
        only have a 40% interest.
<p>
        This is in keeping with a commitment I have made to the 
        President of the Philippines, that we will fix the situation 
        -- even though it has become apparent that Marcopper doesn't 
        have the financial ability to do this on its own.
<p>
        We have some of our best engineering talent assigned to the 
        task, and a swarm of consultants, and they have now devised 
        solutions to repair the tunnel.  We also have a remediation  
        plan awaiting government approval which is centred on dredging 
        of the mouth of the Boac river.
<p>
        Sandy Laird can answer any detailed questions you may have on 
        the technical area, but I will tell you that no tailing flow 
        has occurred since June 11.  Water which appears to be mostly 
        clear groundwater continues to seep at the rate of 120 litres 
        per second.  Work continues to completely stem this flow 
        including further use of bitumen as a sealing agent.
<p>
        Our approach to permanently plugging the tunnel is twofold.  
        We are mobilizing equipment to blind bore from surface to 
        provide access for installing a plug, however ground 
        conditions may prevent this strategy from being successful.  
        We are therefore also preparing to drive a second tunnel next 
        to and parallel with the original one.  If this plan proceeds, 
        we would then drive a drift from the second tunnel to the 
        first to provide access for installing the plug.
<p>
        With regard to river clean-up, we have applied to dredge a 
        deep channel which would intersect the Boac River at its 
        mouth.  Over time we would expect this channel to collect 
        about 30% to 40% of the tailing now deposited in the river, 
        with the remainder being dispersed in the ocean. There is 
        already evidence this has process has started to occur as 
        rainfall increases.
<p>
        We are of course very concerned for the local community, 
        particularly with the monsoon season approaching.  To protect 
        against flooding, we are building berms and dykes along the 
        river, and starting to relocate families whose homes are the 
        most at risk.  A small protective harbour facility is also 
        being built near the mouth of the river for the local 
        fishermen's boats.
<p>
        Jim Cooney, whom some of you know, has just returned from 
        Marinduque where he has been co-ordinating the involvement of 
        non-government organizations.  They are ensuring that the 
        needs of the community are being satisfied.
<p>
        It is important that I point out that Placer Dome does not 
        have control of Marcopper Mining Corporation, since we have 
        had only three Directors on an eight-member Board.
<p>
        The controlling shareholder, who acquired his position in 1994 
        from the Philippine Committee for Good Government, is becoming 
        more involved in the Company than the previous benign 
        shareholder -- to the extent that our representatives have now 
        stepped down from their respective positions as President and 
        General Manager.  The controlling shareholder is appointing 
        his own representatives to these positions from Marcopper 
        personnel.
<p>
        As a result, we will no longer be involved in any on-going 
        operations at Marcopper.  We remain concerned that the mine 
        re-open and will stay involved to see that environmental and 
        community issues be properly dealt with.  But the prospects 
        for re-opening are uncertain.
<p>
        The mine's Environmental Compliance Certificate has been 
        lifted, the copper price cycle appears to have turned and 
        Marcopper's financial situation has not fully recovered from 
        previous typhoons.  Together these factors have caused us to 
        finally conclude that Marcopper may not be able to service its 
        debt and a provision against earnings is required.
<p>
        Let me say how important it is for Placer Dome to see this 
        process at Marcopper through to an appropriate conclusion.  It 
        is critical to our strategic plan that we do so, since we have 
        been working so hard to successfully resolve environmental 
        issues at new projects in Venezuela and Costa Rica and will 
        need to do the same for all the other mines we plan to build 
        in future.
<p>
        In essence, we are trying to look at this expenditure at 
        Marcopper
        as an investment in our future ability to develop mines worldwide.

	<br><br><br>

