<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Latest - Speeches and Presentations</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff" link="52001f" vlink="858585">

	<a href=#00>
	<img src="../gfx/pdlogosm.gif" alt="Placer Dome banner gif" border=0></a>
	
	<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
	<tr>
	<td valign=top>
	<a href="../gfx/00butbar.map">
	<img src="../gfx/06butbar.gif" alt="Button links <li> image mapped gif" border=0 align=left ismap></a>
	</td>
	
	<td valign=top>
	<table border=0>
	<tr>        
	<td valign=top colspan=2>
	<img src="../gfx/09head.gif" alt="The Latest header gif">
	</td>
	
	
	<tr>
	<td>
	<a href="09d.html">Back to "Speeches and Presentations"</a>
	
	<p>
	

	<h2>
	Placer Dome's Las Cristinas project in Venezuela</a><br>
	</h2>
    
    <font size=-1>
    <strong>United Nations Division for Environmental Management and Social Development</strong><br>
    Symposium on Corporations, Communities and Sustainable Social Development
    in the Minerals Sector<br>
    Panel on Canadian Corporations 
    in the Americas<br>
    May 10, 1996<br>
	New York City, New York<br>
  
    <p>
	<strong>Presentation by: James P. Cooney, Director, International 
	and Public Affairs, Placer Dome Inc.</strong>
    </font>

    <p>
	 As a result of the current global opening to foreign investment in 
	 mining, companies such as Placer Dome are moving into unfamiliar and 
	 difficult environments, areas formerly off-limits to us, frontier 
	 zones, where we are confronting a range of difficult and demanding 
	 challenges.  We are encountering migratory populations of small scale 
	 miners (garimp&#233;iros), working the surface of the same lands for 
	 which the large scale developmental rights are being granted by 
	 governments to the newly invited-in foreign companies.  We are coming 
	 into contact with indigenous populations whose rights of land 
	 ownership and usage in most cases remain undefined in their 
	 countries' laws.  We are facing environmental issues, related to the 
	 impact of our activities on sensitive ecosystems newly exposed to our 
	 presence, such as tropical rainforests.  We are entering 
	 relationships with governmental regulatory agencies whose mandates 
	 and responsibilities often greatly exceed their managerial and 
	 technical capacity.  More fundamentally, we are relating across 
	 cultures to value systems and habitual practices which at various 
	 points conflict with our own basic beliefs and principles as to what 
	 is right, acceptable and conducive to everyone's best interests.  
	 Finally, as extractors of a depleting resource, we are inevitably 
	 giving rise to questions from various quarters as to how mining can 
	 possibly contribute to long-term sustainable development.
	<p>
	Responding to these challenges is imposing extensive demands on our 
	resources of time, talent and effort, as well as on our capacity for 
	flexibility, ingenuity and strategic thinking.  Each situation and set 
	of circumstances requires its own, often unique, response.  However, 
	at least three generalizations appear appropriate.
	<p>
	First, multinational mining companies need to reach out to credible 
	allies, institutions which can lend support in addressing these 
	challenges.  For example, national or multilateral aid agencies may 
	have a role to play in optimizing the developmental potential of a 
	mine in the surrounding area. Global non-governmental organizations 
	(NGOs), focused for example on environment (assuming they are 
	scientifically oriented and not purely political), or on social and 
	economic development, or on particular interests, such as indigenous 
	people, may also complement and add credibility to a company's efforts 
	to deal with these issues.  Within countries, foreign mining companies 
	need to be clearly allied to the interests of communities in a strong 
	spirit of cooperation with their local institutions.  Not uncommonly 
	in frontier zones, foreign companies run the risk of becoming 
	surrogate governments, directly providing goods and services to the 
	surrounding community, which the government may have the 
	responsibility but not the capacity to deliver.  Our role should be to 
	strengthen, and sometimes help create, local institutions to support 
	community growth and improvement.
	<p>
	Secondly, multinational mining companies need to clearly recognize and 
	respect the ethical principles that relate to our activities.  
	Corruption, human rights and social issues in many developing 
	countries raise ethical challenges.  These have the potential to 
	become as demanding of the industry's attention and its ability to 
	respond as have been environmental challenges during the past couple 
	of decades.
	<p>
	We need to think through our role with respect to combatting official 
	corruption, to promoting political change in support of human rights, 
	and towards acting as a catalyst for local and national economic and 
	social progress.  Ultimately, I think we will need to articulate our 
	global ethical principles and hold ourselves accountable to acting in 
	conformity with those principles.
	<p>
	Thirdly, multinational mining companies need to define our activities 
	in the framework of "sustainable development."  This policy 
	orientation is being embraced by many governments, including those of 
	many developing countries.  The concept of sustainable development is 
	open to many definitions, but key elements for the mining industry 
	include effective public consultation with populations affected by 
	mine development, equitable distribution of wealth generated by mining 
	to local communities, and effective management of the environmental 
	and socio-economic impacts of mining both during operations and after 
	mine closure.
	<p>
	With this background, I invite you to consider one case of a 
	multinational mining company endeavouring to meet the challenges of 
	building a mine in a frontier zone of a developing country: Placer 
	Dome's Las Cristinas mine in Venezuela, as captured in this brief 
	video clip from an hour-long CNN program on the globalization of gold 
	mining.
	<p>
	(Show video: CNN clip "Fool's Gold")<p>
	Placer Dome is endeavouring to address the complex set of challenges 
	you have just seen through the following multi-faceted strategy:
	<p>
     <strong>(1) Public participation in decision-making.</strong>  Planning for the 
     Las Cristinas mine has involved extensive public consultation 
     with all affected communities, indigenous people, small miners 
     and municipalities in the region.  One instrument of public 
     consultation is the socio-economic impact study, which was 
     undertaken by Venezuelan sociologists, anthropologists, 
     economists and community relations professionals during the 
     course of a year.  Ultimately, the way in which the operation 
     relates to local communities needs to clearly reflect their 
     expressed needs and preferences.
	<p>
	<strong>(2) Constructive engagement with the small scale miners.</strong>  We are 
	facilitating the development of a cooperative with limited membership, 
	which will be allowed to continue small scale mining on a defined part 
	of the Las Cristinas concession.
	<p>
	<strong>(3) A program for improving the health and environmental impact of 
	small scale mining.</strong>  We particularly want to eliminate their use of 
	mercury to recover gold.
	<p>
	<strong>(4) Community improvement.</strong>  We are supporting community self-help 
	programs involved in building community physical infrastructure, as 
	well as local institutional development, with a particular focus on 
	municipal government.
	<p>
	<strong>(5) Training and education of the local community.</strong>  We want to enable 
	as many local people as possible to find economic roles other than 
	small scale mining, either through employment by our mine or in other 
	local businesses, or through the start-up of their own small 
	enterprises.
	<p>
	<strong>(6) Provision of financing mechanisms for small business start-up.</strong>  We 
	are looking into the possible establishment of a cooperatively run 
	revolving fund, which would provide loan financing to local 
	entrepreneurs.
	<p>
     <strong>(7) Coming to terms with the rain forest issue.</strong>  We believe 
     that our environmental management and reclamation plans are 
     more favourable to the long term well-being of the rain forest 
     than the unrestricted activity of small scale miners.  
     Nevertheless, some forest will need to be removed to 
     accommodate the Las Cristinas mine.  To compensate, a program 
     of forest enhancement, using former small scale miners who 
     have been appropriately trained may be implemented.
	<p>
	<strong>(8) Collaboration with Venezuelan and Canadian NGOs in the foregoing 
	community development initiatives.</strong>  We have an alliance with the local 
	Catholic church NGO, Fe y Alegria, and have entered discussions with 
	other Venezuelan NGOs, with CIDA, and with Canadian NGOs.
	<p>
	In conclusion, let me say that I know of no perfect solutions to any 
	of the many challenges posed to mine development in the frontier zones 
	of the world.  What matters most is the correct orientation.  What we 
	can achieve may be limited to incremental improvements in the right 
	direction. However, over the life of a mine, the accumulation of those 
	improvements can become truly significant.  A key factor in making 
	sustainable progress will be the involvement of non-governmental 
	organizations whose institutional presence can help maintain the 
	levels of development achieved, even beyond the life of the mine.  Our 
	objective is to bring about social, environmental and economic 
	improvements which make a lasting contribution to the development of 
	the country where we are operating.  For at the end of the day, mining 
	can only be judged in the context of sustainable development by what remains after the mine closes.



	<br><br><br>

	<tr>
	<td colspan=2 align=center>
			
