	</td>
	
	
	<tr>
	<td>
	<a href="09d.html">Back to "Speeches and Presentations"</a>
	
	<p>
	

	<h2>
	1996 Annual Meeting Presentation</a><br>
	</h2>
    
   
    <font size=-1>
	April 15, 1996<br>
	Royal York Hotel, Toronto<br>
    
    
    <p>
	
	
	<a href="#01">John Willson, President & CEO</a><br>
	<a href="#02">Ian Austin, Senior Vice-President & CFO</a><br>
	<a href="#03">Eliseo Gonz&#225;lez-Urien, Senior Vice-President, Exploration</a><br>
	<a href="#04">Bill Trythall, Vice-President, Evaluations</a><br>
	<a href="#05">Douglas Fraser, President & CEO, Placer Dome Canada</a><br>
	<a href="#06">Jay Taylor, President & CEO, Placer Dome U.S.</a><br>
	<a href="#07">Bill Hayes, President & CEO, Placer Dome Latin America</a><br>
	<a href="#08">Henry Brehaut, Senior Vice-President, Environment</a><br>
	</font>
	
	
	<p>
	<a name="01">
    <strong>John Willson:</strong></a>
    <br>
      It is my privilege and pleasure to welcome you to Placer 
      Dome's Annual General  Meeting.
 <p>
      We are very unhappy and indeed humiliated to be conducting 
      this meeting under   the cloud of the unfortunate accident in 
      the Philippines. As Rob has said we will      be talking about 
      this and you will have the opportunity to ask questions to 
      which we will respond.
 <p>
      Before talking about Marcopper I just want to mention three 
      things:
	 <p>
	<li>We will be reporting a poor first quarter due to a number of mining 
	difficulties that reduced our gold output to below targeted levels.
	 <p>
	<li>We are very encouraged by news from Venezuela that exchange controls 
	will be lifted, news that favours our important Las Cristinas project.
	<p>
	<li>And we are very pleased that despite the shame we feel, and the 
	slings and arrows that we are suffering as a result of the Marcopper 
	accident, our shareholders continue to support us, as shown by the 
	share price.
	<p>
	In the Philippines on March 24th, a massive flow of mine waste which is 
	a mixture of sand and water called tailings started to escape from a 
	drainage tunnel into a river which flows 27 km to the ocean.  This is 
	the only environmental accident on this scale in which we have been 
	involved.  This should not have happened, we have expressed regret and 
	I do so again in all humility to you today.
	<p>
	Our immediate concern is for residents of the riverbanks that have 
	been affected and for their property.  Marcopper, with our backing, 
	has been quick and continues to be diligent in ensuring the health and 
	safety of the local population, in seeking to stop the flow and to 
	lessen the impacts of the sand, silt and water flows in the river.
	<p>
	As regrettable as this accident is, let us keep it in perspective.  No 
	person to our knowledge was injured by the spill, though there was 
	limited property damage.  No loss of livestock has been confirmed and 
	it is unlikely that any long-term environmental damage will occur.
	<p>
	We are well along with mobilizing the technical and financial 
	resources to stop the flow, determine the cause, assist and compensate 
	all the affected people, and to design and implement a permanent 
	solution. Henry Brehaut, our Senior Vice-President, Environment, who 
	has just returned from the Philippines, will bring us up-to-date on 
	the situation at Marcopper later in this presentation, and there will 
	be a question period during this meeting, and a media conference right 
	after it.
	<p>
	Reverting now to our presentation.
	<p>
	We are fortunate in Placer Dome to be making progress towards our 
	growth objective.
	<p>
	We have started construction of  two more mines this year and expect 
	to announce three more within 12 months.   By 1998, we expect to be 
	producing 2.5 million ounces of gold per year on an annualized basis.
	<p>
	To make today's presentation more informative, instead of a 
	report-back by myself from the podium, we have a number of our senior 
	managers from around the world.
	<p>
	As our Annual Report states, our goal is to provide growth for you, 
	our investors.  Our key to achieving this is to increase the value of  
	the Company by increasing our level of gold reserves and production 
	per share, as well as earnings and cash flow per share.
	<p>
	 That means each share you hold becomes more valuable because it 
	 represents more gold and more quality economic activity.
	<p>
	As a gold mining company, what sets us apart is our integrated ability 
	to raise and manage money, to find gold deposits, evaluate them, 
	develop and build them, and then to conduct mining operations and 
	environmental protection.
	<p>
	Our exploration pipeline has 85 mid-stage and advanced projects 
	located in 28 countries.  Of  these, the most exciting projects are in 
	Alaska and Costa Rica.  Further along the pipe are three development 
	projects close to approval, and closer to the production outlet are 
	two mines under construction.
	<p>
	Last year we completed construction of two new mines and two major 
	expansions.  I have a video clip here of one of those openings, a 
	blast at the Zald&#237;var mine in Chile.
	<p>
	That's a copper mine, but if we begin construction on new projects as 
	we expect we would add about 800,000 ounces of gold to our annual 
	output, and reach our production target of 2.5 million ounces of gold 
	per year on an annualized basis during 1998, about two years earlier 
	than we originally forecast in 1992.
	<p>
	During this period production from some of our existing mines, 
	particularly those in Papua New Guinea, will decline but this will be 
	eclipsed by the new production.
	<p>
	To give you a perspective on the people behind these achievements, to 
	show you a sampling of the strength and depth of our management team, 
	we have a number of people here today who will carry the presentation, 
	assisted by charts, pictures and video clips of our projects.
	<p>
	These people represent each of our strengths which, in total, we 
	believe make us a very strong competitor in our chosen field.
	<p>
	We have Ian Austin, our Senior Vice-President and Chief Financial 
	Officer to show you our strategy and how well we are doing with it, 
	and to briefly comment on recent results.
	<p>
	Eliseo Gonz&#225;lez-Urien, Senior Vice-President Exploration, will give 
	a brief overview of our ongoing gold finding success -- our 
	"legendary" exploration performance, as it was described by one 
	highly-respected gold analyst.
	<p>
	Bill Trythall, Vice-President Evaluations, who is responsible for 
	producing our feasibility studies and computing ore reserves and 
	resources, will speak about the process of  that activity and the 
	development part of the pipeline, an area that we believe is another 
	unusual strength.
	<p>
	We are diversified internationally, and fortunate that three of our 
	four regional CEOs were able to join us today from Canada (Doug 
	Fraser), the U.S. (Jay Taylor), and Latin America (Bill Hayes) to show 
	highlights of growth activities in their regions.  Unfortunately Dick 
	Zandee, the newly-appointed Managing Director of Placer Pacific in 
	Sydney, Australia, was unable to join us.
	<p>
	Lastly, but by no means least, Henry Brehaut, Senior Vice-President, 
	Environment, is here to say a few words about how we strive to lessen 
	the impacts of our activities and to make good what we have disturbed.  
	As I said, he will also update us on Marcopper.
	
	<p>
	<a name="02">
	<strong>Ian Austin:</strong></a>
	<br>
	<li> As John was saying, we seek global growth in gold.
	<p>
	<li> We intend to add shareholder value through successful exploration.
	<p>
	<li> While we produce metals other than gold, we plan to keep gold revenues 
	above 75% of total revenue.
	<p>
	<li> How are we doing relative to our plan?
	<p>
	<li> Our first quarter gold production, which I can announce today, was 
	458,000 ounces, which is less than planned, but we still expect to 
	achieve our goal of 2 million ounces in 1996.
	<p>
	<li> We are focused on gold production and on investing in exploration for 
	more gold.
	<p>
	<li> Total operating earnings show a growth trend.
	<p>
	<li> Decline in gold's contribution to total earnings in 1995 will turn 
	around in 1996.
	<p>
	<li> Exploration expense will remain at about $100 million per year.
	<p>
	<li> Canada generated half of  total operating earnings in 1995, much from 
	molybdenum.
	<p>
	<li> Contribution from Papua New Guinea declining.
	<p>
	<li> United States will contribute more in future.
	<p>
	<li> Cash and Short-term Investments $321 million at end of 1995 after 
	Capital expenditures of $451 million.
	<p>
	<li> Cash flow a strong $230 million per year.
	<p>
	<li> We should generate $350 million in cash in 1996 with help of new and 
	expanded mines.
	<p>
	As in 1995 with Zald&#237;var and Osborne, we expect new mines will 
	continue to be financed by cash and short-term investments, cash flow 
	and some debt. No issue of new equity as we see it today, or at least 
	for the five projects we have mentioned.
	
	<p>
	
	<a name="03">
	<strong>Eliseo Gonz&#225;lez-Urien:</strong></a><br>
	
	<li> Map illustrates target areas for our global activities.
	<p>
	<li> Currently more than 85 active projects around the world.
	<p>
	<li> Added 3 million ounces after producing 1.9 million in 1995.
	<p>
	<li> And 4.4 million ounces in measured and indicated mineralization.
	<p>
	<li> From 1991 to 1995 have added 30 million ounces to our mineral 
	inventory at an average finding cost of $16 per ounce, further 
	evidence of very cost effective growth.
	<p>
	<li> Steady growth in reserves reflects only partially this exploration 
	success because discoveries take time to reach reserve status.  In 
	fact several projects are advancing towards reserve status, but are 
	not included in the above list
	<p>
	<li> Chart shows all South American reserves in Chile but this will change 
	as we add Venezuela and Costa Rica.
	<p>
	<li> Note importance of North America.
	<p>
	<li> See further major increases in 1996 from inclusion of Las Cristinas 
	and Mulatos and probably thereafter from Cerro Crucitas and Donlin 
	Creek.
	<p>
	<li> The Donlin Creek project was one of our success stories of 1995.
	<p>
	
	Our work since last June has identified a resource of more than 5 
	million ounces. This year we will spend US$6 million to US$8 million 
	dollars to further define resources in at least four target areas, two 
	of which have received over 100 drillholes to date.
	<p>
	Strategically, our exploration is based on aggressive, disciplined, 
	well-funded programmes in areas of the world which are geologically 
	most promising for discovery of gold deposits, where our early 
	presence may give us an advantage.
	<p>
	In addition to our significant effort in North America and Australia, 
	we explore in countries newly opened to international mining 
	investment where we seek what we call mid-stage projects for further 
	evaluation.  These projects hold the most promise of helping us fulfil 
	our growth goals at an acceptable finding cost.
	<p>
	At nearly $100 million a year we are probably one of the best funded 
	exploration outfits in the gold sector.
	<p>
	These strategies have been successful so far and will continue to be 
	the basis of our growth in the future.
	<p>
	
	<a name="04">
	<strong>Bill Trythall:</strong></a><br>
	
	<li> Our   evaluation,   design   and   construction   teams   turn 
	exploration   projects   into   operating   mines.
	<p>
	<li> The  core  group of evaluation engineers in the   
	Vancouver Project Development Division is staffed with   
	25 mining, geological, mechanical and civil engineers   
	involved in the evaluation process from scoping   
	studies through to bankable feasibility studies.
	<p>
	<li> This   group   is   supported   by   Exploration's   Resource 
	Estimating Group   and   by   metallurgical,   mechanical   and 
	electrical   engineer in   Project   Development's   design   group. 
	Computer   Applications staff   provide   the   needed   mine   design   
	software   and   cash flow   modeling   capability.    PDG's 
	environmental  staff   complete the   evaluation   team.
	<p>
	<li> Smaller,   but   just   as   experienced,   core   groups   of   
	evaluation engineers   have   been   established  in   Placer Pacific,   
	Placer Dome   Latin   America   and   Placer   Dome   U.S. they   make   
	a significant   contribution   to    PDG's   overall evaluation   
	process.
	<p>
	<li> From   mine   scoping   study   through   to   the   publishing   of   
	a feasibility   study   can   take   up   to   3   years   and   cost   
	up to $15   million   dollars   inclusive   of   late   stage   
	exploration drilling.    Evaluation   and   Pre-feasibility   Studies   
	are   often necessary   prior   to   commissioning   the   final   
	feasibility study.
	<p>
	<li> A   typical   6   volume   Feasibility   Study   covers:
        Geology,   Exploration   and   Resource   Estimates -<li> Mine   
        Design   and   Ore   Reserves -<li> Metallurgical   Testwork   and   
        Process   Plant   Design -<li> Environmental   Studies   and   
        Socio   Economic   Matters -<li> Power,   Water,   and tailing  
        Studies -<li> Legal   Matters -<li> Capital   and   Operating   Cost   
        Estimates -<li> Project   Economics   and  risk assessment
	<p>
	<li> Two   Feasibility   Studies   were   completed   in   the   first   
	quarter of   1996,   namely   Musselwhite   and   Las   Cristinas.
	<p>
	<li> Three   additional   studies   are   scheduled   for   completion   in 
	1996: Cerro   Crucitas,   Mount   Rawdon   and   Mulatos.
	<p>
	<li> Pipeline   was  finalized   in 1995   and   Donlin   Creek   is   
	scheduled for   completion   in   1997.
	<p>
	<li> Exploration   projects   do   become   operating   mines.
    
    <p>
	<a name="05">
    <strong>Doug Fraser:</strong></a>
    <br>
      <li> Placer Dome Canada is in the midst of a major growth phase.
	<p>	
		<li> Canadian mines produced 866,000 ounces of gold in 1995, or 46% of Placer
		Dome's 1.9 million ounces.   We are constructing a new gold mine at
		Musselwhite in northern Ontario at a cost to Placer Dome of US$130 million.
	<p>	
		<li> We are also spending US$51 million to sink a new shaft at the
		Campbell Mine.
	<p>	
		<li> The Detour Lake Mine has just undergone a mill expansion and while we are
		also solving some mining problems, we are exploring a promising new zone of
		mineralization.  Improvements are also under way at our two mines in
		Quebec.
	<p>	
		<li> With all this, Canadian mines are expected to be producing 1.2 million
		ounces of gold annually as their contribution to the Placer Dome Group's
		growth objectives.
	<p>	
		<li> The major contributor will be 135,000 ounces per year from Musselwhite.
	<p>	
		<li> The other big item at Placer Dome Canada is the depth development project
		at Campbell Mine.
	<p>	
		We have recognized the increased potential of finding new ore at depth.
		While the mine currently has reserves of under 10 years, with the new shaft
		we expect to extend the life of the mine further into the next century.
		
	<p>	
		<a name="06">
		<strong>Jay Taylor:</strong></a><br>
		
		<li> Placer Dome U.S. is on the threshold of making big contributions to the
		Placer Dome Group.
		<p>
		<li> One factor is that the Golden Sunlight Mine in Montana after 12 years
		finally gets into the heart of the orebody and we'll have considerably
		higher grades for a number of years.
		<p>
		<li> But the major development will be the commissioning in June next year of
		the Pipeline Project.  With an open pit grade of more than 4 grams of gold
		per tonne and more than four million ounces of gold in the ground this is
		the top Placer Dome project.
		<p>
		<li> On March 4, after three and a half years of study by the federal and state
		governments, we received permits to develop the deposit.
		<p>
		<li> On the same day, we started moving the first dirt for the open pit.  This
		video was taken a few days after.
		<p>
		<li> Capital expenditure $320 million of which our share is $192 million.
		<p>
		<li> New plant will have built-in flexibility to accommodate future potential of
		Cortez.
		<p>
		<li> Our share of production 250,000 ounces of gold in the early years.
		<p>
		<li> Lowest cost mine in the group at $110 per ounce.
		<p>
		<li> Operating earnings in early years $43 million based on gold at $375 per ounce.
		<p>
		<li> Separate South Pipeline is lower grade but has contributed 1.5 million ozs.
		to reserves end of 1995.  Exploration continuing, expected to increase
		reserves modestly.
		<p>
		<li> We are preparing a feasibility study on the Mulatos deposit in Mexico, seen
		here.
		<p>
		<li> Our 70% share of the resource is 2.3 million ounces.  At a grade of 1.1
		grams gold per tonne it is a bigger challenge than Pipeline.
		<p>
		<li> We also have a nearby community that will be impacted and we have to manage
		the changes which a mine will bring.
		<p>
		<li> The feasibility study is due to be completed by the end of the year.
		<p>
		<li> This appears to be a good-sized heap-leach operation.
		<p>
		<li> If all goes according to plan, Placer Dome U.S. could have a new mine
		starting here in 1998 and producing more than 100,000 ounces a year for our
		account.
		<p>
		<li> The Pipeline and Mulatos projects, plus higher production at Golden
		Sunlight, will be major contributors to the Placer Dome Group's growth
		spurt.
		
		<p>
		<a name="07">
		<strong>Bill Hayes:</strong></a><br>
		
		
		<li> Greetings from Latin America, where we are also going through an exciting
		period of growth.
		<p>
		<li> The Zald&#237;var copper mine in which we have a 50% interest started operations
		last year.
	    <p>	
		<li> It is operating to plan and is forecast to produce 85,000 tonnes of cathode
		copper in 1996.
		<p>
		From the high desert country of the Atacama desert we go to a different
		climate where we are about to go ahead with construction of the largest
		precious metals mine in South America.
		<p>
		<li> This is a project we are proud of because it demonstrates Placer Dome's
		expertise at each phase of the mine development process, from exploration
		to production.
		<p>
		<li> The property adds 8 million ounces to our ore reserves at minimal finding
		cost, which is the kind of cost-effective growth we strive for.
		<p>
		<li> When this starts operating in 1998, it will produce nearly half a million
		ounces of gold per year for at least 15 years.   And we are certain we will
		add further reserves in the Mesones/Sofia area close to the main deposits,
		where this drill is operating.
		<p>
		<li> We now go to Costa Rica where we have started a pre-feasibility study on
		the Cerro Crucitas property.  This is another one with a minimal finding
		cost.
		<p>
		<li> The gold was discovered in these distinctive dome-shaped hills.
		<p>
		<li> Cerro Crucitas is in a country famous for eco-tourism and which does not
		have a mining tradition.  The way we strive to operate mines is not out of
		keeping with the values of Costa Rica.  We have mobilized an information
		effort in the communities and with the Government.
		
		<p>
		<a name="08">
		<strong>Henry Brehaut:</strong></a><br>
		
		<li> The Latin American operations and future projects are good examples of our
		environmental responsibilities.  Cerro Crucitas has become a model
		exploration project with reclamation of disturbed areas.
		<p>
		<li> At Las Cristinas environmental factors were important considerations in the
		design of key components such as tailing dam design, effluent quality and
		site water control.  At Zald&#237;var and La Coipa we are implementing
		leading-edge environmental management systems.
		<p>
		<li> For the closure of the Equity Silver Mine we developed innovative solutions
		to reduce acid rock drainage and have provided $32 million to ensure our
		obligations are met over the long-term as long as treatment is required.
		<p>
		<li> The same commitment and effort will be applied to the remediation of the
		Marcopper tailing discharge.  We already have a good example of this
		commitment in the Philippines at the abandoned tailing disposal site in
		Calancan Bay.
		<p>
		<li> When Marcopper ceased the disposal of tailing in the bay in 1991, we
		restored the area by growing vegetation on the waste material seen here on
		this causeway.  It is now a swimming area of choice with shade and sandy
		beaches.
		<p>
		<li> In the water, mangrove trees have been planted along the shoreline with
		good success and this programme is continuing.  In deeper water seagrass is
		being transplanted and artificial reef structures are being put in place.
		We have restored the habitat to attract a wide range of fish species.
		<p>
		<li> All this work has led to the return of an active fishery in the bay at a
		productivity greater than that of surrounding areas.
        <p>		
		<li> Reclamation is part of our ongoing mining activities as illustrated by our
		Bald Mountain Mine in Nevada.  Waste dumps are also planned in advance to
		meld with local topography.  Bald Mountain has received an award from the
		State of Nevada for the quality of their programmes.
		<p>
		<li> At our Golden Sunlight Mine in Montana reclamation is also important.  The
		final configuration of the dumps has been projected and whereever possible
		final slopes are reclaimed when available.
		<p>
		 <li> This programme is supported by an extensive research program and the
		results to date are very encouraging as illustrated by the excellent growth
		that has been established and by the diversity of wildlife which is found
		on the site.
		<p>
		<li> For the Musselwhite project environmental considerations have been in the
		forefront.  This is the site as it is today.
		<p>
		<li> This is how we envisage it when it is operating.  Musselwhite should be an
		example of how neat and clean a mining operation can be.
		<p>
		<li> And this is how we expect it to be when mining has ceased, long after I've
		retired. Musselwhite has developed a vision of what a mining project should
		look like once the ore has been extracted.  It will be returned to part of the
		local ecosystem.
		<p>
		<li> We have started the process of having all our mines develop such a vision
		of how they wish the site to be reclaimed to best advantage.
		
	    <p>
	    
		<strong>John Willson:</strong></a><br>
		
		I regret that Dick Zandee was not able to be with us today from Sydney.
		<p>
		However, I have some pictures to show you on behalf of Placer Pacific, our
		75%-owned subsidiary, of which I am the Chairman.
		<p>
		The notable event of the year was bringing the Osborne Mine into production
		in Queensland.
		<p>
		Now that Osborne is in production, in Australia we are turning our
		attention to Mt. Rawdon which is a gold heap leach project on which we are
		currently conducting a feasibility study.
		<p>
		This is a property we have held since 1980.
		<p>
		The leaching properties of the ore are looking good.  Soon we'll be in a
		position to make a decision.  At a capital cost of about US$25 million, 
		we could add another 50,000 ounces per year to our production.
		<p>
		This nine-metre-high, roller-compacted concrete water supply weir was
		constructed ahead of the feasibility study to allow two season's rainfall
		to collect in readiness for possible commissioning of the mine in early
		1997.
		<p>
		With that, I want to conclude our "show and tell" by reiterating it is
		clear from what we have seen that our Company is in a strong position to
		grow.
		<p>
		Production will grow to 2.5 million ounces per year during 1998.  As to how
		we will finance this growth, Ian assures me that with a combination of our
		cash in hand, cash flow and some debt we can make it happen.
		<p>
		And all over the world, Eliseo and his team will continue to conduct their
		successful strategies of gold discovery which can give us growth in
		shareholder value.
        <p>		
		My colleagues and I would be happy to answer your questions, both now and
		afterwards when we have finished the meeting.

