<HTML><TITLE>International Admission Information and Electronic
Application</title>
<BODY>
<Center>
<H2>Electronic Application Instructions and<br>
Admission Information for International Students
</H2><P></Center>
<B>IMPORTANT: All <I>supplementary documentation</I> (except test
scores) should be mailed together in one envelope.</B><p>
Applicants to the graduate programs at Clemson University must
hold a four-year bachelor's degree (or equivalent) or a master's
degree from an institution whose scholastic rating is
satisfactory to the University.  Initial enrollment of
international students in summer sessions is strongly
discouraged.<P>

<H3>Application Fee</H3><P>

A $35 non refundable application fee payable to Clemson
University via money order or a check drawn on a U.S. bank, is
required. If you apply to a second program, you do not need to
pay an additional fee.  If you apply to more than two programs,
each program after the second will require an additional $35 fee.
The application fee(s) must be
received before the application will be processed. 
<B>Application fee(s)
cannot be waived or deferred.</B>  Applications received
electronically will be discarded after 60 days if application fee
is not received.<P>

<H3>Application Deadline Dates</H3><P>
<OL>
<LI><B>Students from abroad.</B> Completed applications for
admission of prospective international students from abroad
<B>must be</B> received by the Graduate School by May 1 and
October 1 for registration in the subsequent fall and spring
semesters, respectively. <B>Every required item in support of the
application must be on file with the Graduate School by these
dates.</B> A number of programs have earlier deadlines or
restrict admission to fall semester only. Students should contact
the department of their interest for the deadlines. <P>
International applicants living outside the United States should
complete the required standardized tests at least three months
prior to May 1 and October 1, as appropriate.  Documents for a
student visa will be issued no later than June 15 and November 1
for registration in fall and spring semesters, respectively. 
Initial enrollment of international students during the summer
sessions is strongly discouraged and is permitted only on rare
occasions.<P>
<LI><B>Students living in the United States.</B> International
students living in the United States do not require Form I-20
from OIPS until they arrive on the Clemson University Campus. 
Consequently, slightly more time is allowed for international
students living in the United States to complete their
applications for admission to the University.  Completed
applications for admission of prospective international students
who currently reside in the United States should be received by
the Graduate School by June 15 and November 1 for registration in
the subsequent fall and spring semesters, respectively.  Every
required item in support of the application must be on file with
the Graduate School by these dates.<P>
</OL>
<H3>Application Time Limit</H3><P>
Generally, acceptance under an application is valid for one year
beyond the initial date desired for enrollment.  Academic
departments reserve the right to deny deferred admission because
of limited space and/or resources.  Thus, students must make a
written request for deferred enrollment from the department in
which they wish to study.<P>
After an application has become invalid, a student must reapply
to the University by submitting a new application, including
the required fee.  Students also need to resubmit all academic
supporting materials with the application. All application
materials received must be in the original form.<P>

<H3>Transcripts and References</H3><P>
Official transcripts of academic records must be received from
each postsecondary college and/or university attended before an
application can be processed.  Students should request two (2)
official transcripts of their academic work from the respective
registrar's office of each college or university attended.  The
transcripts should be in a sealed envelope.  Include both an
official copy written in one's native language and an official
English translation of all academic records.  For those
institutions that provide transcripts of academic work in
English, a transcript in the native language is not required. 
<B>DO NOT OPEN THE ENVELOPE ONCE SEALED.</B><P>
A minimum of two (2) recommendations is required for certain
degree programs.  Please request that the recommenders complete
the <A Href="recommfm.htm">Recommendation Form</a> and return
them to
you in sealed envelopes.  <B>DO NOT OPEN THESE ENVELOPES.</B><P>

<H3>Required Test Scores</H3><P>
A satisfactory score on the Graduate Management Admission Test
(GMAT) is required of each applicant to the master's program in
major codes 505, 509 and 520, and may be accepted in lieu of GRE
scores for the PhD program in major code 520. Except as just
noted, a satisfactory score on the general portion of the
Graduate Examination (GRE) is required of each applicant.<P>
Test of English as a Foreign Language (TOEFL) scores are required
of all international applicants whose native language is not
English and whose secondary education (and beyond) was not taught
fully in English.  Applicants who hope to receive a graduate
assistantship must submit scores from the Test of Written English
(TWE) administered simultaneously with the TOEFL at most test
locations.<P>
GRE and GMAT scores are valid for five (5) years, and the TOEFL
and TWE scores are valid for two (2) years.  All scores must be
sent directly from the <A HREF=http://www.gre.org/>Educational
Testing Service (ETS)</A> in
Princeton, New Jersey. Outdated test scores will not be accepted.
<P>

<H3>International Programs and Services</H3><P>
The Office of International Programs and Services (OIPS) is
responsible for providing all supportive services unique to
international students as well as encouraging students to utilize
the services of all student affairs units on campus.<P>
The staff of OIPS includes a director, an international student
advisor, an exchange visitor coordinator and support staff.<P>
OIPS provides orientation, registration, guidance and counseling,
immigration advising, cultural programming and other forms of
support to international students, international student
organizations, faculty and international exchange visitors.<P>
OIPS cooperates with Clemson Area International Friendship (CAIF)
to provide community programming.<P>

<H3>International Student Financial Certification</H3><P>
U. S. universities are required by law to verify that students
entering the United States on temporary visas have adequate
financial resources to meet expenses.  Clemson University
requires all fees to be paid on the first day of late
registration. Loans and deferred payments generally are not
available to international students. A minimum of one (1) year's
expenses must be available to the student upon arrival.  The
Certificate of Eligibility for F-1 visa (Form I-20) will not be
issued without the receipt by Clemson University of approved
documents verifying funds.  All documentation must be current,
and signatures must be original.  Photocopies or FAX copies of
the documentation will not be accepted.  The deadline for
submitting this <A HREF="fincert.htm">Financial Certification
Form</a>
 is May 1 for the
fall semester and October 1 for the spring semester.
<P>

<H3>Important Information</H3><P>
The Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act of 1974 protects
the information provided by applicants to the University which is
retained in official records and documents.  University staff are
not allowed to divulge certain information contained in these
document to applicants, relatives or friends.<P>
Do <B>NOT</B> request friends or relatives to inquire about the
status
of applications, admission decisions, etc.  Processing of
applications and visa credentials is affected adversely by
telephone calls from abroad, E-Mail or visits to the Admissions
or OIPS offices by friends attending Clemson University.  In
order to serve prospective students better, please read carefully
the information provided below.<P>
An applicant to Clemson University (who can establish proper
identity) may call Graduate Admissions, (864) 656-3195 or E-Mail,
grdapp@clemson.clemson.edu, to inquire about the following:<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>*receipt of official test scores (GRE, TOEFL,
GMAT or TWE) from ETS.</BLOCKQUOTE><P>
Or, an applicant may call OIPS, (864)656-3614 or E-Mail,
findlej@clemson.clemson.edu, to inquire about the issuance of
visa credentials (IAP-66 or I-20 forms).<P>
Decisions to admit students to the University are made by
individual departments.  DO NOT call, E-Mail or write Graduate
Admissions or OIPS to inquire whether or not admission has been
granted.<P>

Approximate notification of admission decision: three months
following receipt of <I><B>completed application.</I></B><P>

Remember to use your NR identification number when corresponding
with the Office of International Programs and Services, the
Graduate School and/or the department. <B>Inquiries without the
NR
identification number will not be answered.</B><P>
         

<H2><Center>APPLICATION CHECK LIST</H2></Center><P>
<table border>
<td nowrap valign=top>Step 1<td>Read all
<B>application instructions.</B><tr>
<td nowrap valign=top>Step 2 <td>Electronic application
form must be complete.<tr>
<td nowrap valign=top>Step 3 <td>If you have
not already done so, register
for the
GRE, GMAT, TOEFL and TWE examinations as appropriate.  The
Information and Registration Bulletin may be obtained by
contacting USIS office, binational centers, your institution or
<A HREF=http://www.gre.org/>ETS</A> (P. O. Box 6000, Princeton,
New Jersey 08541-6000, U.S.A.)<tr> 
<td nowrap valign=top>Step 4<td>If you have
already taken the appropriate
test(s),
request that the Educational Testing Service forward official
copies of your score(s) to Clemson University (institution code,
5111).  Be reminded that certified copies of your scores are not
acceptable except from sponsoring international agencies that
have received scores directly from ETS.<tr>
<td nowrap valign=top>Step 5<td>If you wish
to apply for assistantship,fellowship
or traineeship, complete the <A HREF="fin.htm">Financial
Assistance
Application.</a>  Please be certain to include the student
identification number (i.e., NR 000001) or U.S. Social Security
number in the space labeled "U.S. Social Security Number or NR
Identification Number". <B>NOTE:</B>  All future correspondence
and/or questions regarding financial assistance should be
addressed to the department to which you are
applying.<tr> 
<td nowrap valign=top>Step 6<td>Complete the
<A HREF="fincert.htm">International Student Financial
Certification Form.</a>  Source of funds and amounts must be
documented.  Attach documented proof of amounts indicated
(previous two months' bank statements and signatures of bank
officials if personal or family funds; letter of support from
sponsor; copy of letter of award of Clemson University
assistantship).  All documents should specify amount of funds in
U.S. dollars.  Visa credentials cannot be issued without required
proof of funding.  Documents must not be more than one year old
to be acceptable.<tr>
<td nowrap valign=top>Step 7<td>Use the
<A Href="recommfm.htm">Recommendation Form</a> to
obtain two (2) references, as
applicable.  Ask that each recommender complete a form, place it
in a envelope, seal it, sign the back of the envelope across the
seal and return it to you.  <B>Once you receive these sealed
recommendations, please do not open
them.</B><tr>
<td nowrap valign=top>Step 8<td>Request
that the registrar of each college or
university you have attended give you two (2) official
transcripts of your academic work.  These transcript should be in
a sealed envelope.  Include both an official copy in your native
language and an official English translation of all academic
records.  <B>Do not open these envelopes once sealed.</B>
<BLOCKQUOTE>(a)  If you have attended an institution that does
not transmit records similar to transcripts issued in the U.S.A.,
alternative documentation of your educational records will be
accepted.  All documents must be certified (i.e., each page
attested) by an authorized official of the institution(s) from
which you have received or will receive the degree(s). 
Uncertified or illegible copies will be rejected. All documents
received, including official transcripts, become the property of
the Graduate School and cannot be returned.</BLOCKQUOTE><P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>(b)  If you have attended an institution in the
U.S.A., you must request that the registrar send two (2) official
transcripts.  <A HREF="trans.htm">Request
Form.</a></blockquote><tr>
<td nowrap valign=top>Step 9<td>Applicants
admitted on the basis of a provisional
certificate must supply a copy of their degree(s), with an
English translation, within six (6) months of the date of
graduation or not later than one year after enrollment at Clemson
University.  A graduate degree will not be awarded in the absence
of these documents.  Applicants are, therefore, strongly
encouraged to forward this evidence prior to leaving their home
countries.<tr>
<td nowrap valign=top>Step 10<td>Please make
note of any materials, such as a portfolio, which are to be
submitted separately to the department.  Also, do not submit high
school transcripts, school-leaving certificates, or copies of
awards or honors.  Only send the
materials requested.<tr>
<td nowrap valign=top>Step 11<td>Package all
original documents together in an air
mail envelope:<p>
<UL>
<LI>Two sealed official transcripts
<LI>two sealed letters of recommendation
<LI>graduate assistantship form (optional)
<LI>the financial certification form and required documentation 
<LI>nonrefundable $35 application fee
</UL><tr>
</Table>

<P>
Be reminded that your application will not be processed
without the fee and that Clemson University cannot waive or defer
the fee.  If the application fee is not received within 60 days,
the electronic application will
be discarded. Be certain to write your NR student
identification (or U.S. Social Security) number on all envelopes
and application fee check.<P>
<dl>
<dt>Mail supporting documentation and application fee to:
<dd>The Graduate School
<dd>Clemson University
<dd>E-108 Martin Hall
<dd>Box 345120
<dd>Clemson, South Carolina 29634-5120
<dd>U.S.A.<P>
<H2><center>Electronic Application for International
Students</center></H2>
