<HR>





  <B><A NAME=Research Facilities and Resources></A><H2>Research
Facilities and
Resources</H2>
</B><P> 
     Activities coordinated by the Sponsored Programs Office
include sponsored 
     research; educational services; public service proposals to
outside agencies;
     patent disclosures, applications and negotiations of
licensing agreements; 
     and facility security clearance. Information and assistance
are available on
     applications for research support from federal and state
agencies, industrial
     organizations, foundations and institutes, and fellowships
of interest to the
     faculty. <P>
<P>
     Clemson University is a member of Oak Ridge Associated
Universities. ORAU, a
     consortium of colleges and universities, is a management and
operating
     contractor for the U.S. Department of Energy located in Oak
Ridge, Tenn.
     ORAU works with its member institutions to help students and
faculty gain 
     access to federal research facilities throughout the
country; to keep members
     informed about opportunities for fellowship, scholarship and
research 
     appointments; and to organize research alliances among
members. ORAU manages
     the Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education to give
undergraduate, 
     graduate and postgraduate students as well as faculty access
to a multitude
     of study and research opportunities. <P>
<P>
     The Electron Microscope Facility is equipped with
transmission electron 
     microscopes, scanning electron microscopes, an Auger
microprobe with a 
     secondary ion mass spectrometer, an atomic force microscope,
a virtual 
     reality work station and an XRF. This facility is one of the
most outstanding
     in the Southeast.<P>
<P>
     The Department of Experimental Statistics provides a
statistical consulting
     service to faculty, staff and graduate students. Advice and
assistance are
     provided in the design, analysis and interpretation of
research. Entry and 
     computer analysis of data are available. <p>
<P>
     The Department of Electronic and Photographic Services
produces professional
     quality video and audio tapes, multi-image presentations,
and still and motion
     picture photography.  Various types of projectors, screens,
and audio and
     visual recorders/players are available for loan. The unit
can produce and 
     receive state and nationwide audio or video
teleconferences.<P>
<P>
<B><A NAME=Library Facilities ></A><H2>
<A HREF="http://www.lib.clemson.edu/">Library Facilities
</A></B></H2><P>
<P>
     The Clemson University Libraries include the main Robert
Muldrow Cooper
     Library and one branch library, the Emery Gunnin
Architectural Library. The
     libraries have a collection of more than 7,000 serial titles
and 1,500,000
     volumes and volume equivalencies.  The collections are
developed to support
     the undergraduate and graduate curricula and research. <P>
<P>
     Outstanding collections of journals, books, government
documents and primary
     research materials have been developed in many areas,
especially agriculture,
     the natural and physical sciences, economics and technology.
<P>
<P>
     The libraries have an on-line catalog, LUIS (Library User
Information System),
     which permits access by any terminal tied to the
University's mainframe
     computer and by remote dial-up access. DORIS (Document
On-line Retrieval
     Information System) provides access to periodical literature
by electronic
     data bases housed on the University's mainframe, and
currently houses nine
     bibliographic data bases and seven locally created full-text
data bases.
     The Cooper Library is linked electronically to OCLC, Inc. to
more than
     11,000 other libraries around the world for cataloging and
interlibrary
     loan services.<P>
<P>
<B><A NAME=Computing Facilities ></A><H2>
<A HREF="http://www.cts.clemson.edu">Computing Facilities
</A></B></H2><P>
<P>
     The Clemson University Division of Computing and Information
Technology (DCIT)
     plays a central role in the life of the University by
providing computing
     services to faculty, staff and students of the University,
the state and 
     federal governments, and industry. <P>
<P>
     The division supports graduate student course work and
research through a
     network of on-campus computers. This network consists of an
MVS mainframe
     with 192 megabytes of main memory and several Digital
Equipment Corporation
     computers, including a VAX 6000-610 running Open VMS and a
DEC 3000-500
     computer running OSP/1.<P>
<P>
     Remote sites containing a variety of microcomputers,
terminals and 
     peripheral equipment are maintained in many academic
buildings, laboratories 
     and the Cooper Library.  An extensive campus Ethernet
connects all major
     buildings and computers on campus. The University is
connected to Internet,
     a global network of networks which support electronic mail
as well as remote
     login and file transfer. Gopher is available on all
DCIT-supported platforms,
     allowing access to a world of on-line information. Various
national and
     international networks are accessible.<P>
<P>
     Upon enrollment, each student is issued a computer user ID
on the MVS
     mainframe.  This allows access to a wide range of computing
services,
     including electronic mail, on-line registration and an
on-line housing
     sign-up system. <P>
<P>
<P>
</dl>
<A HREF="http://www.grad.clemson.edu/page1.htm"><IMG
SRC=/images/back.gif></A>
