<BODY background=/images/back1.gif><B><H2>
     <A NAME=QuickMark></A>Campus Living and Services</B></H2>
     <P>
     <LI><A HREF=#Housing><H3>Housing </A><P>
     <P>
     <LI><A HREF=#FoodService>Food Service </A><P>
     <P>
     <LI><A HREF=#HealthServices>Health Services </A><P>
     <P>
     <LI><A HREF=#CareerServices>Career Services </A><P>
     <P>
     <LI><A HREF=#GraduateStudentGovernment>Graduate Student
Government
     </A><P>
     <P>
     <LI><A HREF=#InternationalProgramsand>International Programs
and Services
</A><P></H3>
<hr>
     <B><A NAME=Housing ></A><H2>
<A HREF="http://www.housing.clemson.edu">Housing</H2></B></A>
<P>
Residence halls and apartments on the main campus
provide accommodations at economical rates for graduate students.
All University housing is air-conditioned, and cable television
is provided in the apartments and all residence halls. Residence
hall rooms are equipped with beds, chests of drawers, desks and
chairs. Two students share a room unless the single-occupancy
option is chosen. Apartments have two bedrooms, a living room and
a kitchen to be shared by four students.
<P>
Graduate students interested in single-student accommodations
should contact the Housing Office, (864)656-2295, for
information. An advance payment is required to reserve a room in
University housing. An on-campus graduate housing area also is
available for single graduate students. These apartments have two
bedrooms, a bathroom, kitchen and living room, and house two
students. All bedrooms are furnished, and utilities are included
in the rental cost.  Additional amenities include local telephone
service and basic cable.
<P>
The University also provides a limited number of comfortable and
economical family/faculty apartments located near the campus.
Students with a graduate assistantship or fellowship are given
first priority for family housing. Information concerning these
facilities is available from the University Family Housing
Office, (864)656-0829. Graduate students must have a graduate
assistantship or fellowship to qualify for this housing.
<P>
Commercial housing in the surrounding community accommodates the
majority of graduate students, both married and single. For more
information, contact the Clemson Chamber of Commerce.
<P>
For further information, contact:
<blockquote>
The Housing Office<br>
200 Mell Hall<br>
Clemson, SC 29634<br>
</blockquote>
(864) 656-2295.
<P>
     <B><A NAME=FoodService></A><H2>Food Service </H2></B><P>
     <P>
          The University offers several economical meal plans, a
declining
     balance account and meals on a cash basis in two student
dining halls. Students
     may use meal cards at the Clemson House. Meals also are
available in the
     canteen, or food may be purchased in the East Campus store
on a cash basis.
     <P>
     <P>
          Meal plans for graduate students are selected on a
semester or session
     basis. <P>
     <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
     <B><A NAME=HealthServices ></A><H2>Health Services
</H2></B><P>
     <P>
          Graduate students living in University residence halls
(irrespective of
     their enrollment) and all graduate students enrolled in 12
or more semester
     hours who pay full-time rates (irrespective of their
residence) are required to
     pay the University medical fee. The fee covers a variety of
medical services,
     including outpatient treatment for illness and injury,
health education, women's
     health care, nutritional counseling, dermatology care and
orthopedic clinics.
     <P>
     <P>
          The medical fee covers the services of the University
physicians, nurse
     practitioners and nursing staff, and supports in part
psychologists in the
     Counseling and Psychological Services Department. There is a
nominal
     copayment for laboratory and X-ray procedures performed at
the health center.
     Dental and optical care are not offered by the health
service but can be
     obtained locally at the student's expense. <P>
     <P>
          The University offers an inexpensive plan of accident
and sickness
     insurance designed to help cover major medical expenses not
covered by the
     health plan. <P>
     <P>
          The health service is housed in Redfern Health Center,
an ambulatory
     outpatient facility. Physician care is available during
hours. The nurses clinic
     assists students in handling minor illnesses and injuries
and makes referrals to
     area emergency rooms for more serious problems.<P>
     <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
     <B><A NAME=CareerServices ></A><H2>Career Services
</H2></B><P>
     <P>
          The Career Center coordinates campus visits for
hundreds of
     representatives from business, industry and government who
are interviewing
     graduate students for permanent employment and summer
internships.
     Recruiters are scheduled from September through April.<P>
     <P>
          Clemson University has one of the most sophisticated
placement
     systems in the country, allowing students to research
employers and sign up for
     interviews from any on-campus computer terminal connected to
the mainframe.
     <P>
     <P>
          Graduate students are encouraged to attend seminars on
writing
     resumes, interviewing and job-searching techniques.
Individual career
     counseling is available as well as a computer-assisted
career information
     system. Students are encouraged to register with the
Placement Office one year
     before their expected graduation date. <P>
     <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
     <B><A NAME=GraduateStudentGovernment></A><H2>Graduate
Student
     Government</H2></B><P>
     <P>
          The Graduate Student Government (GSG) provides a voice
for all
     graduate students by investigating problems or issues that
concern graduate
     students and by making recommendations to the proper
authorities.<P>
     <P>
          The GSA elects representatives to various University
councils which
     may elicit graduate student opinions. It also seeks to
support and promote an
     academic and cultural atmosphere in the University community
and to establish
     better interdepartmental communications among graduate
students.<P>
     <P>
          The GSA is composed of a Steering Committee, with
elected officers
     including at least one graduate student from each department
on campus.<P>
     <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
      <P>
     <B><A NAME=InternationalProgramsand >
     </A><H2>International Programs and Services</H2></B><P>
      <P>
          This information is written primarily for students from
the United States.
     Information concerning international students may be
obtained from the Office
     of International Programs and Services, E-208 Martin Hall,
Clemson, SC 29634 or
     call (864) 656-2357 or email <A
HREF="mailto:blouis@clemson.clemson.edu>blouis@clemson.clemson.ed
u</A>.
     <P>
     <P></dl>
<A HREF="http://www.grad.clemson.edu/page1.htm"><IMG
SRC=/images/back.gif></A>
