<html><head><title> Plant Physiology
</title></head>
<body><h1>Plant Physiology</h1>
N. Dwight Camper, Program Coordinator, Department of Plant Pathology and  Physiology
<P>
<table>
<th>Major<th>Degree<tr>
<td>Plant Physiology<td>Ph.D.<tr>
</table>
The graduate program in plant physiology is interdisciplinary. Students may select courses and a major area of 
research from the departments of Agronomy, Biological Sciences, Forest Resources, Horticulture, and Plant 
Pathology and Physiology. Dissertation projects are available in the Food Science Department.
<P>
<I>
The following courses offered by various departments represent possible electives for the student in plant 
physiology. Descriptions for all 800-level courses are under the respective departmental headings.</i>
